<p>From the above Table we perceive that the fish, of which the greatest quantity is eaten by the poor, is herrings; of this, compared with plaice there is upwards of <num value="30">thirty</num> times the number consumed. After plaice rank mackerel, and of these the consumption is about <num value="1">one</num>-half less in number than plaice, while the number of soles vended in the streets, is again half of that of mackerel. Then come whiting, which are about <num value="2">two</num>-thirds the number of the soles, while the consumption to the poor of haddock, cod, eels, and salmon, is comparatively insignificant. Of sprats, which are estimated by weight, only <num value="1">one</num>-<num value="5">fifth</num> of the number of pounds are consumed compared with the weight of mackerel. The pounds&rsquo; weight of herrings sold in the streets, in the course of a year, is upwards of <num value="7">seven</num> times that of plaice, and <num value="14">fourteen</num> times that of mackerel. Altogether more than <measure value="260000000l." type=currency><num value="260000000">260,000,000</num> pounds</measure>, or <num value="116000">116,000</num> tons weight of wet fish are yearly purchased in the streets of London, for the consumption of the humbler classes. Of this aggregate amount, no less than <num value="5">five</num>-sixths consists of herrings; which, indeed, constitute the great slop diet of the metropolis. 
<milestone unit=col>

<div2 type="chapter" n="7" id="c.7"><head>Of Sprat-Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>Sprats&mdash;<num value="1">one</num> of the cheapest and most grateful luxuries of the poor&mdash;are generally introduced about the <datestruct VALUE="-11-9"><day reg="9">9th</day> of <month reg="11">November</month></datestruct>. Indeed &ldquo;Lord Mayor&lsquo;s day&rdquo; is sometimes called &ldquo;sprat day.&rdquo; They continue in about <num value="10">ten</num> weeks. They are sold at Billingsgate by the &ldquo;toss,&rdquo; or &ldquo;chuck,&rdquo; which is about half a bushel, and weighs from <num value="40">40</num>lbs. to <num value="50">50</num>lbs. The price varies from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
Sprats are, this season, pronounced remarkably fine. &ldquo;Look at my lot sir,&rdquo; said a street-seller to me; &ldquo;they&lsquo;re a heap of new silver,&rdquo; and the bright shiny appearance of the glittering little fish made the comparison not inappropriate. In very few, if in any, instances does a costermonger confine himself to the sale of sprats, unless his means limit him to that <num value="1">one</num> branch of the business. A more prosperous street-fishmonger will sometimes detach the sprats from his stall, and his wife, or <num value="1">one</num> of his children will take charge of them. Only a few sprat-sellers are itinerant, the fish being usually sold by stationary street-sellers at &ldquo;pitches.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> who worked his sprats through the streets, or sold them from a stall as he thought best, gave me the following account. He was dressed in a newish fustian-jacket, buttoned close up his chest, but showing a portion of a clean cotton shirt at the neck, with a bright-coloured coarse handkerchief round it; the rest of his dress was covered by a white apron. His hair, as far as I could see it under his cloth cap, was carefully brushed, and (it appeared) as carefully oiled. At the <num value="1">first</num> glance I set him down as having been a gentleman&lsquo;s servant. He had a somewhat deferential, though far from cringing manner with him, and seemed to be about <num value="25">twenty-five</num> or <num value="26">twenty-six</num>&mdash;he thought he was older, he said, but did not know his age exactly. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Ah! sir,&rdquo; he began, in a tone according with his look, &ldquo;sprats <hi rend=italics>is</hi> a blessing to the poor. Fresh herrings is a blessing too, and sprats is young herrings, and is a blessing in &lsquo;portion&rdquo; [for so he pronounced what seemed to be a favourite word with him &ldquo;proportion&rdquo;]. &ldquo;It&lsquo;s only <num value="4">four</num> years&mdash;yes, <num value="4">four</num>, I&lsquo;m sure of that&mdash; since I walked the streets starving, in the depth of winter, and looked at the sprats, and said, I wish I could fill my belly off you. Sir, I hope it was no great sin, but I could hardly keep my hands from stealing some and eating them raw. If they make me sick, thought I, the police &lsquo;ll take care of me, and that&lsquo;ll be something. While these thoughts was a passing through my mind, I met a man who was a gentleman&lsquo;s coachman; I knew him a little formerly, and so I stopped him and told him who I was, and that I hadn&lsquo;t had a meal for <num value="2">two</num> days. &lsquo;Well, by G&mdash;,&rsquo; said the coachman, &lsquo;you look like it, why I shouldn&lsquo;t have known you. Here&lsquo;s a shilling.&rsquo; And then he went on a little way, and then stopped, and turned back and thrust <num value="3.50">3 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
more into my hand, and bolted off. I&lsquo;ve never seen him since. But I&lsquo;m grateful to him in the <pb id="p.70" n="70"> 
<milestone unit=col>
same &lsquo;portion (proportion) as if I had. After I&lsquo;d had a penn&lsquo;orth of bread and a penn&lsquo;orth of cheese, and half-a-pint of beer, I felt a new man, and I went to the party as I&lsquo;d longed to steal the sprats from, and told him what I&lsquo;d thought of. I can&lsquo;t say what made me tell him, but it turned out for good. I don&lsquo;t know much about religion, though I can read a little, but may be that had something to do with it.&rdquo; The rest of the man&lsquo;s narrative was&mdash;briefly told &mdash; as follows. He was the only child of a gentleman&lsquo;s coachman His father had deserted his mother and him, and gone abroad, he believed, with some family. His mother, however, took care of him until her death, which happened &ldquo;when he was a little turned <num value="13">thirteen</num>, he had heard, but could not remember the year.&rdquo; After that he was &ldquo;a helper and a jobber in different stables,&rdquo; and &ldquo;anybody&lsquo;s boy,&rdquo; for a few years, until he got a footman&lsquo;s, or rather footboy&lsquo;s place, which he kept above a year. After that he was in service, in and out of different situations, until the time he specified, when he had been out of place for nearly <num value="5">five</num> weeks, and was starving. His master had got in difficulties, and had gone abroad; so he was left without a character. &ldquo;Well, sir,&rdquo; he continued, &ldquo;the man as I wanted to steal the sprats from, says to me, says he, &lsquo;Poor fellow; I know what a hempty belly is myself&mdash;come and have a pint.&rsquo; And over that there pint, he told me, if I could rise <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> there might be a chance for me in the streets, and he&lsquo;d show me how to do. He died not very long after that, poor man. Well, after a little bit, I managed to borrow <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> of Mr. &mdash;&mdash; (I thought of him all of a sudden). He was butler in a family that I had lived in, and had a charitable character, though he was reckoned very proud. But I plucked up a spirit, and told him how I was off, and he said, &lsquo;Well, I&lsquo;ll try you,&rsquo; and he lent me <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, which I paid him back, little by little, in <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="8">eight</num> weeks; and so I started in the costermonger line, with the advice of my friend, and I&lsquo;ve made from <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, sometimes more, a week, at it ever since. The police don&lsquo;t trouble me much. They is civil to me in &lsquo;portion (proportion) as I am civil to them. I never mixed with the costers but when I&lsquo;ve met them at market. I stay at a lodginghouse, but it&lsquo;s very decent and clean, and I have a bed to myself, at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week, for I&lsquo;m a regular man. I&lsquo;m on sprats now, you see, sir, and you&lsquo;d wonder, sometimes, to see how keen people looks to them when they&lsquo;re new. They&lsquo;re a blessing to the poor, in &lsquo;portion (proportion) of course. Not <num value="20">twenty</num> minutes before you spoke to me, there was <num value="2">two</num> poor women came up&mdash;they was sickly-looking, but I don&lsquo;t know what they was &mdash;perhaps shirt-makers&mdash;and they says to me, says they, &lsquo;Show us what a penny plateful is.&rsquo; &lsquo;Sart&lsquo;nly, ladies,&rsquo; says I. Then they whispered together, and at last <num value="1">one</num> says, says she, &lsquo;We&lsquo;ll have <num value="2">two</num> platefuls.&rsquo; I told you they was a blessing to the poor, sir&mdash;&lsquo;specially to such as them, as lives all the year round on bread and 
<milestone unit=col>
tea. But it&lsquo;s not only the poor as buys; others in &lsquo;portion (proportion). When they&lsquo;re new they&lsquo;re a treat to everybody. I&lsquo;ve sold them to poor working-men, who&lsquo;ve said, &lsquo;I&lsquo;ll take a treat home to the old &lsquo;oman and the kids; they dotes on sprats.&rsquo; Gentlemen&lsquo;s servants is very fond of them, and mechanics comes down &mdash; such as shoemakers in their leather aprons, and sings out, &lsquo;Here, old sprats, give us <num value="2">two</num> penn&lsquo;orth.&rsquo; They&lsquo;re <hi rend=italics>such</hi> a relish. I sell more to men than to women, perhaps, but there&lsquo;s little difference. They&lsquo;re best stewed, sir, I think &mdash; if you&lsquo;re fond of sprats &mdash; with vinegar and a pick of allspice; that&lsquo;s my opinion, and, only yesterday, an old cook said I was right. I makes <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day, and sometimes rather more, on my sprats, and sticks to them as much as I can. I sell about my &lsquo;toss&rsquo; a day, seldom less. Of course I can make as many penn&lsquo;orths of it as I please, but there&lsquo;s no custom without <num value="1">one</num> gives middling penn&lsquo;orths. If a toss costs me <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, I may make <num value="60">sixty</num> penn&lsquo;orths of it sometimes&mdash; sometimes <num value="70">seventy</num> or more &mdash; and sometimes less than <num value="60">sixty</num>. There&lsquo;s many turns over as much as me and more than that. I&lsquo;m thinking that I&lsquo;ll work the country with a lot; they&lsquo;ll keep to a <num value="2">second</num> day, when they&lsquo;re fresh to start, &lsquo;specially if its frosty weather, too, and then they&lsquo;re better than ever &mdash; yes, and a greater treat&mdash;scalding hot from the fire, they&lsquo;re the cheapest and best of all suppers in the winter time. I hardly know which way I&lsquo;ll go. If I can get anythink to do among horses in the country, I&lsquo;ll never come back. I&lsquo;ve no tie to London.</QUOTE>
 
<p>To show how small a sum of money will enable the struggling striving poor to obtain a living, I may here mention that, in the course of my inquiries among the mudlarks, I casually gave a poor shoeless urchin, who was spoken of by <num value="1">one</num> of the City Missionaries as being a welldisposed youth, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> out of the funds that had been entrusted to me to dispense. Trifling as the amount appears, it was the means of keeping his mother, sister, and himself through the winter. It was invested in sprats, and turned over and over again. 
<p>I am informed, by the best authorities, that near upon <datestruct value="1000--"><year reg="1000">1000</year></datestruct> &ldquo;tosses&rdquo; of sprats are sold daily in London streets, while the season lasts. These, sold retail in pennyworths, at very nearly <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the toss, give about <num value="150">150</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> a day, or say <num value="1000">1,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> a week spent on sprats by the poorer classes of the metropolis; so that, calculating the sprat season to last <num value="10">ten</num> weeks, about <num value="10000">10,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>
would be taken by the costermongers during that time from the sale of this fish alone. 
<p>Another return, furnished me by an eminent salesman at Billingsgate, estimates the gross quantity of sprats sold by the London costers in the course of the season at <num value="3">three</num> millions of pounds weight, and this disposed of at the rate of <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> per pound, gives upwards of <num value="12000">12,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> for the sum of money spent upon this <num value="1">one</num> kind of fish. <pb id="p.71" n="71"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<div2 type=section id="c.7.53"><head>Of Shell-Fish Sellers in the Streets.</head>

<p>I had the following account from an experienced man. He lived with his mother, his wife, and <num value="4">four</num> children, in <num value="1">one</num> of the streets near Gray&lsquo;s-inn-lane. The street was inhabited altogether by people of his class, the women looking sharply out when a stranger visited the place. On my <num value="1">first</num> visit to this man&lsquo;s room, his wife, who is near her confinement, was at dinner with her children. The time was <num value="0.25">1/4</num> to <num value="12">12</num>. The meal was tea, and bread with butter very thinly spread over it. On the wife&lsquo;s bread was a small piece of pickled pork, covering about <num value="1">one</num>-<num value="8">eighth</num> of the slice of a quartern loaf cut through. In <num value="1">one</num> corner of the room, which is on the groundfloor, was a scantily-covered bed. A few dingy-looking rags were hanging up to dry in the middle of the room, which was littered with baskets and boxes, mixed up with old furniture, so that it was a difficulty to stir. The room (although the paper, covering the broken panes in the window, was torn and full of holes) was most oppressively close and hot, and there was a fetid smell, difficult to sustain, though it was less noticeable on a subsequent call. I have often had occasion to remark that the poor, especially those who are much subjected to cold in the open air, will sacrifice much for heat. The adjoining room, which had no door, seemed littered like the <num value="1">one</num> where the family were. The walls of the room I was in were discoloured and weather-stained. The only attempt at ornament was over the mantel-shelf, the wall here being papered with red and other gay-coloured papers, that once had been upholsterer&lsquo;s patterns. 
<p>On my <num value="2">second</num> visit, the husband was at dinner with the family, on good boiled beef and potatoes. He was a small-featured man, with a head of very curly and long black hair, and both in mien, manners, and dress, resembled the mechanic far more than the costermonger. He said:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I&lsquo;ve been <num value="20">twenty</num> years and more, perhaps <num value="24">twenty-four</num>, selling shell-fish in the streets. I was a boot-closer when I was young, and have made my <num value="20">20</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and <num value="30">30</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, and sometimes <num value="40">40</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, and then sometimes not <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week; but I had an attack of rheumatic-fever, and lost the use of my hands for my trade. The streets hadn&lsquo;t any great name, as far as I knew, then, but as I couldn&lsquo;t work, it was just a choice between street-selling and starving, so I didn&lsquo;t prefer the last. It was reckoned degrading to go into the streets&mdash;but I couldn&lsquo;t help that. I was astonished at my success when I <num value="1">first</num> began, and got into the business&mdash;that is into the understanding of it&mdash;after a week, or <num value="2">two</num>, or <num value="3">three</num>. Why, I made <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> the <num value="1">first</num> week I knew my trade, properly; yes, I cleared <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>! I made, not long after, <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> a week&mdash;but not often. I was giddy and extravagant. Indeed, I was a fool, and spent my money like a fool I could have brought up a family then like a gentleman&mdash;I 
<milestone unit=col>
send them to school as it is&mdash;but I hadn&lsquo;t a wife and family then, or it might have been better; it&lsquo;s a great check on a man, is a family. I began with shell-fish, and sell it still; very seldom anything else. There&lsquo;s more demand for shells, no doubt, because its far cheaper, but then there&lsquo;s so many more sellers. I don&lsquo;t know why exactly. I suppose it&lsquo;s because poor people go into the streets when they can&lsquo;t live other ways, and some do it because they think it&lsquo;s an idle life; but it ain&lsquo;t. Where I took <num value="35">35</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
in a day at my stall&mdash;and well on to half of it profit&mdash;I now take <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, or perhaps <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, in the day and less profit on that less money. I don&lsquo;t clear <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day now, take the year through. I don&lsquo;t keep accounts, but I&lsquo;m certain enough that I average about <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week the year through, and my wife has to help me to make that. She&lsquo;ll mind the stall, while I take a round sometimes. I sell all kinds of shell-fish, but my great dependence is on winkles. I don&lsquo;t do much in lobsters. Very few speculate in them. The price varies very greatly. What&lsquo;s <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a score <num value="1">one</num> day may be <num value="25">25</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the next. I sometimes get a score for <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, but it&lsquo;s a poor trade, for <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> is the top of the tree, with me, for a price to a seller. I never get more. I sell them to mechanics and tradesmen. I do more in pound crabs. There&lsquo;s a great call for haporths and pennorths of lobster or crab, by children; that&lsquo;s their claws. I bile them all myself, and buy them alive. I can bile <num value="20">twenty</num> in half an hour, and do it over a grate in a back-yard. Lobsters don&lsquo;t fight or struggle much in the hot water, if they&lsquo;re properly packed. It&lsquo;s very few that knows how to bile a lobster as he should be biled. I wish I knew any way of killing lobsters before biling them. I can&lsquo;t kill them without smashing them to bits, and that won&lsquo;t do at all. I kill my crabs before I bile them. I stick them in the throat with a knife and they&lsquo;re dead in an instant. Some sticks them with a skewer, but they kick a good while with the skewer in them. It&lsquo;s a shame to torture anything when it can be helped. If I didn&lsquo;t kill the crabs they&lsquo;d shed every leg in the hot water; they&lsquo;d come out as bare of claws as this plate. I&lsquo;ve known it oft enough, as it is; though I kill them uncommon quick, a crab will be quicker and shed every leg&mdash;throw them off in the moment I kill them, but that doesn&lsquo;t happen once in <num value="50">fifty</num> times. Oysters are capital this season, I mean as to quality, but they&lsquo;re not a good sale. I made <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> a week in oysters, not reckoning anything else, eighteen or <num value="20">twenty</num> years back. It was easy to make money then; like putting down <num value="1">one</num> sovereign and taking <num value="2">two</num> up. I sold oysters then oft enough at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece. Now I sell far finer at <num value="3">three</num> a penny and <num value="5">five</num> for <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> People can&lsquo;t spend money in shell-fish when they haven&lsquo;t got any. They say that fortune knocks once at every man&lsquo;s door. I wish I&lsquo;d opened my door when he knocked at it.</QUOTE>

<p>This man&lsquo;s wife told me afterwards, that last <pb id="p.72" n="72"> 
<milestone unit=col>
winter, after an attack of rheumatism, all their stock-money was exhausted, and her husband sat day by day at home almost out of his mind; for nothing could tempt him to apply to the parish, and &ldquo;he would never have mentioned his sufferings to me,&rdquo; she said; &ldquo;he had too much pride.&rdquo; The loan of a few shillings from a poor costermonger enabled the man to go to market again, or he and his family would now have been in the Union. 
