<div2 type=section id="c.7.54"><head>Of Shrimp Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>Shrimp selling, as I have stated, is <num value="1">one</num> of the trades to which the street-dealer often con fines himself throughout the year. The sale is about equally divided between the <num value="2">two</num> sexes, but the men do the most business, walking some of them <num value="15">fifteen</num> to <num value="20">twenty</num> miles a day in a &ldquo;round&rdquo; of &ldquo;<num value="10">ten</num> miles there and <num value="10">ten</num> back.&rdquo; 
<p>The shrimps vended in the streets are the Yarmouth prawn shrimps, sold at Billingsgate at from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a gallon, while the best shrimps (chiefly from Lee, in Essex,) vary in price from <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a gallon; <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> being a common price. The shrimps are usually mixed by the street-dealers, and they are cried, from stalls or on rounds, &ldquo;a penny half-pint, fine fresh s&lsquo;rimps.&rdquo; (I heard them called nothing but &ldquo;s&lsquo;rimps&rdquo; by the street-dealers.) The half-pint, however, is in reality but half that quantity. &ldquo;It&lsquo;s the same measure as it was <num value="30">thirty</num> years back,&rdquo; I was told, in a tone as if its antiquity removed all imputation of unfair dealing. Some young men &ldquo;do well on s&lsquo;rimps,&rdquo; sometimes taking <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> in an hour on a Saturday evening, &ldquo;when people get their money, and wants a relish.&rdquo; The females in the shrimp line are the wives, widows, or daughters of costermongers. They are computed to average <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day profit in fine, and from <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
in bad weather; and, in snowy, or very severe weather, sometimes nothing at all. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> shrimp--seller, a middle--aged woman, wrapped up in a hybrid sort of cloak, that was half a man&lsquo;s and half a woman&lsquo;s garment, gave me the following account. There was little vulgarity in either her language or manner. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I was in the s&lsquo;rimp trade since I was a girl. I don&lsquo;t know how long. I don&lsquo;t know how old I am. I never knew; but I&lsquo;ve <num value="2">two</num> children, <num value="1">one</num>&lsquo;s <num value="6">six</num> and t&lsquo;other&lsquo;s near <num value="8">eight</num>, both girls; I&lsquo;ve kept count of that as well as I can. My 
<milestone unit=col>
husband sells fish in the street; so did father, but he&lsquo;s dead. We buried him without the help of the parish, as many gets&mdash;that&lsquo;s something to say. I&lsquo;ve known the trade every way. It never was any good in public-houses. They want such great ha&lsquo;p&lsquo;orths there. They&lsquo;ll put up with what isn&lsquo;t very fresh, to be sure, sometimes; and good enough for them too, I say, as spoils their taste with drink.&rdquo; [This was said very bitterly.] &ldquo;If it wasn&lsquo;t for my husband&lsquo;s drinking for a day together now and then we&lsquo;d do better. He&lsquo;s neither to have nor to hold when he&lsquo;s the worse for liquor; and it&lsquo;s the worse with him, for he&lsquo;s a quiet man when he&lsquo;s his own man. Perhaps I make <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day, perhaps <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or more. Sometimes my husband takes my stand, and I go a round. Sometimes, if he gets through his fish, he goes my round. I give good measure, and my pint&lsquo;s the regular s&lsquo;rimp pint.&rdquo; [It was the <hi rend=italics>half</hi>-pint I have described.] &ldquo;The trade&lsquo;s not so good as it was. People hasn&lsquo;t the money, they tells me so. It&lsquo;s bread before s&lsquo;rimps, says they. I&lsquo;ve heard them say it very cross, if I&lsquo;ve wanted hard to sell. Some days I can sell nothing. My children stays with my sister, when me and my old man&lsquo;s out. They don&lsquo;t go to school, but Jane (the sister) learns them to sew. She makes drawers for the slopsellers, but has very little work, and gets very little for the little she does; she would learn them to read if she knew how. She&lsquo;s married to a pavior, that&lsquo;s away all day. It&lsquo;s a hard life mine, sir. The winter&lsquo;s a coming, and I&lsquo;m now sometimes numbed with sitting at my stall in the cold. My feet feels like lumps of ice in the winter; and they&lsquo;re beginning now, as if they weren&lsquo;t my own. Standing&lsquo;s far harder work than going a round. I sell the best s&lsquo;rimps. My customers is judges. If I&lsquo;ve any s&lsquo;rimps over on a night, as I often have <num value="1">one</num> or <num value="2">two</num> nights a week, I sells them for half-price to an Irishwoman, and she takes them to the beer-shops, and the coffee-shops. She washes them. to look fresh. I don&lsquo;t mind telling that, because people should buy of regular people. It&lsquo;s very few people know how to pick a s&lsquo;rimp properly. You should take it by the head and the tail and jam them up, and then the shell separates, and the s&lsquo;rimp comes out beautifully. That&lsquo;s the proper way.</QUOTE>

<p>Sometimes the sale on the rounds may be the same as that at the stalls, or <num value="10">10</num> or <num value="20">20</num> per cent. more or less, according to the weather, as shrimps can be sold by the itinerant dealers better than by the stall-keepers in wet weather, when people prefer buying at their doors. But in hot weather the stall trade is the best, &ldquo;for people often fancy that the s&lsquo;rimps is sent out to sell &lsquo;cause they&lsquo;ll not keep no longer. It&lsquo;s only among customers as knows you, you can do any good on a round then.&rdquo; 
<p>The costermongers sell annually, it appears, about <num value="770000">770,000</num> pints of shrimps. At <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a pint (a very low calculation) the street sale of shrimps amount to upwards of <num value="6400">6,400</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>
yearly. <pb id="p.73" n="73" img="2001.p1.0027"> 
