<div2 type=section id="c.7.55"><head>Of Oyster Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>THE trade in oysters is unquestionably <num value="1">one</num> of the oldest with which the London&mdash;or rather the English&mdash;markets are connected; for oysters from Britain were a luxury in ancient Rome. 
<p>Oysters are now sold out of the smacks at Billingsgate, and a few at Hungerford. The more expensive kind such as the real Milton, are never bought by the costermongers, but they buy oysters of a &ldquo;good middling quality.&rdquo; At the commencement of the season these oysters are <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a &ldquo;bushel,&rdquo; but the measure contains from a bushel and a half to <num value="2">two</num> bushels, as it is more or less heaped up. The general price, however, is <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, but they <hi rend=italics>have</hi> been <num value="16">16</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
and <num value="18">18</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> The &ldquo;big trade&rdquo; was unknown until <datestruct value="1848--"><year reg="1848">1848</year></datestruct>, when the very large shelly oysters, the fish inside being very small, were introduced from the Sussex coast. They were sold in Thamesstreet and by the Borough-market. Their sale was at <num value="1">first</num> enormous. The costermongers distinguished them by the name of &ldquo;scuttle-mouths.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> coster informant told me that on the Saturdays he not unfrequently, with the help of a boy and a girl, cleared <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> by selling these oysters in the streets, disposing of <num value="4">four</num> bags. He thus sold, reckoning <num value="21">twenty-one</num> dozen to the bag, <num value="2016">2,016</num> oysters; and as the price was <num value="2">two</num> for a penny, he took just <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> by the sale of oysters in the streets in <num value="1">one</num> night. With the scuttlemouths the costermonger takes no trouble: he throws them into a yard, and dashes a few pails of water over them, and then places them on his barrow, or conveys them to his stall. Some of the better class of costermongers, however, lay down their oysters carefully, giving them oatmeal &ldquo;to fatten on.&rdquo; 
<p>In April last, some of the street-sellers of this article established, for the <num value="1">first</num> time, &ldquo;oysterrounds.&rdquo; These were carried on by costermongers whose business was over at <num value="12">twelve</num> in the day, or a little later; they bought a bushel of scuttle-mouths (never the others), and, in the afternoon, went a round with them to poor neighbourhoods, until about <num value="6">six</num>, when they took a stand in some frequented street. Going these oyster-rounds is hard work, I am told, and a boy is generally taken to assist. Monday afternoon is the best time for this trade, when <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> is sometimes taken, and <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> profit made. On other evenings only from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
is taken &mdash; very rarely the larger sum&mdash;as the later the day in the week the smaller is the receipt, owing to the wages of the working classes getting gradually exhausted. 
<p>The women who sell oysters in the street, and whose dealings are limited, buy either of the costermongers or at the coal-sheds. But nearly all the men buy at Billingsgate, where as small a quantity as a peck can be had. 
<p>An old woman, who had &ldquo;seen better days,&rdquo; but had been reduced to keep an oyster-stall, gave me the following account of her customers. She showed much shrewdness in her conversation, but having known better days, she declined 
<milestone unit=col>
to enter upon any conversation concerning her former life:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>As to my customers, sir,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;why, indeed, they&lsquo;re all sorts. It&lsquo;s not a very few times that gentlemen (I call them so because they&lsquo;re mostly so civil) will stop&mdash;just as it&lsquo;s getting darkish, perhaps,&mdash;and look about them, and then come to me and say very quick: &lsquo;<num value="2">Two</num> penn&lsquo;orth for a whet.&rsquo; Ah! some of &lsquo;em will look, may be, like poor parsons down upon their luck, and swallow their oysters as if they was taking poison in a hurry. They&lsquo;ll not touch the bread or butter once in <num value="20">twenty</num> times, but they&lsquo;ll be free with the pepper and vinegar, or, mayhap, they&lsquo;ll say quick and short, &lsquo;A crust off that.&rsquo; I many a time think <hi rend=italics>that</hi> <num value="2">two</num> penn&lsquo;orth is a poor gentleman&lsquo;s dinner. It&lsquo;s the same often&mdash;but only half as often, or not half &mdash;with a poor lady, with a veil that once was black, over a bonnet to match, and shivering through her shawl. She&lsquo;ll have the same. About <num value="2">two</num> penn&lsquo;orth is the mark still; it&lsquo;s mostly <num value="2">two</num> penn&lsquo;orth. My son says, it&lsquo;s because that&lsquo;s the price of a glass of gin, and some persons buy oysters instead&mdash;but that&lsquo;s only his joke, sir. It&lsquo;s not the vulgar poor that&lsquo;s our chief customers. There&lsquo;s many of them won&lsquo;t touch oysters, and I&lsquo;ve heard some of them say: &lsquo;The sight on &lsquo;em makes me sick; it&lsquo;s like eating snails.&rsquo; The poor girls that walk the streets often buy; some are brazen and vulgar, and often the finest dressed are the vulgarest; at least, I think so; and of those that come to oyster stalls, I&lsquo;m sure it&lsquo;s the case. Some are shy to such as me, who may, perhaps, call their own mothers to their minds, though it aint many of them that is so. <num value="1">One</num> of them always says that she must keep at least a penny for gin after her oysters. <num value="1">One</num> young woman ran away from my stall once after swallowing <num value="1">one</num> oyster out of <num value="6">six</num> that she&lsquo;d paid for. I don&lsquo;t know why. Ah! there&lsquo;s many things a person like me sees that <num value="1">one</num> may say, &lsquo;I don&lsquo;t know why&rsquo; to; that there is. My heartiest customers, that I serve with the most pleasure, are working people, on a Saturday night. <num value="1">One</num> couple&mdash;I think the wife always goes to meet her husband on a Saturday night&mdash; has <num value="2">two</num>, or <num value="3">three</num>, or <num value="4">four</num> penn&lsquo;orth, as happens, and it&lsquo;s pleasant to hear them say, &lsquo;Won&lsquo;t you have another, John?&rsquo; or, &lsquo;Do have <num value="1">one</num> or <num value="2">two</num> more, Mary Anne.&rsquo; I&lsquo;ve served them that way <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> years. They&lsquo;ve no children, I&lsquo;m pretty sure, for if I say, &lsquo;Take a few home to the little ones,&rsquo; the wife tosses her head, and says, half vexed and half laughing, &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>Such</hi> nonsense.&rsquo; I send out a good many oysters, opened, for people&lsquo;s suppers, and sometimes for supper parties&mdash;at least, I suppose so, for there&lsquo;s <num value="5">five</num> or <num value="6">six</num> dozen often ordered. The maid-servants come for them then, and I give them <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> for themselves, and say, jokingly-like, &lsquo;It&lsquo;s no use offering you any, perhaps, because you&lsquo;ll have plenty that&lsquo;s left.&rsquo; They&lsquo;ve mostly <num value="1">one</num> answer: &lsquo;Don&lsquo;t we wish we may get &lsquo;em?&rsquo; The <hi rend=italics>very</hi>
poor never buy of me, as I told you. A penny <pb id="p.76" n="76"> 
<milestone unit=col>
buys a loaf, you see, or a ha&lsquo;porth of bread and a ha&lsquo;porth of cheese, or a half-pint of beer, with a farthing out. My customers are mostly working people and tradespeople. Ah! sir, I wish the parson of the parish, or any parson, sat with me a fortnight; he&lsquo;d see what life is then. &lsquo;It&lsquo;s different,&rsquo; a learned man used to say to me&mdash;that&lsquo;s long ago&mdash;&lsquo;from what&lsquo;s noticed from the pew or the pulpit.&rsquo; I&lsquo;ve missed the gentleman as used to say that, now many years&mdash;I don&lsquo;t know how many. I never knew his name. He was drunk now and then, and used to tell me he was an author. I felt for him. A dozen oysters wasn&lsquo;t much for him. We see a deal of the world, sir&mdash;yes, a deal. Some, mostly working people, take quantities of pepper with their oysters in cold weather, and say it&lsquo;s to warm them, and no doubt it does; but frosty weather is very bad oyster weather. The oysters gape and die, and then they are not so much as manure. They are very fine this year. I clear <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day, I think, during the season&mdash;at least <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, taking the fine with the wet days, and the week days with the Sundays, though I&lsquo;m not out then; but, you see, I&lsquo;m known about here.</QUOTE>
 
<p>The number of oysters sold by the costermongers amounts to <num value="124000000">124,000,000</num> a year. These, at <num value="4">four</num> a penny, would realise the large sum of <num value="129650">129,650</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> We may therefore safely assume that <num value="125000">125,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is spent yearly in oysters in the streets of London. 
<div2 type=section id="c.7.56"><head>Of Periwinkle Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>THERE are some street people who, nearly all the year through, sell nothing but periwinkles, and go regular rounds, where they are well known. The &ldquo;wink&rdquo; men, as these periwinkle sellers are called, generally live in the lowest parts, and many in lodging-houses. They are forced to live in low localities, they say, because of the smell of the fish, which is objected to. The city district is ordinarily the best for winklesellers, for there are not so many cheap shops there as in other parts. The summer is the best season, and the sellers then make, upon the average, <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week clear profit; in the winter, they get upon the average, <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week clear, by selling mussels and whelks&mdash;for, as winkles last only from March till October, they are then obliged to do what they can in the whelk and mussel way. &ldquo;I buy my winks,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num>, &ldquo;at Billingsgate, at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the wash. A wash is about a bushel. There&lsquo;s some at <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, and some sometimes as low as <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the wash, but they wouldn&lsquo;t do for me, as I serve very respectable people. If we choose we can boil our winkles at Billingsgate by paying <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a week for boiling, and <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for salt, to salt them after they are boiled. Tradesmen&lsquo;s families buy them for a relish to their tea. It&lsquo;s reckoned a nice present from a young man to his sweetheart, is winks. Servant girls are pretty good customers, and want them cheaper when they say it&lsquo;s for themselves; but I have only <num value="1">one</num> price.&rdquo; 
<p><num value="1">One</num> man told me he could make as much as <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week&mdash;sometimes more and sometimes less. 
<milestone unit=col>
He made no speeches, but sung&mdash;&ldquo;Winkettywinketty-wink-wink-wink &mdash; wink-wink &mdash; wicketty-wicketty-wink&mdash;fine fresh winketty-winks wink wink.&rdquo; He was often so sore in the stomach and hoarse with hallooing that he could hardly speak. He had no child, only himself and wife to keep out of his earnings. His room was <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week rent. He managed to get a bit of meat every day, he said, &ldquo;somehow or &lsquo;nother.&rdquo; 
<p>Another, more communicative and far more intelligent man, said to me concerning the character of his customers: &ldquo;They&lsquo;re people I think that like to daddle&rdquo; (dawdle, I presume) &ldquo;over their teas or such like; or when a young woman&lsquo;s young man takes tea with her mother and her, then they&lsquo;ve winks; and then there&lsquo;s joking, and helping to pick winks, between Thomas and Betsy, while the mother&lsquo;s busy with her tea, or is wiping her spees, &lsquo;cause she 
<hi rend=italics>can&lsquo;t</hi> see. Why, sir, I&lsquo;ve known it! I was a Thomas that way myself when I was a tradesman. I was a patten-maker once, but pattens is no go now, and hasn&lsquo;t been for <num value="15">fifteen</num> year or more. Old people, I think, that lives by themselves, and has perhaps an annuity or the like of that, and nothing to do pertickler, loves winks, for they likes a pleasant way of making time long over a meal. They&lsquo;re the people as reads a newspaper, when it&lsquo;s a week old, all through. The other buyers, I think, are tradespeople or working-people what wants a relish. But winks is a bad trade now, and so is many that depends on relishes.&rdquo; 
<p><num value="1">One</num> man who &ldquo;works&rdquo; the New Cut, has the &ldquo;best wink business of all.&rdquo; He sells only a little dry fish with his winks, never wet fish, and has &ldquo;got his name up,&rdquo; for the superiority of that shell-fish &mdash; a superiority which he is careful to ensure. He pays <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
a week for a stand by a grocer&lsquo;s window. On an ordinary afternoon he sells from <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
worth of periwinkles. On a Monday afternoon he often takes <num value="20">20</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; and on the Sunday afternoon <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> and <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> He has <num value="2">two</num> coster lads to help him, and sometimes on a Sunday from <num value="20">twenty</num> to <num value="30">thirty</num> customers about him. He wraps each parcel sold in a neat brown paper bag, which, I am assured, is of itself, an inducement to buy of him. The &ldquo;unfortunate&rdquo; women who live in the streets contiguous to the Waterloo, Blackfriars, and Borough-roads, are among his best customers, on Sundays especially. He is rather a public character, getting up dances and the like. &ldquo;<hi rend=italics>He</hi> aint bothered&mdash; not he&mdash;with ha&lsquo;p&lsquo;orths or penn&lsquo;orths of a Sunday,&rdquo; said a person who had assisted him. &ldquo;It&lsquo;s the top of the tree with his customers; <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> or <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> at a go.&rdquo; The receipts are <num value="1">one</num>-half profit. I heard from several that he was &ldquo;the best man for winks a-going.&rdquo; 
<p>The quantity of periwinkles disposed of by the London street-sellers is <num value="3600000">3,600,000</num> pints, which, at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> per pint, gives the large sum of <num value="15000">15,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>
expended annually in this street luxury. It should be remembered, that a very large con- <pb id="p.77" n="77"> 
<milestone unit=col>
sumption of periwinkles takes place in publichouses and suburban tea-gardens. 
<div2 type=section id="c.7.57"><head>Of &ldquo;Dry&rdquo; Fish Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>THE dealing in &ldquo;dry&rdquo; or salt fish is never carried on as a totally distinct trade in the streets, but some make it a principal part of their business; and many wet fish-dealers whose &ldquo;wet fish&rdquo; is disposed of by noon, sell dry fish in the afternoon. The dry fish, proper, consists of dried mackerel, salt cod&mdash;dried or barrelled&mdash;smoked or dried haddocks (often called &ldquo;finnie haddies&rdquo;), dried or pickled salmon (but salmon is only salted or pickled for the streets when it can be sold cheap), and salt herrings. 
<p>A keen-looking, tidily-dressed man, who was at <num value="1">one</num> time a dry fish-seller principally, gave me the following account. For the last <num value="2">two</num> months he has confined himself to another branch of the business, and seemed to feel a sort of pleasure in telling of the &ldquo;dodges&rdquo; he once resorted to: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>There&lsquo;s Scotch haddies that never knew anything about Scotland,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;for I&lsquo;ve made lots of them myself by Tower-street, just a jump or <num value="2">two</num> from the Lambeth station-house. I used to make them on Sundays. I was a wet fish-seller then, and when I couldn&lsquo;t get through my haddocks or my whitings of a Saturday night, I wasn&lsquo;t a-going to give them away to folks that wouldn&lsquo;t take the trouble to lift me out of a gutter if I fell there, so I presarved them. I&lsquo;ve made haddies of whitings, and good ones too, and Joe made them of codlings besides. I had a bit of a back-yard to <num value="2">two</num> rooms, <num value="1">one</num> over the other, that I had then, and on a Sunday I set some wet wood a fire, and put it under a great tub. My children used to gut and wash the fish, and I hung them on hooks all round the sides of the tub, and made a bit of a chimney in a corner of the top of the tub, and that way I gave them a jolly good smoking. My wife had a dry fish-stall and sold them, and used to sing out &lsquo;Real Scotch haddies,&rsquo; and tell people how they was from Aberdeen; I&lsquo;ve often been fit to laugh, she did it so clever. I had a way of giving them a yellow colour like the real Scotch, but that&lsquo;s a secret. After they was well smoked they was hung up to dry all round the rooms we lived in, and we often had stunning fires that answered as well to boil crabs and lobsters when they was cheap enough for the streets. I&lsquo;ve boiled a mate&lsquo;s crabs and lobsters for <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; it was <num value="2">two</num> boilings and more, and <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> was reckoned the price of half a quarter of a <num value="100">hundred</num> of coals and the use of the pan. There&lsquo;s more ways than <num value="1">one</num> of making <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, if a man has eyes in his head and keeps them open. Haddocks that wouldn&lsquo;t fetch <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece, nor any money at all of a Saturday night, I&lsquo;ve sold&mdash;at least she has&rdquo; (indicating his wife by a motion of his thumb)&mdash; &ldquo;at <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> I&lsquo;ve bought fish of costers that was over on a Saturday night, to make Scotch haddies of them. I&lsquo;ve tried experience&rdquo; (experiments) &ldquo;too. Ivy, burnt 
<milestone unit=col>
under them, gave them, I thought, a nice sort of flavour, rather peppery, for I used always to taste them; but I hate living on fish. Ivy with brown berries on it, as it has about this time o&rsquo; year, I liked best. Holly wasn&lsquo;t no good. A black-currant bush was, but it&lsquo;s too dear; and indeed it couldn&lsquo;t be had. I mostly spread wetted fire-wood, as green as could be got, or damp sticks of any kind, over shavings, and kept feeding the fire. Sometimes I burnt sawdust. Somehow, the dry fish trade fell off. People does get so prying and so knowing, there&lsquo;s no doing nothing now for no time, so I dropped the dry fish trade. There&lsquo;s few up to smoking them proper; they smoke &lsquo;em black, as if they was hung up in a chimbley.</QUOTE>

<p>Another costermonger gave me the following account: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I&lsquo;ve salted herrings, but the commonest way of salting is by the Jews about Whitechapel. They make real Yarmouth bloaters and all sorts of fish. When I salted herrings, I bought them out of the boats at Billingsgate by the <num value="100">hundred</num>, which is <num value="120">120</num> fish. We give them a bit of a clean &mdash;hardly anything&mdash;then chuck them into a tub of salt, and keep scattering salt over them, and let them lie a few minutes, or sometimes half an hour, and then hang them up to dry. They eat well enough, if they&lsquo;re eaten in time, for they won&lsquo;t keep. I&lsquo;ve known <num value="3">three</num> day&lsquo;s old herrings salted, just because there was no sale for them. <num value="1">One</num> Jew sends out <num value="6">six</num> boys crying &lsquo;real Yarmouth bloaters.&rsquo; People buy them in preference, they look so nice and clean and fresh-coloured. It&lsquo;s quite a new trade among the Jews. They didn&lsquo;t do much that way until <num value="2">two</num> years back. I sometimes wish I was a Jew, because they help <num value="1">one</num> another, and start <num value="1">one</num> another with money, and so they thrive where Christians are ruined. I smoked mackerel, too, by thousands; that&lsquo;s a new trade, and is done the same way as haddocks. Mackerel that won&lsquo;t bring <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece fresh, bring <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
smoked; they are very nice indeed. I make about <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="11">11</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week by dry fish in the winter months, and about as much by wet,&mdash; but I have a tidy connection. Perhaps I make <num value="17">17</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="18">18</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week all the year round.</QUOTE>

