<div2 type=section id="c.11.90"><head>Statement of <num value="2">Two</num> Poultry Hawkers.</head>

<p><num value="2">TWO</num> brothers, both good-looking and wellspoken young men&mdash;<num value="1">one</num> I might characterise as handsome&mdash;gave me the following account. I found them unwilling to speak of their youth, and did not press them. I was afterwards informed that their parents died within the same month, and that the family was taken into the workhouse; but the <num value="2">two</num> boys left it in a little time, and before they could benefit by any schooling. Neither of them could read or write. They left, I believe, with some little sum in hand, to &ldquo;start theirselves.&rdquo; An intelligent costermonger, who was with me when I saw the <num value="2">two</num> brothers, told me that &ldquo;a costermonger would rather be thought to have come out of prison than out of a workhouse,&rdquo; for his &ldquo;mates&rdquo; would say, if they heard he had been locked up, &ldquo;O, he&lsquo;s only been quodded for pitching into a crusher.&rdquo; The <num value="2">two</num> brothers wore clean smock country frocks over their dress, and made a liberal display of their clean, <pb id="p.126" n="126"> 
<milestone unit=col>
but coarse, shirts. It was on a Monday that I saw them. What <num value="1">one</num> brother said, the other confirmed: so I use the plural &ldquo;we.&rdquo; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>We sell poultry and game, but stick most to poultry, which suits our connection best. We buy at Leadenhall. We&lsquo;re never cheated in the things we buy; indeed, perhaps, we could&lsquo;nt be. A salesman will say&mdash;Mr. H&mdash;&mdash; will&mdash; &lsquo;Buy, if you like, I can&lsquo;t recommend them. Use your own judgment. They&lsquo;re cheap.&rsquo; He has only <num value="1">one</num> price, and that&lsquo;s often a low <num value="1">one</num>. We give from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for good chickens, and from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> mostly for geese and turkeys. Pigeons is <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a dozen. We aim at <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> profit on chickens; and <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, if we can get it, or <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> if we can do no better, on geese and turkeys. Ducks are the same as chickens. All the year through, we may make <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week a piece. We work together, <num value="1">one</num> on <num value="1">one</num> side of the street and the other on the other. It answers best that way. People find we can&lsquo;t undersell <num value="1">one</num> another. We buy the poultry, whenever we can, undressed, and dress them ourselves; pull the feathers off and make them ready for cooking. We sell cheaper than the shops, or we couldn&lsquo;t sell at all. But you must be known, to do any trade, or people will think your poultry&lsquo;s bad. We work game as well, but mostly poultry. We&lsquo;ve been on hares to-day, mostly, and have made about <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece, but that&lsquo;s an extra day. Our best customers are tradesmen in a big way, and people in the houses a little way out of town. Working people don&lsquo;t buy of us now. We&lsquo;re going to a penny gaff to-night&rdquo; (it was then between <num value="4">four</num> and <num value="5">five</num>); &ldquo;we&lsquo;ve no better way of spending our time when our day&lsquo;s work is done.</QUOTE>

