<div2 type=section id="c.11.91"><head>Of the Street Sale of Live Poultry.</head>

<p>THE street trade in live poultry is not considerable, and has become less considerable every year, since the facilities of railway conveyance have induced persons in the suburbs to make their purchases in London rather than of the hawkers. Geese used to be bought very largely by the hawkers in Leadenhall, and were driven in flocks to the country, <num value="500">500</num> being a frequent number of a flock. Their sale commenced about <num value="6">six</num> miles from town in all directions, the purchasers being those who, having the necessary convenience, liked to fatten their own Christmas geese, and the birds when bought were small and lean. A few flocks, with <num value="120">120</num> or <num value="150">150</num> in each, are still disposed of in this way; but the trade is not a <num value="5">fifth</num> of what it was. As this branch of the business is not in the hands of the hawkers, but generally of country poulterers resident in the towns not far from the metropolis, I need but allude to it. A few flocks of ducks are driven in the same way. 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>The street trade in live poultry continues only for <num value="3">three</num> months&mdash;from the latter part of June to the latter part of September. At this period, the hawkers say, as they can&lsquo;t get &ldquo;dead&rdquo; they must get &ldquo;live.&rdquo; During these <num value="3">three</num> months the hawkers sell <num value="500">500</num> chickens and <num value="300">300</num> ducks weekly, by hawking, or <num value="10400">10,400</num> in the season of <num value="13">13</num> weeks. Occasionally, as many as <num value="50">50</num> men and women&mdash;the same who hawk dead game and poultry&mdash;are concerned in the traffic I am treating of. At other times there are hardly <num value="30">30</num>, and in some not <num value="20">20</num> so employed, for if the weather be temperate, dead poultry is preferred to live by the hawkers. Taking the average of &ldquo;live&rdquo; sellers at <num value="25">25</num> every week, it gives only a trade of <num value="32">32</num> birds each weekly. Some, however, will sell <num value="18">18</num> in a day; but others, who occasionally resort to the trade, only a dozen in a week. The birds are sometimes carried in baskets on the hawker&lsquo;s arm, their heads being let through network at the top; but more frequently they are hawked in open wicker-work coops carried on the head. The best live poultry are from Surrey and Sussex; the inferior from Ireland, and perhaps more than <num value="3">three</num>-fourths of that sold by the hawkers is Irish. 
<p>The further nature of the trade, and the class of customers, is shown in the following statement, given to me by a middle-aged man, who had been familiar with the trade from his youth. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Yes, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I&lsquo;ve had a turn at live poultry for&mdash;let me see&mdash;someways between <num value="20">twenty</num> and <num value="25">twenty-five</num> years. The business is a sweater, sir; it&lsquo;s heavy work, but &lsquo;live&rsquo; aint so heavy as &lsquo;dead.&rsquo; There&lsquo;s fewer of them to carry in a round, that&lsquo;s it. Ah! <num value="20">twenty</num> years ago, or better, live poultry was worth following. I did a good bit in it. I&lsquo;ve sold <num value="160">160</num> fowls and ducks, and more, in a week, and cleared about <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> But out of that I had to give a man <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day, and his peck, to help me. At that time I sold my ducks and chickens&mdash;I worked nothing else&mdash;at from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece, according to size and quality. Now, if I get from <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> it&lsquo;s not so bad. I sell more, I think, however, over <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> than under it, but I&lsquo;m perticler in my &lsquo;live.&rsquo; I never sold to any but people out of town that had convenience to keep them, and Lord knows, I&lsquo;ve seen ponds I could jump over reckoned prime for ducks. Them that keeps their gardens nice won&lsquo;t buy live poultry. I&lsquo;ve seldom sold to the big houses anything like to what I&lsquo;ve done to the smaller. The big houses, you see, goes for fancy bantems, such as Sir John Seabright&lsquo;s, or Spanish hens, or a bit of a game cross, or real game&mdash;just for ornament, and not for fighting&mdash;or for anything that&lsquo;s got its name up. I&lsquo;ve known young couples buy fowls to have their breakfast eggs from them. <num value="1">One</num> young lady told me to bring her&mdash;that&lsquo;s <num value="15">fifteen</num> year ago, it is so&mdash;<num value="6">six</num> couples, that I knew would lay. I told her she&lsquo;d better have <num value="5">five</num> hens to a cock, and she didn&lsquo;t seem pleased, but I&lsquo;m sure I don&lsquo;t know why, for I hope I&lsquo;m always civil. I told her there would be murder if there was a cock to every hen. I supplied her, and made <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> by the job. I <hi rend=italics>have</hi> sold 
<pb id="p.127" n="127" img="2001.p1.0001">

<FIGURE id="Fig.127"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE>

<FIGURE id="Fig.127.1"><head>The Wallflower Girl. [<hi rend=italics>From a Daguerreotype by</hi> Beard.]</head></figure>
<pb id="p.129" n="129"> 
<milestone unit=col>
live fowls to the Jews about Whitechapel, on my way to Stratford and Bow, but only when I&lsquo;ve bought a bargain and sold <num value="1">one</num>. I don&lsquo;t know nothing how the Jews kills their fowls. Last summer I didn&lsquo;t make <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day; no, nor more than <num value="3">three</num> half-crowns a week in &lsquo;live.&rsquo; But that&lsquo;s only part of my trade. I don&lsquo;t complain, so it&lsquo;s nothing to nobody what I makes. From Beever (De Beauvoir) Town to Stamford Hill, and on to Tottenham and Edmonton, and turning off Walthamstow way is as good a round as any for live; it is so; but nothing to what it was. Highgate and Hampstead is middling. The t&lsquo;other side the water isn&lsquo;t good at all.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Fancy chickens, I may add, are never hawked, nor are live pigeons, nor geese, nor turkeys. 
<p>The hawkers&rsquo; sale of live poultry may be taken, at a moderate computation, as <num value="6500">6,500</num> chickens, and <num value="3900">3,900</num> ducks. 
<div2 type=section id="c.11.92"><head>Of Rabbit Selling in the Streets.</head>

<p>RABBIT-SELLING cannot be said to be a distinct branch of costermongering, but some streetsellers devote themselves to it more exclusively than to other &ldquo;goods,&rdquo; and, for <num value="5">five</num> or <num value="6">six</num> months of the year, sell little else. It is not often, though it is sometimes, united with the game or poultry trade, as a stock of rabbits, of a dozen or a dozen and a half, is a sufficient load for <num value="1">one</num> man. The best sale for rabbits is in the suburbs. They are generally carried slung <num value="2">two</num> and <num value="2">two</num> on a long pole, which is supported on the man&lsquo;s shoulders, or on a short <num value="1">one</num> which is carried in the hand. Lately, they have been hawked about hung up on a barrow. The trade is the briskest in the autumn and winter months; but some men carry them, though they do not confine themselves to the traffic in them, all the year round. The following statement shows the nature of the trade. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I was born and bred a costermonger,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and I&lsquo;ve been concerned with everything in the line. I&lsquo;ve been mostly &lsquo;on rabbits&rsquo; these <num value="5">five</num> or <num value="6">six</num> years, but I always sold a few, and now sometimes I sell a hare or <num value="2">two</num>, and, if rabbits is too dear, I tumble on to fish. I buy at Leadenhall mainly. I&lsquo;ve given from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a dozen for my rabbits. The usual price is from <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a dozen. [I may remark that the costers buy nearly all the Scotch rabbits, at an average of <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the dozen; and the Ostend rabbits, which are a shilling or <num value="2">two</num> dearer.] They&lsquo;re Hampshire rabbits; but I don&lsquo;t know where Hampshire is. I know they&lsquo;re from Hampshire, for they&lsquo;re called &lsquo;Wild Hampshire rabbits, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a pair.&rsquo; But still, as you say, that&lsquo;s only a call. I never sell a rabbit at <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, in course&mdash;it costs more. My way in business is to get <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> profit, and the skin, on every rabbit. If they cost me <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, I try to get <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
It&lsquo;s the skins is the profit. The skins now brings me from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a dozen. They&lsquo;re best in frosty weather. The fur&lsquo;s thickest then. It grows best in frost, I suppose. If I sell a dozen, it&lsquo;s a tidy day&lsquo;s work. If I get <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
 
<milestone unit=col>
a-piece on them, and the skins at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, it&lsquo;s <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, but I dont sell above <num value="5">5</num> dozen in a week &mdash;that&lsquo;s <num value="16">16</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a week, sir, is it? Wet and dark weather is against me. People won&lsquo;t often buy rabbits by candlelight, if they&lsquo;re ever so sweet. Some weeks in spring and summer I can&lsquo;t sell above <num value="2">two</num> dozen rabbits. I have sold <num value="2">two</num> dozen and <num value="10">ten</num> on a Saturday in the country, but then I had a young man to help me. I sell the skins to a warehouse for hatters. My old &lsquo;oman works a little fish at a stall sometimes, but she only can in fine weather, for we&lsquo;ve a kid that can hardly walk, and it don&lsquo;t do to let it stand out in the cold. Perhaps I may make <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week all the year round. I&lsquo;m paying <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week for <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> borrowed, and paid <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
all last year; but I&lsquo;ll pay no more after Christmas. I did better on rabbits <num value="4">four</num> or <num value="5">five</num> year back, because I sold more to working-people and small shopkeepers than I do now. I suppose it&lsquo;s because they&lsquo;re not so well off now as they was then, and, as you say, butchers&rsquo;--meat may be cheaper now, and tempts them. I do best short ways in the country. Wandsworth way ain&lsquo;t bad. No more is parts of StokeNewing- ton and Stamford-hill. St. John&lsquo;s Wood and Hampstead is middling. Hackney&lsquo;s bad. I goes all ways. I dont know what sort of people&lsquo;s my best customers. <num value="2">Two</num> of &lsquo;em, I&lsquo;ve been told, is banker&lsquo;s clerks, so in course they is rich.</QUOTE>
 
<p>There are <num value="600000">600,000</num> rabbits sold every year in the streets of London; these, at <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a-piece, give <num value="17500">17,500</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> thus expended annually in the metropolis. 
<div2 type=section id="c.11.93"><head>Of the Street Sale of Butter, Cheese, and Eggs.</head>

<p>ALL these commodities used to be hawked in the streets, and to a considerable extent. Until, as nearly as I can ascertain, between <num value="20">twenty</num> and <num value="30">thirty</num> years back, butter was brought from Epping, and other neighbouring parts, where good pasture existed, and hawked in the streets of London, usually along with poultry and eggs. This trade is among the more ancient of the street-trades. Steam-vessels and railways, however, have so stocked the markets, that no hawking of butter or eggs, from any agricultural part, even the nearest to London, would be remunerative now. Eggs are brought in immense quantities from France and Belgium, though <num value="30">thirty</num>, or even <num value="20">twenty</num> years ago the notion having of a good French egg, at a London breakfast-table, would have been laughed at as an absurd attempt at an impossible achievement. The number of eggs now annually imported into this kingdom, is <num value="98000000">98,000,000</num>, half of which may be said to be the yearly consumption of London. No butter is now hawked, but sometimes a few &ldquo;new laid&rdquo; eggs are carried from a rural part to the nearest metropolitan suburb, and are sold readily enough, if the purveyor be known. Mr. M&lsquo;Culloch estimates the average consumption of butter, in London, at <num value="6250000">6,250,000</num> lbs. per annum, or <num value="5">5</num> oz., weekly, each individual. <pb id="p.130" n="130"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>The hawking of cheese was never a prominent part of the street-trade. Of late, its sale in the streets, may be described as accidental. A considerable quantity of American cheese was hawked, or more commonly sold at a standing, <num value="5">five</num> or <num value="6">six</num> years ago; unto December last, and for <num value="3">three</num> months preceding, cheese was sold in the streets which had been rejected from Government stores, as it would not &ldquo;keep&rdquo; for the period required; but it was good for immediate consumption, for which all streetgoods are required. This, and the American cheese, were both sold in the streets at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the pound; usually, at fair weights, I am told, for it might not be easy to deceive the poor in a thing of such frequent purchase as &ldquo;half a quarter or a quarter&rdquo; (of a pound) of cheese. 
<p>The total quantity of foreign cheese consumed, yearly, in the metropolis may be estimated at <num value="25000000">25,000,000</num> lbs. weight, or half of the gross quantity annually imported. 
