<p>The cant or slang of the patterer is not the cant of the costermonger, but a system of their own. As in the case of the costers, it is so interlarded with their general remarks, while their ordinary language is so smothered and subdued, that unless when they are professionally engaged and talking of their wares, they might almost pass for foreigners. 
<p>There can be no doubt,&rdquo; continues my informant, &ldquo;that the <hi rend=italics><num value="2">second</num></hi> class of streetpatterers, to whom nature, or parents, or circumstances have been unpropitious, are the most moral, and have a greater sense of right and wrong, with a quicksightedness about humane and generous things, to which the &lsquo;aristocratic&rsquo; patterer is a stranger. Of the dealers in useful or harmless wares&mdash;although, of course, they use allowable exaggeration as to the goodness of the article&mdash;many are devout communicants at church, or members of dissenting bodies; while others are as careless about religion, and are still to be found once or twice a week in the lecture-rooms of the Mechanics&rsquo; Institute nearest to their residence. Orchard-street, Westminster, is a great locality for this sort of patterers. <num value="3">Three</num> well-known characters,&mdash;Bristol George, Corporal Casey, and Jemmy the Rake, with a very respectable and highly-informed man called &lsquo;Grocer,&rsquo; from his having been apprenticed to that business,&mdash;have maintained a character for great integrity among the neighbours for many years. 
<p>I come now to the <hi rend=italics><num value="3">third</num></hi> class of patterers,&mdash; those who, whatever their early pursuits and pleasures, have manifested a predilection for vagrancy, and neither can nor will settle to any ordinary calling. There is now on the streets a man scarcely <num value="30">thirty</num> years old, conspicuous by the misfortune of a sabre-wound on the cheek. He is a native of the Isle of Man. His father was a captain in the Buffs, and himself a commissioned officer at <num value="17">seventeen</num>. He left the army, designing to marry and open a boardingschool. The young lady to whom he was betrothed died, and <hi rend=italics>that</hi> event <hi rend=italics>might</hi> affect his mind; at any rate, he has had <num value="38">38</num> situations in a dozen years, and will not keep <num value="1">one</num> a week. He has a mortal antipathy to good clothes, and will not keep them <num value="1">one</num> hour. He sells anything&mdash;chiefly needle-cases. He &lsquo;patters&rsquo; very little in a <hi rend=italics>main drag</hi> (public street); but in the little private streets he preaches an outline of his life, and makes no secret of his wandering propensity. His aged mother, who still lives, pays his lodgings in Old Pye-street. 
<p>From the hasty glance I have taken at the patterers, any well-constructed mind may deduce the following inference: although a great amount of intelligence sometimes consists with a great want of principle, that an utter want of education, or 
<hi rend=italics>mis</hi>-education, leaves man, like a reed floating on the stream of time, to follow every direction which the current of affairs may give him. 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>There is yet another and a larger class, who are wanderers from choice,&mdash;who would rather be street-orators, and quacks, and performers, than anything else in the world. In <num value="9">nine</num> cases out of <num value="10">ten</num>, the street-patterers are persons of intemperate habits, no veracity, and destitute of any desire to improve their condition, even where they have the chance. <num value="1">One</num> of this crew was lately engaged at a bazaar; he had <num value="18">18</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week, and his only work was to walk up and down and extol the articles exhibited. This was too monotonous a life; I happened to pass him by as he was taking his wages for the week, and heard him say, &lsquo;I shall cut this b&mdash;y work; I can earn more on the streets, and be my own master.&rsquo;</QUOTE>
 
<p>It would be a mistake to suppose that the patterers, although a vagrant, are a disorganized class. There is a telegraphic dispatch between them, through the length and breadth of the land. If <num value="2">two</num> patterers (previously unacquainted) meet in the provinces, the following, or something like it, will be their conversation: &mdash;&ldquo;Can you &lsquo;voker romeny&rsquo; (can you speak cant)? What is your &lsquo;monekeer&rsquo; (name)?&rdquo; &mdash;Perhaps it turns out that <num value="1">one</num> is &ldquo;Whiteheaded Bob,&rdquo; and the other &ldquo;Plymouth Ned.&rdquo; They have a &ldquo;shant of gatter&rdquo; (pot of beer) at the ncarest &ldquo;boozing ken&rdquo; (ale-house), and swear eternal friendship to each other. The old saying, that &ldquo;When the liquor is in, the wit is out,&rdquo; is remarkably fulfilled on these occasions, for they betray to the &ldquo;flatties&rdquo; (natives) all their profits and proceedings. 
<p>It is to be supposed that, in country districts, where there are no streets, the patterer is obliged to call at the houses. As they are mostly without the hawker&lsquo;s licence, and sometimes find wet linen before it is lost, the rural districts are not fond of their visits; and there are generally <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> persons in a village reported to be &ldquo;gammy,&rdquo; that is (unfavourable). If a patterer has been &ldquo;crabbed,&rdquo; that is (offended) at any of the &ldquo;cribbs&rdquo; (houses), he mostly chalks a signal on or near the door. I give <num value="1">one</num> or <num value="2">two</num> instances: 
<p><FIGURE id="Fig.218"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE> &ldquo;Bone,&rdquo; meaning good. 
<p><FIGURE id="Fig.218.1"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE> &ldquo;Cooper&lsquo;d,&rdquo; spoiled by the imprudence of some other patterer. 
<p><FIGURE id="Fig.218.2"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE> &ldquo;Gammy,&rdquo; likely to have you taken up. 
<p><FIGURE id="Fig.218.3"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE> &ldquo;Flummuxed,&rdquo; sure of a month in quod. 
<p>In most lodging-houses there is an old man who is the guide to every &ldquo;walk&rdquo; in the vicinity, and who can tell every house, on every round, that is &ldquo;good for a cold &lsquo;tater.&rdquo; In many cases there is over the kitchen mantlepiece a map of the district, dotted here and there with memorandums of failure or success. 
<p>Patterers are fond of carving their names and avocations about the houses they visit. The old jail at Dartford has been some years a &ldquo;padding-ken.&rdquo; In <num value="1">one</num> of the rooms appears the following autographs: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Jemmy, the Rake, bound to Bristol; bad beds, but no bugs. Thank God for all things.</QUOTE>
 
<p>&ldquo;Razor George and his moll slept here the <pb id="p.219" n="219"> 
<milestone unit=col>
day afore Christmas; just out of &lsquo;stir&rsquo; (jail), for &lsquo;muzzling a peeler.&rsquo;&rdquo; 
<p>&ldquo;Scotch Mary, with &lsquo;driz&rsquo; (lace), bound to Dover and back, please God.&rdquo; 
<p>Sometimes these inscriptions are coarse and obscene; sometimes very well written and orderly. Nor do they want illustrations. 
<p>At the old factory, Lincoln, is a portrait of the town beadle, formerly a soldier; it is drawn with different-coloured chalks, and ends with the following couplet: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>You are a B for false swearing, 
<L>In hell they&lsquo;ll roast you like a herring.</quote>

<p>Concubinage is very common among patterers, especially on their travels; they have their regular rounds, and call the peregrination &ldquo;going on circuit.&rdquo; For the most part they are early risers; this gives them a facility for meeting poor girls who have had a night&lsquo;s shelter in the union workhouses. They offer such girls some refreshment,&mdash;swear they are single men,&mdash;and promise comforts certainly superior to the immediate position of their victims. Consent is generally obtained; perhaps a girl of <num value="14">14</num> or <num value="15">15</num>, previously virtuous, is induced to believe in a promise of constant protection, but finds herself, the next morning, ruined and deserted; nor is it unlikely that, within a month or <num value="2">two</num>, she will see her seducer in the company of a dozen incidental wives. A gray-headed miscreant called &ldquo;Cutler Tom&rdquo; boasts of <num value="500">500</num> such exploits; and there is too great reason to believe that the picture of his own drawing is not greatly overcharged. 
<p>Some of the patterers are married men, but of this class very few are faithful to the solemn obligation. I have heard of a renowned patterer of this class who was married to <num value="4">four</num> women, and had lived in criminal intercourse with his own sister, and his own daughter by <num value="1">one</num> of the wives. This sad rule has, however, I am happy to state, some splendid exceptions. There is a man called &ldquo;Andy&rdquo;&mdash;well known as the companion of &ldquo;Hopping Ned;&rdquo; this &ldquo;Andy&rdquo; has a wife of great personal attractions, a splendid figure, and teeth without a parallel. She is a strictly-virtuous woman, a most devoted wife, and tender mother; very charitable to any <num value="1">one</num> in want of a meal, and very constant (she is a Catholic) in her religious duties. Another man of the same school, whose name has escaped me, is, with his wife, an exception to the stigma on almost the whole class; the couple in question have no children. The wife, whose name is Maria, has been in every hospital for some complaint in her knees, probably white swelling: her beauty is the theme of applause, and whenever she opens her mouth silence pervades the &ldquo;paddin&lsquo; ken.&rdquo; Her common conversation is music and mathematics combined, her reading has been masculine and extensive, and the whisper of calumny has never yet attacked her own demeanour or her husband&lsquo;s. 
<p>Of patterers who have children, many are very exemplary; sending them to Day and Sunday-schools, causing them to say grace before 
<milestone unit=col>
and after meals, to attend public worship, and always to speak the truth: these, instances, however, stand in fearful contrast with the conduct of other parents. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I have seen,&rdquo; proceeds my reverend informant, &ldquo;fathers and mothers place their boys and girls in positions of incipient enormity, and command them to use language and gestures to each other, which would make an harlot blush, and almost a heathen tremble. I have hitherto viewed the patterer as a salesman,&mdash;having something in his hand, on whose merits, real or pretended, he talks people out of their money. By slow degrees prosperity rises, but rapid is the advance of evil. The patterer sometimes gets &lsquo;out of stock,&rsquo; and is obliged, at no great sacrifice of conscience, to &lsquo;patter&rsquo; in another strain. In every large town sham official documents, with crests, seals, and signatures, can be got for half-a-crown. Armed with these, the patterer becomes a &lsquo;lurker,&rsquo;&mdash;that is, an impostor; his papers certify any and every &lsquo;ill that flesh is heir to.&rsquo; Shipwreck is called a &lsquo;shake lurk;&rsquo; loss by fire is a &lsquo;glim.&rsquo; Sometimes the petitioner has had a horse, which has dropped dead with the mad staggers; or has a wife ill or dying, and <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="7">seven</num> children at once sickening of the small-pox. Children are borrowed to support the appearance; the case is certified by the minister and churchwardens of a parish which exists only in imagination; and as many people dislike the trouble of investigation, the patterer gets enough to raise a stock in trade, and divides the spoil between the swag-shop and the gin-palace. Sometimes they are detected, and get a &lsquo;drag&rsquo; (<num value="3">three</num> months in prison). They have many narrow escapes: <num value="1">one</num> occurs to me, of a somewhat ludicrous character. A patterer and lurker (now dead) known by the name of &lsquo;Captain Moody,&rsquo; unable to get a &lsquo;fakement&rsquo; written or printed, was standing almost naked in the streets of a neighbouring town. A gentleman stood still and heard his piteous tale, but having been &lsquo;done&rsquo; more than once, he resolved to examine the affair, and begged the petitioner to conduct him to his wife and children, who were in a garret on a bed of languishing, with neither clothes, food, nor fire, but, it appeared, with faith enough to expect a supply from &lsquo;Him who feedeth the ravens,&rsquo; and in whose sacred name even a cold &lsquo;tater was implored. The patterer, or half-patterer and halfbeggar, took the gentleman (who promised a sovereign if every thing was square) through innumerable and intricate windings, till he came to an outhouse or sort of stable. He saw the key outside the door, and begged the gentleman to enter and wait till he borrowed a light of a neighbour, to show him up-stairs. The illumination never arrived, and the poor charitable man found that the miscreant had locked him into the stable. The patterer went to the padding-ken,&mdash;told the story with great glee, and left that locality within an hour of the occurrence.</QUOTE>
 
<p>[Concerning the mendicancy and vagrancy of <pb id="p.220" n="220"> 
<milestone unit=col>
patterers, I shall have more to say when I speak of vagrancy in general, and when I describe the general state and characteristics of the low lodging-houses in London, and those in the country, which are in intimate connection with the metropolitan abodes of the vagrant. My present theme is the London patterer, who is also a street-seller.] 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.159"><head>Of the Publishers and authors of Street-Literature.</head>

<p>THE best known, and the most successful printer and publisher of all who have directed their industry to supply the &ldquo;paper&rdquo; in demand for street sale, and in every department of street literature, was the late &ldquo;Jemmy Catnach,&rdquo; who is said to have amassed upwards of <num value="10000">10,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> in the business. He is reported to have made the greater part of this sum during the trial of Queen Caroline, by the sale of whole-sheet &ldquo;papers,&rdquo; descriptive of the trial, and embellished with &ldquo;splendid illustrations.&rdquo; The next to Catnach stood the late &ldquo;Tommy Pitt,&rdquo; of the noted toy and marble-warehouse. These <num value="2">two</num> parties were the Colburn and Bentley of the &ldquo;paper&rdquo; trade. Catnach retired from business some years ago, and resided in a country-house at Barnet, but he did not long survive his retirement. &ldquo;He was an out and out sort,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> old paper-worker to me, &ldquo;and if he knew you&mdash; and he could judge according to the school you belonged to, if he hadn&lsquo;t known you long&mdash;he was friendly for a bob or <num value="2">two</num>, and sometimes for a glass. He knew the men that was stickers though, and there was no glass for them. Why, some of his customers, sir, would have stuck to him long enough, if there&lsquo;d been a chance of another glass&mdash;supposing they&lsquo;d managed to get 
<hi rend=italics><num value="1">one</num></hi>&mdash;and then would have asked him for a coach home! When I called on him, he used to say, in his north country way&mdash;he wasn&lsquo;t Scotch, but somewhere north of England&mdash;and he was pleasant with it, &lsquo;Well, d&mdash;you, how are you?&rsquo; He got the cream of the pail, sir.&rdquo; 
<p>The present street literature printers and publishers are, Mrs. Ryle (Catnach&lsquo;s niece and successor), Mr. Birt, and Mr. Paul (formerly with Catnach), all of the <num value="7">Seven</num> Dials; Mr. Powell (formerly of Lloyd&lsquo;s), Brick-lane, Whitechapel; and Mr. Good, Aylesbury-street, Clerkenwell. Mr. Phairs, of Westminster; Mr. Taylor, of the Waterloo-road; and Mr. Sharp, of Kent-street, Borough, have discontinued street printing. <num value="1">One</num> man greatly regretted Mr. Taylor&lsquo;s discontinuing the business; &ldquo;he was so handy for the New-cut, when it <hi rend=italics>was</hi> the Newcut.&rdquo; Some classes of patterers, I may here observe, work in &ldquo;schools&rdquo; or &ldquo;mobs&rdquo; of <num value="2">two</num>, <num value="3">three</num>, or <num value="4">four</num>, as I shall afterwards show. 
<p>The authors and poets who give its peculiar literature, alike in prose or rhyme, to the streets, are now <num value="6">six</num> in number. They are all in some capacity or other connected with street-patter or song, and the way in which a narrative or a &ldquo;copy of werses&rdquo; is prepared for press is usually 
<milestone unit=col>
this:&mdash;The leading members of the &ldquo;schools,&rdquo; some of whom refer regularly to the evening papers, when they hear of any out-of-the-way occurrence, resort to the printer and desire its publication in a style proper for the streets. This is usually done very speedily, the school (or the majority of them) and the printer agreeing upon the author. Sometimes an author will voluntarily prepare a piece of street literature and submit it to a publisher, who, as in the case of other publishers, accepts or declines, as he believes the production will or will not prove remunerative. Sometimes the school carry the manuscript with them to the printer, and undertake to buy a certain quantity, to insure publication. The payment to the author is the same in all cases&mdash;a shilling. 
<p>Concerning the history and character of our street and public-house literature, I shall treat hereafter, when I can comprise the whole, and after the descriptions of the several classes engaged in the trade will have paved the way for the reader&lsquo;s better appreciation of the curious and important theme. I say, <hi rend=italics>important;</hi> because the street-ballad and the streetnarrative, like all popular things, have their influence on masses of the people. Specimens will be found adduced, as I describe the several classes, or in the statements of the patterers. 
<p>It must be borne in mind that the street author is closely restricted in the quality of his effusion. It must be such as the patterers approve, as the chaunters can chaunt, the balladsingers sing, and&mdash;above all&mdash;such as streetbuyers will buy. <num value="1">One</num> chaunter, who was a great admirer of the &ldquo;Song of the Shirt,&rdquo; told me that if Hood himself had written the &ldquo;Pitiful Case of Georgy Sloan and his Wife,&rdquo; it would not have sold so well as a ballad he handed to me, from which I extract a verse: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><L>Jane Willbred we did starve and beat her very hard 
<L>I confess we used her very cruel, 
<L>But now in a jail <num value="2">two</num> long years we must bewail, 
<L>We don&lsquo;t fancy mustard in the gruel.</quote>

<p>What I have said of the <hi rend=italics>necessity</hi> which controls street authorship, may also be said of the art which is sometimes called in to illustrate it. 
<p>The paper now published for the streets is classed as quarter sheets, which cost (wholesale) <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a gross; half sheets, which cost <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; and whole or broad sheets (such as for executions), which cost <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a gross the <num value="1">first</num> day, and <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
the next day or <num value="2">two</num>, and afterwards, but only if a ream be taken, <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; a ream contains <num value="40">forty</num> dozen. When &ldquo;illustrated,&rdquo; the charge is from <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> per ream extra. The books, for such cases as the Sloanes, or the murder of Jael Denny, are given in books&mdash;which are best adapted for the suburban and country trade, when London is &ldquo;worked&rdquo; sufficiently&mdash;are the &ldquo;whole sheet&rdquo; printed so as to fold into <num value="8">eight</num> pages, each side of the paper being then, of course, printed upon. A book is charged from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> extra (to a whole sheet) per gross, and afterwards the same extra per ream. <pb id="p.221" n="221"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<div2 type=section id="c.15.160"><head>Of Long Song-Sellers.</head>

<p>I have this week given a daguerreotype of a well-known long-song seller, and have preferred to give it as the trade, especially as regards London, has all but disappeared, and it was curious enough. &ldquo;Long songs&rdquo; <num value="1">first</num> appeared between <num value="9">nine</num> and <num value="10">ten</num> years ago. 
<p>The long-song sellers did not depend upon patter&mdash;though some of them pattered a little&mdash; to attract customers, but on the veritable cheapness and novel form in which they vended popular songs, printed on paper rather wider than this page, &ldquo;<num value="3">three</num> songs abreast,&rdquo; and the paper was about a yard long, which constituted the &ldquo;<num value="3">three</num>&rdquo; yards of song. Sometimes <num value="3">three</num> slips were pasted together. The vendors paraded the streets with their &ldquo;<num value="3">three</num> yards of new and popular songs&rdquo; for a penny. The songs are, or were, generally fixed to the top of a long pole, and the vendor &ldquo;cried&rdquo; the different titles as he went along. This branch of &ldquo;the profession&rdquo; is confined solely to the summer; the hands in winter usually taking to the sale of song-books, it being impossible to exhibit &ldquo;the <num value="3">three</num> yards&rdquo; in wet or foggy weather. The paper songs, as they fluttered from a pole, looked at a little distance like huge much-soiled white ribbons, used as streamers to celebrate some auspicious news. The cry of <num value="1">one</num> man, in a sort of recitative, or, as I heard it called by street-patterers, &ldquo;singsong,&rdquo; was, &ldquo;<num value="3">Three</num> yards a penny! <num value="3">Three</num> yards a penny! Beautiful songs! Newest songs! Popular Songs! <num value="3">Three</num> yards a penny! Song, song, songs!&rdquo; Others, however, were generally content to announce merely &ldquo;<num value="3">Three</num> yards a penny!&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> cried &ldquo;<num value="2">Two</num> under <num value="50">fifty</num> a fardy!&rdquo; As if <num value="250">two hundred and fifty</num> songs were to be sold for a farthing. The whole number of songs was about <num value="45">45</num>. They were afterwards sold at a halfpenny, but were shorter and fewer. It is probable that at the best had the songs been subjected to the admeasurement of a jury, the result might have been as little satisfactory as to some tradesmen who, however, after having been detected in attempts to cheat the poor in weights and scales, and to cheat them hourly, are still &ldquo;good men and true&rdquo; enough to be jurymen and parliamentary electors. The songs, I am informed, were often about <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num> yards, (not as to paper but as to admeasurement of type); <num value="3">3</num> yards, occasionally, at <num value="1">first</num>, and not often less than <num value="2">2</num> yards. 
<p>The crying of the titles was not done with any other design than that of expressing the great number of songs purchasable for &ldquo;the small charge of <num value="1">one</num> penny.&rdquo; Some of the patterers I conversed with would have made it sufficiently droll. <num value="1">One</num> man told me that he had cried the following songs in his <num value="3">three</num> yards, and he believed in something like the following order, but he had cried penny song books, among other things, lately, and might confound his more ancient and recent cries: 
<p>&ldquo;I sometimes began,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;with sing- 
<milestone unit=col>
ing, or trying to sing, for I&lsquo;m no vocalist, the <num value="1">first</num> few words of any song, and them quite loud. I&lsquo;d begin 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>The Pope he leads a happy life, 
<L>He knows no care&mdash;&mdash;</quote>

<p>&lsquo;Buffalo gals, come out to-night;&rsquo; &lsquo;Death of Nelson;&rsquo; The gay cavalier;&rsquo; &lsquo;Jim along Josey;&rsquo; &lsquo;There&lsquo;s a good time coming;&rsquo; &lsquo;Drink to me only;&rsquo; &lsquo;Kate Kearney;&rsquo; &lsquo;Chuckaroo--choo, choo--choo--choot--lah;&rsquo; &lsquo;Chockala--roony--ninkaping--nang;&rsquo; &lsquo;Pagadaway-dusty-kanty-key;&rsquo; &lsquo;Hottypiegunnypo- china-coo&rsquo; (that&lsquo;s a Chinese song, sir); &lsquo;I dreamed that I dwelt in marble halls;&rsquo; &lsquo;The standard bearer;&rsquo; &lsquo;Just like love;&rsquo; &lsquo;Whistle o&lsquo;er the lave o&lsquo;t;&rsquo; &lsquo;Widow Mackree;&rsquo; &lsquo;I&lsquo;ve been roaming;&rsquo; &lsquo;Oh! that kiss;&rsquo; &lsquo;The old English gentleman,&rsquo; &amp;c., &amp;c. &amp;c. I dares say they was all in the <num value="3">three</num> yards, or was once, and if they wasn&lsquo;t there was others as good.&rdquo; 
<p>The chief purchasers of the &ldquo;long songs&rdquo; were boys and girls, but mostly boys, who expended <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> or <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for the curiosity and novelty of the thing, as the songs were not in the most readable form. A few working people bought them for their children, and some women of the town, who often buy anything fantastic, were also customers. 
<p>When &ldquo;the <num value="3">three</num> yards was at their best,&rdquo; the number selling them was about <num value="170">170</num>; the wholesale charge is from <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a dozen, according to size. The profit of the vendors in the <num value="1">first</num> instance was about <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a dozen. When the trade had all the attractions of novelty, some men sold <num value="10">ten</num> dozen on fine days, and for <num value="3">three</num> or <num value="4">four</num> of the summer months; so clearing between <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day. This, however, was not an average, but an average might be at <num value="1">first</num> <num value="21">21</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week profit. I am assured that if <num value="20">twenty</num> persons were selling long songs in the street last summer it was &ldquo;the outside,&rdquo; as long songs are now &ldquo;for fairs and races and country work.&rdquo; Calculating that each cleared <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> in a week, and to clear that took <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, the profit being smaller than it used to be, as many must be sold at <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each&mdash;we find <num value="120">120</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>
expended in long songs in the streets. The character of the vendor is that of a patterer of inferior genius. 
<p>The stock-money required is <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; which with <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for a pole, and <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for paste, is all the capital needed. Very few were sold in the public-houses, as the vendors scrupled to expose them there, &ldquo;for drunken fellows would snatch them, and make belts of them for a lark.&rdquo; 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.161"><head>Of Running Patterers.</head>

<p>Few of the residents in London&mdash;but chiefly those in the quieter streets &mdash; have not been aroused, and most frequently in the evening, by a hurly-burly on each side of the street. An attentive listening will not lead any <num value="1">one</num> to an accurate knowledge of what the clamour is about. It is from a &ldquo;mob&rdquo; or &ldquo;school&rdquo; of the running patterers (for both those words are <pb id="p.222" n="222"> 
<milestone unit=col>
used), and consists of <num value="2">two</num>, <num value="3">three</num>, or <num value="4">four</num> men. All these men state that the greater the noise they make, the better is the chance of sale, and better still when the noise is on each side of a street, for it appears as if the vendors were proclaiming such interesting or important intelligence, that they were vieing with <num value="1">one</num> another who should supply the demand which must ensue. It is not possible to ascertain with any certitude <hi rend=italics>what</hi> the patterers are so anxious to sell, for only a few leading words are audible. <num value="1">One</num> of the cleverest of running patterers repeated to me, in a subdued tone, his announcements of murders. The words &ldquo;Murder,&rdquo; &ldquo;Horrible,&rdquo; &ldquo;Barbarous,&rdquo; &ldquo;Love,&rdquo; &ldquo;Mysterious,&rdquo; &ldquo;Former Crimes,&rdquo; and the like, could only be caught by the ear, but there was no announcement of anything like &ldquo;particulars.&rdquo; If, however, the &ldquo;paper&rdquo; relate to any well-known criminal, such as Rush, the name is given distinctly enough, and so is any new or pretended fact. The running patterers describe, or profess to describe, the contents of their papers as they go rapidly along, and they seldom or ever stand still. They usually deal in murders, seductions, crim.-cons., explosions, alarming accidents, &ldquo;assassinations,&rdquo; deaths of public characters, duels, and love-letters. But popular, or notorious, murders are the &ldquo;great goes.&rdquo; The running patterer cares less than other streetsellers for bad weather, for if he &ldquo;work&rdquo; on a wet and gloomy evening, and if the work be &ldquo;a cock,&rdquo; which is a fictitious statement or even a pretended fictitious statement, there is the less chance of any <num value="1">one</num> detecting the <hi rend=italics>ruse.</hi>
But of late years no new &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; have been printed, excepting for temporary purposes, such as I have specified as under its appropriate head in my account of &ldquo;Death and Fire-Hunters.&rdquo; Among the old stereotyped &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; are love-letters. <num value="1">One</num> is well known as &ldquo;The Husband caught in a Trap,&rdquo; and being in an epistolary form subserves any purpose: whether it be the patterer&lsquo;s aim to sell the &ldquo;Love Letters&rdquo; of any well-known person, such as Lola Montes, or to fit them for a local (pretended) scandal, as the &ldquo;Letters from a Lady in this neighbourhood to a Gentleman not <num value="100">100</num> miles off.&rdquo; 
<p>Of running patterers there are now in London from <num value="80">80</num> to <num value="100">100</num>. They reside&mdash;some in their own rooms, but the majority in lodging-houses &mdash;in or near Westminster, St. Giles&lsquo;s, Whitechapel, Stratford, Deptford, Wandsworth, and the <num value="7">Seven</num> Dials. The &ldquo;Dials,&rdquo; however, is their chief locality, being the residence of the longest-established printers, and is the &ldquo;head meet&rdquo; of the fraternity. 
<p>It is not easy to specify with exactitude the number of running or flying patterers at any <num value="1">one</num> time in London. Some of these men become, occasionally, standing patterers, chaunters, or ballad-singers&mdash;classes I shall subsequently describe&mdash;and all of them resort at intervals to country rounds. I heard, also, many complaints 
<milestone unit=col>
of boys having of late &ldquo;taken to the running patter&rdquo; when anything attractive was before the public, and of ignorant fellows&mdash;that wouldn&lsquo;t have thought of it at <num value="1">one</num> time&mdash;&ldquo;trying their hands at it.&rdquo; Waiving these exceptional augmentations of the number, I will take the body of running patterers, generally employed in their peculiar craft in London, at <num value="90">90</num>. To ascertain their earnings presents about the same difficulties as to ascertain their number; for as all they earn is spent&mdash;no patterer ever saving money&mdash; they themselves are hardly able to tell their incomes. If any new and exciting fact be before the public, these men may each clear <num value="20">20</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week; when there is no such fact, they may not earn <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> The profit is contingent, moreover, upon their being able to obtain <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, or only <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, for their paper. Some represented their average weekly earnings at <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the year through; some at <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; and others at less than half of <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> Reckoning, however, that only <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
weekly is an average profit per individual, and that <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> be taken to realise that profit, we find <num value="3276">3,276</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> expended yearly on running patterers in London; but in that sum the takings of the chaunters must be included, as they are members of the same fraternity, and work with the patterers. 
<p>The capital required to commence as a running patterer is but the price of a few papers&mdash;from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> The men have no distinctive dress: &ldquo;our togs,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> of them, &ldquo;is in the latest fashion of Petticoat-lane;&rdquo; unless on the very rare occasions, when some character has to be personated, and then coloured papers and glazed calicoes are made available. But this is only a venture of the old hands. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.162"><head>Experience of a Running Patterer.</head>

<p>FROM a running patterer, who has been familiar with the trade for many years, I received, upwards of a twelvemonth ago, the following statement. He is well known for his humour, and is a leading man in his fraternity. After some conversation about &ldquo;cocks,&rdquo; the most popular of which, my informant said, was the murder at Chigwell-row, he continued: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>That&lsquo;s a trump, to the present day. Why, I&lsquo;d go out now, sir, with a dozen of Chigwellrows, and earn my supper in half an hour off of &lsquo;em. The murder of Sarah Holmes at Lincoln is good, too&mdash;that there has been worked for the last <num value="5">five</num> year successively every winter. Poor Sarah Holmes! Bless her! she has saved me from walking the streets all night many a time. Some of the best of these have been in work <num value="20">twenty</num> years&mdash;the Scarborough murder has full <num value="20">twenty</num> years. It&lsquo;s called &lsquo;THE SCARBOROUGH TRAGEDY.&rsquo; I&lsquo;ve worked it myself. It&lsquo;s about a noble and rich young naval officer seducing a poor clergyman&lsquo;s daughter. She is confined in a ditch, and destroys the child. She is taken up for it, tried, and executed. This has had a great run. It sells all round the country places, and would sell now if they had it out. Mostly all our customers is females. They are the chief 
<FIGURE id="Fig.222"><head>Long-Song Seller. &ldquo;<num value="2">Two</num> under <num value="50">fifty</num> for a fardy&rsquo;!&rdquo; [<hi rend=italics>From a Daguerreotype by</hi> Beard.]</head></figure>
<pb id="p.223" n="223"> 
<milestone unit=col>
dependence we have. The Scarborough Tragedy is very attractive. It draws tears to the women&lsquo;s eyes to think that a poor clergyman&lsquo;s daughter, who is remarkably beautiful, should murder her own child; it&lsquo;s very touching to every feeling heart. There&lsquo;s a copy of verses with it, too. Then there&lsquo;s the Liverpool Tragedy&mdash;that&lsquo;s very attractive. It&lsquo;s a mother murdering her own son, through gold. He had come from the East Indies, and married a rich planter&lsquo;s daughter. He came back to England to see his parents after an absence of <num value="30">thirty</num> years. They kept a lodging-house in Liverpool for sailors; the son went there to lodge, and meant to tell his parents who he was in the morning. His mother saw the gold he had got in his boxes, and cut his throat&mdash;severed his head from his body; the old man, upwards of <num value="70">seventy</num> years of age, holding the candle. They had put a washing-tub under the bed to catch his blood. The morning after the murder, the old man&lsquo;s daughter calls and inquires for a young man. The old man denies that they have had any such person in the house. She says he had a mole on his arm, in the shape of a strawberry. The old couple go up-stairs to examine the corpse, and find they have murdered their own son, and then they both put an end to their existence. This is a deeper tragedy than the Scarborough Murder. That suits young people better; they like to hear about the young woman being seduced by the naval officer; but the mothers take more to the Liverpool Tragedy&mdash; it suits them better. Some of the &lsquo;cocks&rsquo; were in existence long before ever I was born or thought of. The &lsquo;Great and important battle between the <num value="2">two</num> young ladies of fortune,&rsquo; is what we calls &lsquo;a ripper.&rsquo; I should like to have that there put down correct,&rdquo; he added, &ldquo;&lsquo;cause I&lsquo;ve taken a tidy lot of money out of it.</QUOTE>
 
<p>My informant, who had been upwards of <num value="20">20</num> years in the running patter line, told me that he commenced his career with the &ldquo;Last Dying Speech and Full Confession of William Corder.&rdquo; He was <num value="16">sixteen</num> years of age, and had run away from his parents. &ldquo;I worked that there,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;down in the very town (at Bury) where he was executed. I got a whole hatful of halfpence at that. Why, I wouldn&lsquo;t even give &lsquo;em <num value="7">seven</num> for sixpence&mdash;no, that I wouldn&lsquo;t. A gentleman&lsquo;s servant come out and wanted half a dozen for his master and <num value="1">one</num> for himself in, and I wouldn&lsquo;t let him have no such thing. We often sells more than that at once. Why, I sold <num value="6">six</num> at <num value="1">one</num> go to the railway clerks at Norwich about the Manning affair, only a fortnight back. But Steinburgh&lsquo;s little job&mdash;you know he murdered his wife and family, and committed suicide after &mdash;that sold as well as any &lsquo;die.&rsquo; Pegsworth was an out-and-out lot. I did tremendous with him, because it happened in London, down Ratcliff-highway &mdash; that&lsquo;s a splendid quarter for working&mdash;there&lsquo;s plenty of feelings&mdash;but, bless you, some places you go to you can&lsquo;t move no how, they&lsquo;ve hearts like paving-stones. They 
<milestone unit=col>
wouldn&lsquo;t have &lsquo;the papers&rsquo; if you&lsquo;d give them to &lsquo;em &mdash; especially when they knows you. Greenacre didn&lsquo;t sell so well as might have been expected, for such a diabolical out-and-out crime as he committed; but you see he came close after Pegsworth, and that took the beauty off him. <num value="2">Two</num> murderers together is never no good to nobody. Why there was Wilson Gleeson, as great a villain as ever lived&mdash;went and murdered a whole family at noon--day&mdash;but Rush coopered him&mdash;and likewise that girl at Bristol&mdash;made it no draw to any <num value="1">one</num>. Daniel Good, though, was a <num value="1">first</num>-rater; and would have been much better if it hadn&lsquo;t been for that there Madam Toosow. You see, she went down to Roehampton, and guv <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> for the werry clogs as he used to wash his master&lsquo;s carriage in; so, in course, when the harristocracy could go and see the real things&mdash;the werry identical clogs&mdash;in the Chamber of &lsquo;Orrors, why the people wouldn&lsquo;t look at our authentic portraits of the fiend in human form. Hocker wasn&lsquo;t any particular great shakes. There was a deal expected from him, but he didn&lsquo;t turn out well. Courvoisier was much better; he sold wery well, but nothing to Blakesley. Why I worked him for <num value="6">six</num> weeks. The wife of the murdered man kept the King&lsquo;s Head that he was landlord on open on the morning of the execution, and the place was like a fair. I even went and sold papers outside the door myself. I thought if she war&lsquo;n&lsquo;t ashamed, why should I be? After that we had a fine &lsquo;fake&rsquo;&mdash;that was the fire of the Tower of London&mdash;it sold rattling. Why we had about <num value="40">forty</num> apprehended for that&mdash;<num value="1">first</num> we said <num value="2">two</num> soldiers was taken up that couldn&lsquo;t obtain their discharge, and then we declared it was a wellknown sporting nobleman who did it for a spree. The boy Jones in the Palace wasn&lsquo;t much of an affair for the running patterers; the ballad singers&mdash;or street screamers, as we calls &lsquo;em&mdash;had the pull out of that. The patter wouldn&lsquo;t take; they had read it all in the newspapers before. Oxford, and Francis, and Bean were a little better, but nothing to crack about. The people doesn&lsquo;t care about such things as them. There&lsquo;s nothing beats a stunning good murder, after all. Why there was Rush&mdash;I lived on him for a month or more. When I commenced with Rush, I was <num value="14">14</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> in debt for rent, and in less than <num value="14">fourteen</num> days I astonished the wise men in the east by paying my landlord all I owed him. Since Dan&lsquo;el Good there had been little or nothing doing in the murder line &mdash;no <num value="1">one</num> could cap him&mdash;till Rush turned up a regular trump for us. Why I went down to Norwich expressly to work the execution. I worked my way down there with &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>a sorrowful lamentation</hi>&rsquo; of his own composing, which I&lsquo;d got written by the blind man expressly for the occasion. On the morning of the execution we beat all the regular newspapers out of the field; for we had the full, true, and particular account down, you see, by our own express, and that can beat anything that ever they can publish; for we gets it printed several days afore it comes off, <pb id="p.224" n="224"> 
<milestone unit=col>
and goes and stands with it right under the drop; and many&lsquo;s the penny I&lsquo;ve turned away when I&lsquo;ve been asked for an account of the whole business <hi rend=italics>before</hi> it happened. So you see, for herly and correct hinformation, we can beat the 
<hi rend=italics>Sun</hi>&mdash;aye, or the moon either, for the matter of that. Irish Jem, the Ambassador, never goes to bed but he blesses Rush the farmer; and many&lsquo;s the time he&lsquo;s told me we should never have such another windfall as that. But I told him not to despair; there&lsquo;s a good time coming, boys, says I, and, sure enough, up comes the Bermondsey tragedy. We might have done very well, indeed, out of the Mannings, but there was too many examinations for it to be any great account to us. I&lsquo;ve been away with the Mannings in the country ever since. I&lsquo;ve been through Hertfordshire, Cambridgeshire, and Suffolk, along with George Frederick Manning and his wife&mdash; travelled from <num value="800">800</num> to <num value="1000">1,000</num> miles with &lsquo;em, but I could have done much better if I had stopped in London. Every day I was anxiously looking for a confession from Mrs. Manning. All I wanted was for her to clear her conscience afore she left this here whale of tears (that&lsquo;s what I always calls it in the patter), and when I read in the papers (mind they was none of my own) that her last words on the brink of heternity was, &lsquo;I&lsquo;ve nothing to say to you, Mr. Rowe, but to thank you for your kindness,&rsquo; I guv her up entirely&mdash;had completely done with her. In course the public looks to us for the last words of all monsters in human form, and as for Mrs. Manning&lsquo;s, they were not worth the printing.&rdquo; 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.163"><head>Of the Recent Experience of a Running Patterer.</head>

<p>FROM the same man I had the following account of his vocation up to the present time: 
<p>&ldquo;Well, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I think, take them altogether, things hasn&lsquo;t been so good this last year as the year before. But the Pope, God bless him! he&lsquo;s been the best friend I&lsquo;ve had since Rush, but Rush licked his Holiness. You see, the Pope and Cardinal Wiseman is a <num value="1">one</num>-sided affair; of course the Catholics won&lsquo;t buy anything against the Pope, but <hi rend=italics>all</hi> religions could go for Rush. Our mob once thought of starting a cardinal&lsquo;s dress, and I thought of wearing a red hat myself. I did wear a shovel hat when the Bishop of London was our racket; but I thought the hat began to feel too hot, so I shovelled it off. There was plenty of paper that would have suited to work with a cardinal&lsquo;s hat. There was <num value="1">one</num>,&mdash;&lsquo;Cardinal Wiseman&lsquo;s Lament,&rsquo;&mdash;and it was giving his own words like, and a red hat would have capped it. It used to make the people roar when it came to snivelling, and grumbling at little Jack Russell &mdash;by Wiseman, in course; and when it comes to this part&mdash;which alludes to that &lsquo;ere thundering letter to the Bishop of Durham&mdash;the people was stunned: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>He called me a buffalo, bull, and a monkey, 
<L>And then with a soldier called Old Arthur conkey 
<L>Declared they would buy me a ninepenny donkey, 
<L>And send me to Rome to the Pope.</quote>
 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>They shod me, sir. <hi rend=italics>Who&lsquo;s</hi> they? Why, the Pope and Cardinal Wiseman. I call my clothes after them I earn money by to buy them with. My shoes I call Pope Pius; my trowsers and braces, Calcraft; my waistcoat and shirt, Jael Denny; and my coat, Love Letters. A man must show a sense of gratitude in the best way he can. But I didn&lsquo;t start the cardinal&lsquo;s hat; I thought it might prove disagreeable to Sir Robert Peel&lsquo;s dress lodgers.&rdquo; [What my informant said further of the Pope, I give under the head of the Chaunter.] &ldquo;There was very little doing,&rdquo; he continued, &ldquo;for some time after I gave you an account before; hardly a slum worth a crust and a pipe of tobacco to us. A slum&lsquo;s a paper fake,&mdash;make a foot-note of that, sir. I think Adelaide was the <num value="1">first</num> thing I worked after I told you of my tomfooleries. Yes it was,&mdash;her helegy. She weren&lsquo;t of no account whatsomever, and Cambridge was no better nor Adelaide. But there was poor Sir Robert Peel,&mdash;he <hi rend=italics>was</hi> some good; indeed, I think he was as good as <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day to me for the <num value="4">four</num> or <num value="5">five</num> days when he was freshest. Browns were thrown out of the windows to us, and <num value="1">one</num> copper cartridge was sent flying at us with <num value="13.50">13 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> in it, all copper, as if it had been collected. I worked Sir Robert at the West End, and in the quiet streets and squares. Certainly we had a most beautiful helegy. Well, poor gentleman, what we earned on him was some set-off to us for his starting his new regiment of the Blues&mdash;the Cook&lsquo;s Own. Not that they&lsquo;ve troubled me much. I was once before Alderman Kelly, when he was Lord Mayor, charged with obstructing, or some humbug of that sort. &lsquo;What are you, my man?&rsquo; says he quietly, and like a gentleman. &lsquo;In the same line as yourself, my lord,&rsquo; says I. &lsquo;How&lsquo;s that?&rsquo; says he. &lsquo;I&lsquo;m a paper-worker for my living, my lord,&rsquo; says I. I was soon discharged; and there was such fun and laughing, that if I&lsquo;d had a few slums in my pocket, I believe I could have sold them all in the justice-room. 
<p>Haynau was a stunner, and the drayman came their caper just in the critical time for us, as things was growing very taper. But I did best with him in chaunting; and so, as you want to hear about chaunting, I&lsquo;ll tell you after. We&lsquo;re forced to change our patter&mdash;<num value="1">first</num> running, then chaunting, and then standing&mdash; oftener than we used to. 
<p>Then Calcraft was pretty tidy browns. He was up for starving his mother,&mdash;and what better can you expect of a hangman? Me and my mate worked him down at Hatfield, in Essex, where his mother lives. It&lsquo;s his native, I believe. We sold her <num value="1">one</num>. She&lsquo;s a limping old body. I saw the people look at her, and they told me arterards who she was. &lsquo;How much?&rsquo; says she. &lsquo;A penny, marm,&rsquo; say I. &lsquo;Sarve him right,&rsquo; says she. We worked it, too, in the street in Hoxton where he lives, and he sent out for <num value="2">two</num>, which shows he&lsquo;s a sensible sort of character in some points, after all. Then we had a &lsquo;Woice from the Gaol! or the Horrors <pb id="p.225" n="225"> 
<milestone unit=col>
of the Condemned Cell! Being the Life of William Calcraft, the present Hangman.&rsquo; It&lsquo;s written in the high style, and parts of it will have astonished the hangman&lsquo;s nerves before this. Here&lsquo;s a bit of the patter, now: 
<p>Let us look at William Calcraft,&rdquo; says the eminent author, &ldquo;in his earliest days. He was born about the year <datestruct value="1801"><year reg="1801">1801</year></datestruct>, of humble but industrious parents, at a little village in Essex. His infant ears often listened to the children belonging to the Sunday schools of his native place, singing the well-known words of Watt&lsquo;s beautiful hymn, 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>When e&lsquo;er I take my walks abroad, 
<L>How many poor I see, &amp;c.</quote>

<p>But alas for the poor farmer&lsquo;s boy, he never had the opportunity of going to that school to be taught how to shun &lsquo;the broad way leading to destruction.&rsquo; To seek a chance fortune he travelled up to London where his ignorance and folorn condition shortly enabled that fell demon which ever haunts the footsteps of the wretched, to mark him for her own.&rdquo; 
<p>&ldquo;Isn&lsquo;t that stunning, sir? Here it is in print for you. &lsquo;Mark him for her own!&rsquo; Then, poor dear, he&lsquo;s so sorry to hang anybody. Here&lsquo;s another bit: 
<p>&lsquo;But in vain he repents, he has no real friend in the world but his wife, to whom he can communicate his private thoughts, and in return receive consolation, can any lot be harder than this? Hence his nervous system is fast breaking down, every day rendering him less able to endure the excruciating and agonizing torments he is hourly suffering, he is haunted by remorse heaped upon remorse, every fresh victim he is required to strangle being so much additional fuel thrown upon that mental flame which is scorching him.&rsquo; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>You may believe me, sir, and I can prove the fact&mdash;the author of that beautiful writing ain&lsquo;t in parliament! Think of the mental flame, sir! O, dear.</QUOTE>
 
<p>&ldquo;Sirrell was no good either. Not salt to a herring. Though we worked him in his own neighbourhood, and pattered about gold and silver all in a row. &lsquo;Ah!&rsquo; says <num value="1">one</num> old woman, &lsquo;he was a &lsquo;spectable man.&rsquo; &lsquo;Werry, marm,&rsquo; says I. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Hollest weren&lsquo;t no good either, &lsquo;cause the wictim was a parson. If it had happened a little later, <hi rend=italics>we&lsquo;d</hi> have had it to rights; the newspapers didn&lsquo;t make much of it. We&lsquo;d have shown it was the &lsquo;Commencement of a Most Horrid and Barbarious Plot got up by the Pope and Cardinal Wiseman <hi rend=italics>for-r</hi> the Mas-ser-cree-ing of all good Protestant Ministers.&rsquo; That would have been the dodge, sir! A beautiful idear, now, isn&lsquo;t it? But the murder came off badly, and you can&lsquo;t expect fellows like them murderers to have any regard for the interest of art and literature. Then there&lsquo;s so long to wait between the murder and the trial, that unless the fiend in human form keeps writing beautiful loveletters, the excitement can&lsquo;t be kept up. <hi rend=italics>We</hi>
can write the love-letters for the fiend in human? That&lsquo;s quite true, and we once had a great pull that way over the newspapers. But Lord love you, there&lsquo;s plenty of &lsquo;em gets more and more into our line. They treads in our footsteps, sir; they follows our bright example. O! isn&lsquo;t there <hi rend=italics>a</hi> nice rubbing and polishing up. This 
<milestone unit=col>
here copy won&lsquo;t do. This must be left out, and that put in; &lsquo;cause it suits the walk of the paper. Why, you must know, sir. <hi rend=italics>I</hi> know. Don&lsquo;t tell me. You can&lsquo;t have been on the <hi rend=italics>Morning Chronicle</hi> for nothing. 
<p>Then there was the &lsquo;Horrid and Inhuman Murder, Committed by T. Drory, on the Body of Jael Denny, at Donninghurst, a Village in Essex.&rsquo; We worked it in every way. Drory had every chance given to him. We had halfsheets, and copies of werses, and books. A very tidy book it was, setting off with showing how &lsquo;The secluded village of Donninghurst has been the scene of a most determined and diabolical murder, the discovery of which early on Sunday, the <num value="12">12th</num>, in the morning has thrown the whole of this part of the country into a painful state of excitement.&rsquo; Well, sir, well&mdash;very well; that bit was taken from a newspaper. Oh, we&lsquo;re not above acknowledging when we condescends to borrow from any of &lsquo;em. If you remember, when I saw you about the time, I told you I thought Jael Denny would turn out as good as Maria Martin. And without any joke or nonsense, sir, it really is a most shocking thing. But she didn&lsquo;t. The weather coopered her, poor lass! There was money in sight, and we couldn&lsquo;t touch it; it seemed washed away from us, for you may remember how wet it was. I made a little by her, though. For all that, I haven&lsquo;t done with Master Drory yet. If God spares my life, he shall make it up to me. Why, now, sir, is it reasonable, that a poor man like me should take so much pains to make Drory&lsquo;s name known all over the country, and walk miles and miles in the rain to do it, and get only a few bob for my labour? It can&lsquo;t be thought on. When the Wile and Inhuman Seducer takes his trial, he must pay up my just claims. I&lsquo;m not going to take all that trouble on his account, and let him off so easy.</QUOTE>
 
<p>My informant then gave me an account of his sale of papers relating to the Pope and Cardinal Wiseman, but as he was then a chaunter, rather than a patterer (the distinction is shown under another head), I give his characteristic account, as the statement of a chaunter. He proceeded after having finished his recital of the street business relating to the Pope, &amp;c.: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>My last paying caper was the Sloanes. They beat Haynau. I declare to you, sir, the knowingest among us couldn&lsquo;t have invented a cock to equal the conduct of them Sloanes. Why, it&lsquo;s disgusting to come near the plain truth about them. I think, take it altogether, Sloane was as good as the Pope, but he had a stopper like Pius the <num value="9">Ninth</num>, for that was a <num value="1">one</num>-sided affair, and the Catholics wouldn&lsquo;t buy; and Sloane was too disgusting for the gentry, or better sort, to buy him. But I&lsquo;ve been in little streets where some of the windows was without sashes, and some that had sashes had stockings thrust between the frames, and I&lsquo;ve taken half a bob in ha&lsquo;pennies. Oh! you should have heard what poor women said about <pb id="p.226" n="226"> 
<milestone unit=col>
him, for it was women that bought him most They was more savage against him than against her. Why, they had <num value="50">fifty</num> deaths for him. Rolling in a barrel, with lots of sharp nails inside, down Primrose-hill, and turned out to the women on Kennington-common, and boiled alive in oil or stuff that can&lsquo;t be mentioned, or hung over a slow fire. &lsquo;O, the poor dear girl,&rsquo; says they, &lsquo;what she&lsquo;s suffered.&rsquo; We had accounts of Mistress Sloane&lsquo;s apprehension before the papers. We had it at Jersey, and they had it at Boulogne, but we were <num value="1">first</num>. Then we discovered, because we 
<hi rend=italics>must</hi> be in advance of the papers, that Miss Devaux was Sloane&lsquo;s daughter by a former wife, and Jane Wilbred was Mrs. Sloane&lsquo;s daughter by a former husband, and was entitled to <num value="1000">1,000</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> by rights. Haynau was a fool to Sloane. 
<p>I don&lsquo;t know of anything fresh that&lsquo;s in hand, sir. <num value="1">One</num> of our authors is coming out with something spicy, against Lord John, for doing nothing about Wiseman; &lsquo;cause he says as no <num value="1">one</num> thing that he&lsquo;s written for Lord John ever sold well, something against him may.</QUOTE>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.164"><head>Of the Chaunters.</head>

<p>&ldquo;AS the minstrel&lsquo;s art,&rdquo; writes Mr. Strutt, in his &ldquo;Sports and Pastimes,&rdquo; &ldquo;consisted of several branches, the professors were distinguished by different denominations, as &lsquo;rimours, <hi rend=italics>chanterres</hi>, conteours, jougleours or jongleurs, jestours, lecours, and troubadours or trouvers:&rsquo; in modern language, rhymers, singers, story-tellers, jugglers, relaters of heroic actions, buffoons, and poets; but all of them were included under the general name of minstrel. An eminent French antiquary says of the minstrels, that some of them themselves composed the subjects they sang or related, as the trouvers and the conteurs; and some of them used the compositions of others, as the jougleours and the chanteurs. He further remarks, that the trouvers may be said to have embellished their productions with rhyme, while the conteurs related their histories in prose; the jougleours, who in the middle ages were famous for playing upon the vielle&rdquo; [a kind of hurdy-gurdy], &ldquo;accompanied the songs of the trouvers. These jougleours were also assisted by the chanteurs; and this union of talents rendered the compositions more harmonious and more pleasing to the auditory, and increased their rewards, so that they readily joined each other, and travelled together in large parties. It is, however, very certain that the poet, the songster, and the musician were frequently united in the same person.&rdquo; My account of the authors, &amp;c., of street literature shows that the analogy still holds. 
<p>The French antiquary quoted was Fauchet, in his &ldquo;Origine de la Langue et Po&euml;sie Fran- &ccedil;oise&rdquo; (<datestruct value="1581--"><year reg="1581">1581</year></datestruct>); and though he wrote concerning his own country, his descriptions apply equally to the English minstrels, who were principally Normans, for many reigns after the Conquest, and were of the same race, and habits, and manners as on the French side of the Channel. 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>Of the minstrels, I shall have more to say when I treat of the ballad-singers and the bands of street and public-house musicians of to-day, between whom and the minstrels of old there is, in many respects, a somewhat close resemblance. Minstrelsy fell gradually from its high estate, and fell so low that, in the <num value="39">39th</num> year of Elizabeth&lsquo;s reign&mdash;a period when the noblest poetry of any language was beginning to command the ear of the educated in England&mdash;the minstrels were classed in a penal statute with rogues, vagabonds, and sturdy beggars! Putenham, in his &ldquo;Arte of English Poesie&rdquo; (<datestruct value="1589--"><year reg="1589">1589</year></datestruct>), speaks of &ldquo;taverne minstrels that give a fit of mirth for a groat.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> of the statutes enacted in Cromwell&lsquo;s Protectorate was directed against all persons &ldquo;commonly called fidlers or minstrells.&rdquo; 
<p>In the old times, then, the jougeleurs and jestours were assisted by the chanteurs. In the present day the running patterer&mdash;who, as I have shown, is the sufficiently legitimate descendant of the jestour, and in some respects of the mountebank&mdash;is accompanied generally by a chaunter, so presenting a further point of resemblance between ancient and modern streetfolk. The chaunter now not only sings, but fiddles, for within these few years the running patterers, to render their performances more attractive, are sometimes accompanied by musicians. The running performer then, instead of hurrying along with the members of his mob, making sufficient noise to arouse a whole street, takes his stand with the chaunter in any promising place, and as the songs which are the most popular are&mdash;as is the case at many of the concert-rooms&mdash;sometimes &ldquo;spoken&rdquo; as well as sung, the performers are in their proper capacity, for the patterer not only &ldquo;speaks,&rdquo; but speaks more than is set down for him, while the chaunter fiddles and sings. Sometimes the <num value="1">one</num> patters while the other sings, and their themes are the same. 
<p>I am told, however, that there are only <num value="50">fifty</num> running patterers who are regularly their own chaunters, fiddling to their songs, while the mob work as usual, or <num value="1">one</num> man sings, or speaks and sings, with the chaunter. <num value="2">Two</num> of these men are known as Brummagem Jack, and the Country Paganini. From <num value="20">twenty</num> to <num value="30">thirty</num> patterers, however, are chaunters also, when they think the occasion requires it. 
<p>Further to elucidate chaunting, and to show the quality of the canticles, and the way of proceeding, I cite a statement of his experience as a chaunter, from the running patterer, whose details of his more especial business I have already given, but who also occasionally chaunts:&mdash; 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.165"><head>Of the Experience of a Chaunter.</head>
 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>THE Pope, sir,&rdquo; he began, &ldquo;was as onesided to chaunt as to patter, in course. We had the Greeks (the lately-arrived Irish) down upon us more than once. In Liverpool-street, on the night of the meeting at Guildhall about <pb id="p.227" n="227"> 
<milestone unit=col>
the Papal Aggression, we had a regular skrimmage. <num value="1">One</num> gentleman said: &lsquo;Really, you shouldn&lsquo;t sing such improper songs, my men.&rsquo; Then up comes another, and he was a little orusted with port wine, and he says: &lsquo;What, against that cove the Pope! Here, give me half a dozen of the papers.&rsquo; The city was tidy for the patter, sir, or the chaunt; there was sixpences; but there was shillings at the West End. And for the <num value="1">first</num> time in their innocent lives, the parsons came out as stunning patrons of the patter. <num value="1">One</num> of &lsquo;em as we was at work in the street give a bit of a signal and was attended to without any parade to the next street, and was good for half-a-crown! Other <num value="2">two</num> stopped, that wery same day, and sent a boy to us with a Joey. Then me and my mate went to the Rev. W.&lsquo;s, him as came it so strong for the fire-works on the <datestruct VALUE="-11-5"><day reg="5">Fifth</day> of <month reg="11">November</month></datestruct>. And we pattered and we pattered, and we chaunted and we chaunted, but no go for a goodish bit. His servant said he weren&lsquo;t at home. In course <hi rend=italics>that</hi> wouldn&lsquo;t do for us, so down he came his-self at last, and says, werry soft: &lsquo;Come to-morrow morning, my men, and there&lsquo;ll be <num value="2">two</num> gentlemen to hear you.&rsquo; We stuck to him for something in hand, but he said the business had cost him so much already, he really couldn&lsquo;t. Well, we bounced a bob out of him, and didn&lsquo;t go near him again. After all we did for his party, a shilling was black ingratitude. Of course <hi rend=italics>we</hi> has no feeling either for or agin the Pope. <hi rend=italics>We</hi> goes to it as at an election; and let me tell you, sir, we got very poorly paid, it couldn&lsquo;t be called paid, for working for Lord John at the City Election; and I was the original of the live rats, which took well. But there&lsquo;s a good time coming to pay Lord Johnny off. 
<p>Some of the tunes&mdash;there&lsquo;s no act of parliament about tunes, you know, sir&mdash;was stunners on the fiddle; as if a <num value="1000">thousand</num> bricks was falling out of a cart at once. I think &lsquo;The Pope and Cardinal Wiseman,&rsquo; <num value="1">one</num> of the <num value="1">first</num> of the songs, did as well as any. This werse was greatly admired:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><LG type=stanza><L>Now Lord John Russell did so bright, 
<L>to the Bishop of Durham a letter write 
<L>Saying while I&lsquo;ve a hand I&lsquo;ll fight, 
<L>The pope and cardinal wiseman, 
<L>Lord John&lsquo;s ancestor as I tell, 
<L>Lord William Russell then known well 
<L>His true religion would not sell, 
<L>A martyr he in glory fell, 
<L>And now Lord John so bold and free, 
<L>Has got a rope as we may see, 
<L>To hang up on each side of a tree, 
<L>The pope and cardinal wiseman.</quote>

<p>This finishing werse, too, was effective, and out came a few browns:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><LG type=stanza><L>Now we don&lsquo;t care a fig for Rome, 
<L>why can&lsquo;t they let the girls alone, 
<L>And mind their business at home, 
<L>the pope and cardinal wiseman. 
<L>With their monsical red cardinals hat, 
<L>And lots of wafers in a sack, 
<L>If they come here with all their clack, 
<L>we&lsquo;ll wound them fil fal la ra whack, 
<L>In England they shall not be loose, 
<L>Their hum bugging is all no use, 
<milestone unit=col>

<L>If they come here we&lsquo;ll cook their goose, 
<L>The pope and Cardinal Wiseman. 
<LG type=stanza><head>Chorus</head>

<L>Monks and Nuns and fools afloat, 
<L>We&lsquo;ll have no bulls shoved down our throat, 
<L>Cheer up and shout down with the Pope, 
<L>And his bishop cardinal Wiseman.</quote>

<p>Then there was another, sir. &lsquo;The Pope he is coming; oh, crikey, oh dear!&rsquo; to the tune of the &lsquo;Camels are coming.&rsquo; There was <num value="1">one</num> bit that used to tickle them. I mayn&lsquo;t exactly remember it, for I didn&lsquo;t do anything beyond a spurt in it, and haven&lsquo;t a copy for you, but it tickled &lsquo;em with others. This was the bit:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><L>I&lsquo;ve heard my old grandmother&lsquo;s grandmother say, 
<L>They burnt us in Smithfield full <num value="10">ten</num> every day. 
<L>O, what shall I do, for I feel very queer, 
<L>The Pope he&lsquo;s a-coming, oh! crikey, oh, dear!</quote>

<p>Bless you, sir, if I see a smart dressed servant girl looking shyly out of the street-door at us, or through the area railings, and I can get a respectful word in and say, &lsquo;My good young lady, do buy of a poor fellow, we haven&lsquo;t said a word to your servants, we hasn&lsquo;t seen any on &lsquo;em,&rsquo; then she&lsquo;s had, sir, for <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> at least, and twice out of thrice; that &lsquo;good young lady&rsquo; chloroforms her. 
<p>Then this <num value="1">one</num>, now, is stunning. It&lsquo;s part of what the Queen was a going to sing at the opening of the parliament, but she changed her mind, and more&lsquo;s the pity, for it would have had a grand effect. It&lsquo;s called &lsquo;The Queen, the Pope, and the Parliament,&rsquo; and these is the best of the stanzas; I calls them werses in common, but stanzas for Wick: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><LG type=stanza><L>My lords and my gentlemen all, 
<L>The bishops and great house of commons 
<L>On you for protection I call, 
<L>For you know I am only a woman, 
<L>I am really quite happy indeed&mdash; 
<L>To meet you like birds of a feather, 
<L>So I hope you will all struggle with me, 
<L>And pull away boys altogether, 
<L>My name is Victoria the Queen. 
</LG><LG type=stanza><L>Our bishops and deans did relent, 
<L>And say they for ever was undone, 
<L>Bishop Philpott a long challenge sent 
<L>To his lordship the bishop of London, 
<L>To fight him on Hounslow Heath&mdash; 
<L>But the bishop of London was coosey, 
<L>He gave him <num value="1">one</num> slap in the mouth, 
<L>And then sent a letter to pusey, 
<L>No humbuggery stories for vick&mdash; 
</LG><LG type=stanza><L>I heard my old grandfather say 
<L>His great grandmother easily loved reckon 
<L>When they made a fool run away, 
<L>Whose name was king Jemmy the <num value="2">second</num>. 
<L>Billy gave him a ticket for soup, 
<L>Though Bill married old Jemmy&lsquo;s daughter 
<L>He knocked him from old Palace yard, 
<L>To Ireland, across the Boyne water, 
<L>Long life to Victoria the Queen. 
</LG><LG type=stanza><L>Come here my old friend Joey Hume, 
<L>I know you in silence wont mope now, 
<L>Go up and get inside the moon 
<L>And make fast a great torry rope now, 
<L>And then give a spring and a jump 
<L>And you to a peerage shall rise then, 
<L>For we&lsquo;ll swing up old Pius the Pope 
<L>And his eminence cardinal Wiseman, 
<L>Old England and down with the Pope.</quote>
 <pb id="p.228" n="228"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>Then there wasn&lsquo;t no risk with Haynau&mdash;I told you of the Pope <num value="1">first</num>, &lsquo;cause he was most chaunted&mdash;no fear of a <hi rend=italics>ferricadouzer</hi> for the butcher. How is it spelled, sir? Well, if you can&lsquo;t find it in the dictionary, you must use your own judgment. What does it mean? It means a dewskitch (a good thrashing). I&lsquo;ve been threatened with dark nights about the Pope, after the Greeks has said: &lsquo;Fat have you to say agin the holy gintleman? To the divil wid all the likes o&rsquo; ye.&rsquo; Haynau was a fair stage and no favour. This werse was best liked:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><LG type=stanza><L>The other day as you must know, 
<L>In Barclay&lsquo;s brewhouse he did go 
<L>And signed his bloody name &ldquo;Haynau. 
<L>The fellow that flogged the women. 
<L>Baron Rothchild did him shend, 
<L>And in the letter which he penn&lsquo;d 
<L>He shaid the sheneral wash his friend, 
<L>And so good a man he could not mend. 
<LG type=stanza><head>Chorus</head>

<L>Rumpsey bumsy&mdash;bang him well&mdash; 
<L>Make his back and sides to swell 
<L>Till he roars aloud with dreadful yell, 
<L>The fellow that flogged the women.</quote>

<p>The women bought very free; poor women, mostly; we only worked him to any extent in the back drags. <num value="1">One</num> old body at Stepney was so pleased that she said, &lsquo;O, the bloodyminded willain! Whenever you come this way again, sir, there&lsquo;s always <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for you.&rsquo; She didn&lsquo;t pay in advance though. 
<p>Then it ended, sir, with a beautiful moral as appeals to every female bosom:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=stanza><LG type=couplet><L>That man who would a female harm, 
<L>Is never fit to live.</quote>

<p>We always likes something for the ladies, bless &lsquo;em. They&lsquo;re our best customers. 
<p>Then there was poor Jael Denny, but she was humped, sir, and I&lsquo;ve told you the reason. Her copy of werses began:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><LG type=couplet><LG type=stanza><L>Since Corder died on Buystree, 
<L>No mortal man did read or see, 
<L>Of such a dreadful tragedy, 
<L>As I will now unfold. 
<L>A maid in bloom&mdash;to her silent tomb, 
<L>Is hurried in the prime of life, 
<L>How could a villain cause such strife 
<L>She worthy was a famous wife. 
<L>The like was seldom told. 
<LG type=stanza><head>Chorus.</head>

<L>She was young and gay, 
<L>Like the flowers of may, 
<L>In youth and vigour health and bloom, 
<L>She is hurried to the silent tomb. 
<L>Through Essex, such a dreadfull gloom, 
<L>Jael Denny&lsquo;s murder caused.</quote>

<p>My last chaunt was Jane Wilbred; and her werses&mdash;and they did tidy well&mdash;began:&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>A Case like this you seldom read, 
<L>Or <num value="1">one</num> so sad and true, 
<L>And we sincerely hope the perper- 
<L>trators both will rue 
<L>To serve a friendless servant girl, 
<L><num value="2">Two</num> years they did engage, 
<L>Her name it is Jane Willbred, 
<L>And eighteen years of age.</quote>

<p>What do you think of the Great Exhibition, sir? I shall be there. Me and my 
<milestone unit=col>
mates. We are going to send in a copy of werses in letters of gold for a prize. <hi rend=italics>We&lsquo;ll</hi>
let the foreigners know what the real native melodies of England is, and no mistake.</QUOTE>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.166"><head>Of the Death and Fire Hunters.</head>

<p>I have described the particular business of the running patterer, who is known by another and a very expressive cognomen&mdash;as a &ldquo;Death Hunter.&rdquo; This title refers not only to his vending accounts of all the murders that become topics of public conversation, but to his being a &ldquo;murderer&rdquo; on his own account, as in the sale of &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; mentioned incidentally in this narrative. If the truth be saleable, a running patterer prefers selling the truth, for then&mdash;as <num value="1">one</num> man told me&mdash;he can &ldquo;go the same round comfortably another day.&rdquo; If there be no truths for sale&mdash;no stories of criminals&rsquo; lives and loves to be condensed from the diffusive biographies in the newspapers&mdash;no &ldquo;helegy&rdquo; for a great man gone&mdash;no prophecy and no crim. con.&mdash;the death hunter invents, or rather announces, them. He puts some <num value="1">one</num> to death for the occasion, which is called &ldquo;a cock.&rdquo; The paper he sells may give the dreadful details, or it may be a religious tract, &ldquo;brought out in mistake,&rdquo; should the vendor be questioned on the subject; or else the poor fellow puts on a bewildered look and murmurs, &ldquo;O, it&lsquo;s shocking to be done this way&mdash;but I can&lsquo;t read.&rdquo; The patterers pass along so rapidly that this detection rarely happens. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> man told me that in the last <num value="8">eight</num> or <num value="10">ten</num> years, he, either singly or with his &ldquo;mob,&rdquo; had twice put the Duke of Wellington to death, once by a fall from his horse, and the other time by a &ldquo;sudden and myst-<hi rend=italics>e</hi>rious&rdquo; death, without any condescension to particulars. He had twice performed the same mortal office for Louis Phillipe, before that potentate&lsquo;s departure from France; each death was by the hands of an assassin; &ldquo;<num value="1">one</num> was stabbing, and the other a shot from a distance.&rdquo; He once thought of poisoning the Pope, but was afraid of the street Irish. He broke Prince Albert&lsquo;s leg, or arm, (he was not sure which), when his royal highness was out with his harriers. He never had much to say about the Queen; &ldquo;it wouldn&lsquo;t go down,&rdquo; he thought, and perhaps nothing had lately been said. &ldquo;Stop, there, sir,&rdquo; said another patterer, of whom I inquired as to the correctness of those statements, (after my constant custom in sifting each subject thoroughly,) &ldquo;stop, stop, sir. I <hi rend=italics>have</hi> had to say about the Queen lately. In coorse, nothing can be said against her, and nothing ought to; that&lsquo;s true enough, but the last time she was confined, I cried her <hi rend=italics>accouchement</hi> (the word was pronounced as spelt to a merely English reader, or rather more broadly) of <hi rend=italics><num value="3">three</num>!</hi> Lord love you, sir, it would have been no use crying <hi rend=italics><num value="1">one</num>;</hi> people&lsquo;s so used to that; but a Bobby came up and he stops me, and said it was some impudence about the Queen&lsquo;s <hi rend=italics>coachman!</hi> Why look at it, says I, fat-head&mdash;I knew I was safe&mdash;and see if there&lsquo;s <pb id="p.229" n="229"> 
<milestone unit=col>
anything in it about the Queen or her coachman! And he looked, and in coorse there was nothing. I forget just now what the paper <hi rend=italics>was</hi>
about.&rdquo; My <num value="1">first</num>-mentioned informant had apprehended Feargus O&lsquo;Connor on a charge of high treason. He assassinated Louis Napoleon, &ldquo;from a <hi rend=italics><num value="4">fourth</num></hi> edition of the <hi rend=italics>Times</hi>,&rdquo; which &ldquo;did well.&rdquo; He caused Marshal Haynau to die of the assault by the draymen. He made Rush hang himself in prison. He killed Jane Wilbred, and put Mrs. Sloane to death; and he announced the discovery that Jane Wilbred was Mrs. Sloane&lsquo;s daughter. 
<p>This informant did not represent that he had originated these little pieces of intelligence, only that he had been a party to their sale, and a party to originating <num value="1">one</num> or <num value="2">two</num>. Another patterer and of a higher order of genius&mdash;told me that all which was stated was undoubtedly correct, &ldquo;but me and my mates, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;did Haynau in another style. A splendid slum, sir! Capital! We assassinated him&mdash;<hi rend=italics>mys</hi>te- rious. Then about Rush. His hanging hisself in prison was a fake, I know; but we&lsquo;ve had him lately. His ghost appeared&mdash;as is shown in the Australian papers&mdash;to Emily Sandford, and threatened her; and took her by the neck, and there&lsquo;s the red marks of his fingers to be seen on her neck to this day!&rdquo; The same informant was so loud in his praise of the &ldquo;Asssass-sina- tion&rdquo; of Haynau that I give the account. I have little doubt it was his own writing. It is confused in passages, and has a blending of the &ldquo;I&rdquo; and the &ldquo;we:&rdquo;&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote>We have just received upon undisputed authority, that, that savage and unmanly tyrant, that enemy to civil and religious liberty, the inhuman Haynau has at last finished his career of guilt by the hand of an assassin, the term assassin I have no doubt will greet harshly upon the ears of some of our readers, yet never the less I am compelled to use it although I would gladly say the <hi rend=italics>average</hi> of outraged innocence, which would be a name more suitable to <num value="1">one</num> who has been the means of ridden the world of such a despicable monster.</QUOTE>

<p>[My informant complained bitterly, and not without reason, of the printer. &ldquo;Average,&rdquo; for instance (which I have <hi rend=italics>italicised</hi>), should be &ldquo;avenger.&rdquo; The &ldquo;average of outraged innocence!&rdquo;] 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote>It appears by the Columns of the Corour le Constituonal of Brussels,&rdquo; runs the paper, &ldquo;that the evening before last, <num value="3">three</num> men <num value="1">one</num> of which is supposed to be the miscreant, Haynau entered a Cafe in the Neighbourhood of Brussels kept by a man in the name of Priduex, and after partaking of some refreshments which were ordered by his <num value="2">two</num> companions they desired to be shown to their chambers, during their stay in the public or Travellers Room, they spoke but little and seemed to be very cautious as to joining in the conversations which was passing briskly round the festive board, which to use the landlord&lsquo;s own words was rather strange, as his Cafe was mostly frequented by a set of jovial fellows, M. Priduex goes on to state that after the <num value="3">three</num> strangers had retired to rest some time a tall and rather noble looking man enveloped in a large cloak entered and asked for a bed, and after calling for some wine he took up a paper and appeared to be reading it very attentively, in due time he was shown to bed and all passed on without any appearance of anything wrong until about <num value="6">6</num> o&lsquo;clock in the morning, when the landlord and his family, were roused by a noise over head and cries of murder, and 
<milestone unit=col>
upon going up stairs to ascertain the cause, he discovered the person who was [known] to be Marshal Haynau, lying on his bed with his throat cut in a frightful manner, and his <num value="2">two</num> companions standing by his bed side bewailing his loss. On the table was discovered a card, on which was written these words &lsquo;Monster, I am avenged at last. Suspicion went upon the tall stranger, who was not anywhere to be found, the Garde arms instantly were on the alert, and are now in active persuit of him but up to the time of our going to press nothing further has transpired.</QUOTE>
 
<p>It is very easy to stigmatise the death-hunter when he sets off all the attractions of a real or pretended murder,&mdash;when he displays on a board, as does the standing patterer, &ldquo;illustrations&rdquo; of &ldquo;the &lsquo;dentical pick-axe&rdquo; of Manning, or the stable of Good,&mdash;or when he invents or embellishes atrocities which excite the public mind. He does, however, but follow in the path of those who are looked up to as &ldquo;the press,&rdquo;&mdash;as the &ldquo;<num value="4">fourth</num> estate.&rdquo; The conductors of the 
<hi rend=italics>Lady&lsquo;s Newspaper</hi> sent an artist to Paris to give drawings of the scene of the murder by the Duc de Praslin,&mdash;to &ldquo;illustrate&rdquo; the bloodstains in the duchess&lsquo;s bed--chamber. The 
<hi rend=italics>Illustrated London News</hi> is prompt in depicting the locality of any atrocity over which the curious in crime may gloat. The <hi rend=italics>Observer</hi>, in costly advertisements, boasts of its <num value="20">20</num> columns (sometimes with a supplement) of details of some vulgar and mercenary bloodshed,&mdash;the details being written in a most honest deprecation of the morbid and savage tastes to which the writer is pandering. Other weekly papers have engravings&mdash;and only concerning murder &mdash;of any wretch whom vice has made notorious. Many weekly papers had expensive telegraphic despatches of Rush&lsquo;s having been hung at Norwich, which event, happily for the interest of Sunday newspapers, took place in Norwich at noon on a Saturday. [I may here remark, that the patterers laugh at telegraphs and express trains for rapidity of communication, boasting that the press strives in vain to rival 
<hi rend=italics>them</hi>,&mdash;as at a &ldquo;hanging match,&rdquo; for instance, the patterer has the full particulars, dying speech, and confession included&mdash;if a confession be feasible&mdash;ready for his customers the moment the drop falls, and while the criminal may still be struggling, at the very scene of the hanging. At a distance he sells it before the hanging. &ldquo;If the <hi rend=italics>Times</hi> was cross-examined about it,&rdquo; observed <num value="1">one</num> patterer, &ldquo;he must confess he&lsquo;s outdone, though he&lsquo;s a rich <hi rend=italics>Times</hi>, and we is poor fellows.&rdquo; But to resume&mdash;] 
<p>A penny-a-liner is reported, and without contradiction, to have made a large sum by having hurried to Jersey in Manning&lsquo;s business, and by being allowed to accompany the officers when they conducted that paltry tool of a vindictive woman from Jersey to Southampton by steamer, and from Southampton to London by &ldquo;special engine,&rdquo; as beseemed the popularity of so distinguished a rascal and homicide; and next morning the daily papers, in all the typographical honour of &ldquo;leads&rdquo; and &ldquo;a good place,&rdquo; gave details of this fellow&lsquo;s&mdash;this Manning&lsquo;s&mdash;conversation, looks, and demeanour. <pb id="p.230" n="230"> 
<milestone unit=col>
Until the &ldquo;respectable&rdquo; press become a more healthful public instructor, we have no right to blame the death-hunter, who is but an imitator &mdash;a follower&mdash;and that for a meal. So strong has this morbid feeling about criminals become, that an earl&lsquo;s daughter, who had &ldquo;an order&rdquo; to see Bedlam, would not leave the place until she had obtained Oxford&lsquo;s autograph for her album! The rich vulgar are but the poor vulgar&mdash;without an excuse for their vulgarity. 
<p>&ldquo;Next to murders, fires are tidy browns,&rdquo; I was told by a patterer experienced both in &ldquo;murders&rdquo; and &ldquo;fires.&rdquo; The burning of the old Houses of Parliament was very popular among street-sellers, and for the reason which ensures popularity to a commercial people; it was a source of profit, and was certainly made the most of. It was the work of incendiaries,&mdash; of ministers, to get rid of perplexing papers,&mdash; of government officers with troublesome accounts to balance,&mdash;of a sporting lord, for a heavy wager,&mdash;of a conspiracy of builders,&mdash;and of &ldquo;a unsuspected party.&rdquo; The older &ldquo;hands&rdquo; with whom I conversed on the subject, all agreed in stating that they &ldquo;did well&rdquo; on the fire. <num value="1">One</num> man said, &ldquo;No, sir, it wasn&lsquo;t only the working people that bought of me, but merchants and their clerks. I s&lsquo;pose they took the papers home with &lsquo;em for their wives and families, which is a cheap way of doing, as a newspaper costs <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
at least. But stop, sir,&mdash;stop; there wasn&lsquo;t no threepennies then,&mdash;nothing under <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, if they wasn&lsquo;t more; I can&lsquo;t just say, but it was better for us when newspapers was high. I never heard no sorrow expressed,&mdash;not <hi rend=italics>in</hi> the least. Some said it was a good job, and they wished the ministers was in it.&rdquo; The burning of the Royal Exchange was not quite so beneficial to the street-sellers, but &ldquo;was uncommon tidy.&rdquo; The fire at the Tower, however, was almost as great a source of profit as that of the Houses of Parliament, and the following statement shows the profit reaped. 
<p>My informant had been a gentleman&lsquo;s servant, his last place being with a gentleman in Russell-square, who went to the East Indies, and his servant was out of a situation so long that he &ldquo;parted with everything.&rdquo; When he was at the height of his distress, he went to see the fire at the Tower, as he &ldquo;had nothing better to do.&rdquo; He remained out some hours, and before he reached his lodging, men passed him, crying the full and true particulars of the fire. &ldquo;I bought <num value="1">one</num>,&rdquo; said the man, &ldquo;and changed my last shilling. It was a sudden impulse, for I saw people buy keenly. I never read it, but only looked at the printer&lsquo;s name. I went to him at the Dials, and bought some, and so I went into the paper trade. I made <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
some days, while the Tower lasted; and <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> other days, when the <num value="1">first</num> polish was off. I sold them mostly at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece at <num value="1">first</num>. It was good money then. The Tower was good, or middling good, for from <num value="14">14</num> to <num value="20">20</num> days. There was at least <num value="100">100</num> men working nothing but the 
<milestone unit=col>
Tower. There&lsquo;s no great chance of any more great buildings being burnt; worse luck. People don&lsquo;t care much about private fires. A man in this street don&lsquo;t heed so much who&lsquo;s burnt to death in the next. But the foundation-stone of the new Royal Exchange&mdash;fire led to that&mdash;was pretty fair, and portraits of Halbert went off, so that it was for <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> days as good as the Tower. Fires is our best friends next to murders, if they&lsquo;re <hi rend=italics>good</hi> fires. The hopening of the Coal Exchange was rather tidy. I&lsquo;ve been in the streets ever since, and don&lsquo;t see how I could possibly get out of them. At <num value="1">first</num> I felt a great degradation at being driven to the life. I shunned grooms and coachmen, as I might be known to them. I didn&lsquo;t care for others. That sort of feeling wears out though. I&lsquo;m a widower now, and my family feels, as I did at <num value="1">first</num>, that what I&lsquo;m doing is &lsquo;low.&rsquo; They won&lsquo;t assist&mdash; though they may give me <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> now and then&mdash;but they won&lsquo;t assist me to leave the streets. They&lsquo;ll rather blame me for going into them, though there was only that, or robbing, or starving. The fire at Ben. Caunt&lsquo;s, where the poor children was burnt to hashes, was the best of the private house fires that I&lsquo;ve worked, I think. I made <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> on it <num value="1">one</num> day. He was the champion once, and was away at a fight at the time, and it was a shocking thing, and so people bought.&rdquo; 
<p>After the burning of York Minster by Jonathan Martin, I was told by an old hand, the (street) destruction of the best known public buildings in the country was tried; such as Canterbury Cathedral, Dover Castle, the Brighton Pavilion, Edinburgh Castle, or Holyrood House&mdash;all known to &ldquo;travelling&rdquo; patterers&mdash; but the success was not sufficiently encouraging. It was no use, I was told, firing such places as Hampton Court or Windsor Castle, for unless people <hi rend=italics>saw</hi> the reflection of a great fire, they wouldn&lsquo;t buy. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.167"><head>Of the Sellers of <num value="2">Second</num> Editions.</head>

<p>THESE &ldquo;<num value="2">second</num> editions&rdquo; are, and almost universally, <num value="2">second</num> or later editions of the newspapers, morning and evening, but threefourths of the sale may be of the evening papers, and more especially of the <hi rend=italics>Globe</hi> and 
<hi rend=italics>Standard.</hi>

<p>I believe that there is not now in existence&mdash; unless it be in a workhouse and unknown to his fellows, or engaged in some other avocation and lost sight of by them&mdash;any <num value="1">one</num> who sold &ldquo;<num value="2">second</num> editions&rdquo; (the <hi rend=italics>Courier</hi> evening paper being then in the greatest demand) at the time of the Duke of York&lsquo;s Walcheren expedition, at the period of the battle of the Nile, during the continuance of the Peninsular war, or even at the battle of Waterloo. There were a few old men&mdash;some of whom had been soldiers or sailors, and others who have simulated it&mdash;surviving within these <num value="5">5</num> or <num value="6">6</num> years, and some later, who &ldquo;worked Waterloo,&rdquo; but they were swept off, I was told, by the cholera. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I was assured by a gentlemen who had a perfect remembrance of the &ldquo;<num value="2">second</num> editions</QUOTE>
 <pb id="p.231" n="231"> 
<milestone unit=col>
(as they were generally called) sold in the streets, and who had often bought them upwards of <num value="40">forty</num> years ago, that a sketch in the &ldquo;Monthly Review,&rdquo; in a notice of Scott&lsquo;s &ldquo;Lord of the Isles&rdquo; (published in <datestruct value="1815--"><year reg="1815">1815</year></datestruct>), gave the best notion he had met with of what the <num value="2">second</num> edition sale really was. At the commencement of the <num value="6">sixth</num> canto of his poem, Sir Walter, somewhat too grandiloquently, in the judgment of his reviewer, asks&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>O who, that shared them, ever shall forget 
<L>The emotions of the spirit-rousing time, 
<L>When breathless in the mart the couriers met, 
<L>Early and late, at evening and at prime?</quote>
 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Who,&rdquo; in his turn asks the reviewer, &ldquo;can avoid conjuring up the idea of men with broad sheets of foolscap, scored with &lsquo;VICTORIES&rsquo; rolled round their hats, and horns blowing loud defiance in each other&lsquo;s mouth, from the top to the bottom of Pall-mall or the Haymarket, when he reads such a passage? We actually hear the Park and Tower guns, and the clattering of <num value="10000">ten thousand</num> bells, as we read, and stop our ears from the close and sudden intrusion of some hot and <hi rend=italics>horn-fisted</hi> patriot, blowing ourselves, as well as Bonaparte to the devil!</QUOTE>
 
<p>The horn carried by these &ldquo;<hi rend=italics>horn</hi>-fisted&rdquo; men was a common tin tube, from <num value="2">two</num> to <num value="3">three</num> feet long, and hardly capable of being made to produce any sound beyond a sudden and discordant &ldquo;trump, trump.&rdquo; The men worked with papers round their hats, in a way not very dissimilar to that of the running patterers of to-day. 
<p>The &ldquo;editions&rdquo; cried by these men during the war-time often contained spurious intelligence, but for that the editors of the journals were responsible&mdash;or the stock-jobbers who had imposed upon them. Any <num value="1">one</num> who has consulted a file of newspapers of the period to which I have referred, will remember how frequent, and how false, were the announcements, or the rumours, of the deaths of Bonaparte, his brothers, or his marshals, in battle or by assassination. 
<p>As there was no man who was personally conversant with this traffic in what is emphatically enough called the &ldquo;war-time,&rdquo; I sought out an old street-patterer who had been acquainted with the older hands in the trade, whose experience stretched to the commencement of the present century, and from him I received the following account: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Oh, yes,&rdquo; he began, &ldquo;I&lsquo;ve worked &lsquo;seconds.&rsquo; We used to call the editions generally seconds, and cry them sometimes, as the <hi rend=italics>latest</hi>
editions, whatever it was. There was Jack Griffiths, sir,&mdash;now wasn&lsquo;t he a hand at a <num value="2">second</num> edition? I believe you. I do any kind of patter now myself, but I&lsquo;ve done tidy on <num value="2">second</num> editions, when seconds was to be had. Why, Jack Griffiths, sir&mdash;he&lsquo;d been a sailor and was fond of talking about the sea&mdash;Jack Griffiths&mdash;you would have liked to have heard him&mdash;Jack told me that he once took <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&mdash;it was Hyde Park way&mdash;for a <num value="2">second</num> edition of a paper when Queen Caroline&lsquo;s trial was over. Besides 
<milestone unit=col>
Jack, there was Tom Cole, called the Wooden Leg (he&lsquo;d been a soldier I believe), and Whitechapel, and Old Brummagem, and Hell-fire Jack. Hell-fire Jack was said to be something to a man that was a trainer, and a great favourite of the old Duke of Queensberry, and was called Hell-fire Dick; but I can&lsquo;t say how it was. I began to work <num value="2">second</num> editions, for the <num value="1">first</num> time when George IV. died. They went off pretty well at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a piece, and for <num value="3">three</num> or <num value="4">four</num> I got <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> If it&lsquo;s anything good I get <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> still, but very seldom any more. I always show anybody that asks that the paper 
<hi rend=italics>is</hi> just what I&lsquo;ve cried it. There&lsquo;s no regular cry; we cries what&lsquo;s up: &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>Here&lsquo;s</hi> the <num value="2">second</num> edition of the <hi rend=italics>Globe</hi> with the full perticlers of the death of his Majesty King George IV.&rsquo; We work much in the same way as the running patter. <num value="3">Three</num> of us shouts in the same spot. I was <num value="1">one</num> of <num value="3">three</num> who <num value="1">one</num> night sold <num value="5">five</num> quires, mostly <hi rend=italics>Globe</hi> and <hi rend=italics>Standard.</hi> It was at the Reform Bill time, and something about the Reform Bill. I never much heeded what the paper was about. I only wanted the patter, and soon got it. A mate, or any of us, looks out for anything good in the evening papers, to be ready. Why that night I speak of I was kept running backards and for&lsquo;ards to the newspaper offices&mdash;and how they does keep you waiting at times!&mdash;mostly the <hi rend=italics>Globe</hi> and 
<hi rend=italics>Standard;</hi> we worked them all at the West End. There&lsquo;s <num value="27">twenty-seven</num> papers to a quire, and we gave <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece for &lsquo;em and sold none, as well as I mind, for under <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> I carried them mostly under my arm or in my hat, taking care they wasn&lsquo;t spoiled. Belgravesquare way, and St. George&lsquo;s, Hanover-square way, and Hyde Park way, are the best. The City&lsquo;s no good. There&lsquo;s only sixpences there. The coffee-shops has spoiled the City, as I&lsquo;m afeard they will other parts. Murders in <num value="2">second</num> editions don&lsquo;t sell now, and aren&lsquo;t tried much, beyond a few, if there&lsquo;s a late verdict. Curviseer (Courvoisier) was tidy. The trial weren&lsquo;t over &lsquo;til evening, and I sold <num value="6">six</num> papers, and got <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> for them, to gentlemen going away by the mail. I&lsquo;ve heard that Greenacre was good in the same way, but I wasn&lsquo;t in town at the time. The French Revolution&mdash;the last <num value="1">one</num>&mdash;was certainly a fairish go. Lewis Fillup was good many ways. When he used to be shot at&mdash;if the news weren&lsquo;t too early in the day&mdash;and when he got to England, and when he was said to have got back, or to have been taken. Why, of course he wern&lsquo;t to compare with Rush in the regular patter, but he was very fair. I have nothing to say against him, and wish he was alive, and could do it all over again. Lord Brougham&lsquo;s death wern&lsquo;t worth much to us. You remember the time, I dare say, sir, when they said he killed hisself in the papers, to see what folks would say on him. The resignation of a prime minister is mostly pretty good. Lord Melbourne was, and so was Sir Robert Peel. There&lsquo;s always somebody to say, <pb id="p.232" n="232"> 
<milestone unit=col>
&lsquo;Hurra! that&lsquo;s right!&rsquo; and to buy a paper because he&lsquo;s pleased. I had a red paper in my hat when I worked the French Revolution. French news is generally liked in a fashionable drag. Irish news is no good, for people don&lsquo;t seem to believe it. Smith O&lsquo;Brien&lsquo;s battle, though, did sell a little. It&lsquo;s not possible to tell you exactly what I&lsquo;ve made on seconds. How can I? <num value="1">One</num> week I may have cleared <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> in them, and for <num value="6">six</num> months before not a blessed brown. Perhaps&mdash;as near as I can recollect and calculate&mdash;I&lsquo;ve cleared <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> (if that) each year, <num value="1">one</num> with another, in <num value="2">second</num> editions in my time, and perhaps <num value="20">twenty</num> others has done the same.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Another man who also knew the old hands said to me: &ldquo;Lord bless us, how times is changed! you should have heard Jack Griffiths tell how he cried his gazettes: &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>He-ere&lsquo;s</hi>
the <hi rend=italics>London Gazette</hi> Ex-terornary, containing the hof-ficial account of the bloody and decisive wictory of Sally-manker.&rsquo; Something that way. Patter wern&lsquo;t required then; the things sold theirselves. Why, the other day I was talking to a young chap that conceits hisself to be a hout-and-houter in patter, and I mentions Jack&lsquo;s crying <hi rend=italics>Gazettes</hi> and getting <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
apiece for many a <num value="1">one</num> on &lsquo;em, and this young chap says, says he: &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>Gazettes!</hi> What did they cry <hi rend=italics>Gazettes?</hi>&mdash;bankrupts, and all that?&rsquo; &lsquo;Bankrupts be blowed!&rsquo; said I, &lsquo;wictories!&rsquo; I heerd Waterloo cried when I was a little &lsquo;un. The speeches on the opening of parliament, which the newspapers has ready, has no sale in the crowd to what they had. I only sold <num value="2">two</num> papers at <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each this last go. I ventured on no more, or should have been a loser. If the Queen isn&lsquo;t there, none&lsquo;s sold. But we always has a speech ready, as close as can be got from what the morning papers says. <num value="1">One</num> gent. said to me: &lsquo;But that ain&lsquo;t the real speech!&rsquo; &lsquo;It&lsquo;s a far better,&rsquo; says I, and so it is. Why now, sir, there&lsquo;s some reading and spirit in this bit. The Queen says: 
<p>&lsquo;It is my determination by the assistance of divine providence to uphold and protect the Protestant Church of the British Empire, which has been enjoyed <num value="300">three hundred</num> years without interuption, the Religion which our ancestors struggled to obtain. And as long as it shall please God to spare me, I will endeavour to maintain the rights and perogatives of our holy Protestant Church. And now my Lords, I leave you to your duties, to the helm of the state, to the harbour of peace, and happiness.&rsquo;&rdquo; 
<p>This man showed me the street speech, which was on a broad sheet set off with the royal arms. The topics and arrangement were the same as those in the speech delivered by her Majesty. 
<p>On Monday morning last (<datestruct VALUE="-02-24"><month reg="02">Feb.</month> <day reg=24>24</day></datestruct>), I asked the man who told me that prime ministers&rsquo; resignations were &ldquo;pretty good&rdquo; for the street traffic, if he had been well remunerated by the sale of the evening papers of Saturday, with the account of Lord John Russell&lsquo;s resignation. &ldquo;It wern&lsquo;t tried, sir,&rdquo; he answered; &ldquo;there was nothing new in the evenings, and we thought 
<milestone unit=col>
nobody seemed to care about it. The newspaper offices and their boarders (as he called the men going about with announcements on boards) didn&lsquo;t make very much of it, so we got up a song instead; but it was no good,&mdash;not salt to a fresh herring&mdash;for there was some fresh herrings in. It was put strong, though. This was the last verse: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>From the House to the Palace it has caused a bother, 
<L>Old women are tumbling <num value="1">one</num> over another, 
<L>The Queen says it is with her, <num value="1">one</num> thing or &lsquo;tother, 
<L>They must not discharge Little John; 
<L>Her Majesty vows that she is not contented, 
<L>And many ere long will have cause to repent it, 
<L>Had she been in the house she would nobly resent it, 
<L>And fought like a brick for Lord John.&rsquo;</quote>

<p>Adopting the calculation of my <num value="1">first</num> informant, and giving a profit of <num value="150">150</num> per cent., we find <num value="150">150</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> yearly expended in the streets, in <num value="2">second</num> editions, or probably it might be more correct to say <num value="200">200</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> in a year of great events, and <num value="50">50</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> in a year when such events are few. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.168"><head>Of the Standing Patterers.</head>

<p>THE standing patterer I have already described in his resemblance to the mountebank of old, and how, like his predecessor, he required a &ldquo;pitch&rdquo; and an audience. I need but iterate that these standing patterers are men who remain in <num value="1">one</num> place, until they think they have exhausted the custom likely to accrue there, or until they are removed by the police; and who endeavour to attract attention to their papers, or more commonly pamphlets, either by means of a board with coloured pictures upon it, illustrative of the contents of what they sell, or else by gathering a crowd round about them, in giving a lively or horrible description of the papers or books they are &ldquo;working.&rdquo; The former is what is usually denominated in street technology, &ldquo;board work.&rdquo; A few of the standing patterers give street recitations or dialogues. 
<p>Some of the &ldquo;illustrations&rdquo; most &ldquo;in vogue&rdquo; of late for the boards of the standing patterers were,&mdash;the flogging of the nuns of Minsk, the blood streaming from their naked shoulders, (anything against the Emperor of Russia, I was told, was a good street subject for a painting); the young girl, Sarah Thomas, who murdered her mistress in Bristol, dragged to the gallows by the turnkeys and Calcraft, the hangman; Calcraft himself, when charged with &ldquo;starving his mother;&rdquo; Haynau, in the hands of the draymen; the Mannings, and afterwards the Sloanes. The <num value="2">two</num> last-mentioned were among the most elaborate, each having a series of &ldquo;compartments,&rdquo; representing the different stages of the events in which those heroes and heroines flourished. I shall speak afterwards of street-artists who are the painters of these boards, and then describe the pictures more fully. There are also, as before alluded to, what may be called &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; in street paintings, as well as street literature. 
<p><num value="2">Two</num> of the most favourite themes of the standing patterers were, however, the &ldquo;Annals of the White House in Soho-square,&rdquo; and the <pb id="p.233" n="233"> 
<milestone unit=col>
&ldquo;Mysteries of Mesmerism.&rdquo; Both supplied subjects to the boards. 
<p>The White House was a notorious place of ill fame. Some of the apartments, it is said, were furnished in a style of costly luxury; while others were fitted up with springs, traps, and other contrivances, so as to present no appearance other than that of an ordinary room, until the machinery was set in motion. In <num value="1">one</num> room, into which some wretched girl might be introduced, on her drawing a curtain as she would be desired, a skeleton, grinning horribly, was precipitated forward, and caught the terrified creature in his, to all appearance, bony arms. In another chamber the lights grew dim, and then seemed gradually to go out. In a little time some candles, apparently self-ignited, revealed to a horror stricken woman, a black coffin, on the lid of which might be seen, in brass letters, ANNE, or whatever name it had been ascertaind the poor wretch was known by. A sofa, in another part of the mansion, was made to descend into some place of utter darkness; or, it was alleged, into a room in which was a store of soot or ashes. 
<p>Into the truth or exaggeration of these and similar statements, it is not my business to inquire; but the standing patterer made the most of them. Although the house in question has been either rebuilt or altered&mdash;I was told that each was the case&mdash;and its abominable character has ceased to apply to it for some years, the patterer did not scruple to represent it as still in existence (though he might change the venue as to the square at discretion) and that all the atrocities perpetrated&mdash;to which I have not ventured even to allude&mdash;were still the ordinary procedures of &ldquo;high life.&rdquo; Neither did the standing patterer scruple, as <num value="1">one</num> man assured me, to &ldquo;name names;&rdquo; to attribute vile deeds to any nobleman or gentleman whose name was before the public; and to embellish his story by an allusion to a recent event. He not unfrequently ended with a moral exhortation to all ladies present to avoid this &ldquo;abode of iniquity for the rich.&rdquo; The board was illustrated with skeletons, coffins, and other horrors; but neither on it, nor in a hardly intelligible narrative which the patterer sold, was there anything indecent. 
<p>The &ldquo;Mysteries of Mesmerism&rdquo; was an account of the marvels of that &ldquo;newly-discovered and most wonderful power in natur and art.&rdquo; With it Dr. Elliotson&lsquo;s, or some well-known name, was usually associated, and any marvel was &ldquo;pattered,&rdquo; according to the patterer&lsquo;s taste and judgment. The illustrations were of persons, generally women, in a state of coma, but in this also there was no indecency; nor was there in the narrative sold. 
<p>Of these <num value="2">two</num> popular exhibitions there are, I am informed, none now in town, and both, I was told, was more the speculations of a printer, who sent out men, than in the hands of the regular patterers. 
<p>It may tend somewhat to elucidate the cha- 
<milestone unit=col>
racter of the patterers, if I here state, that in my conversation with the whole of them, I heard from their lips strong expressions of disgust at Sloane,&mdash;far stronger than were uttered in abhorrence of any murderer. Rush, indeed, was, and is, a popular man among them. <num value="1">One</num> of them told me, that not long before Madame Tussaud&lsquo;s death, he thought of calling upon that &ldquo;wenerable lady,&rdquo; and asking her, he said, &ldquo;to treat me to something to drink the immortal memory of Mr. Rush, my friend and her&lsquo;n.&rdquo; 
<p>It is admitted by all concerned in the exercise of street elocution, that &ldquo;the stander&rdquo; must have &ldquo;the best of patter.&rdquo; He usually works alone,&mdash;there are very rarely <num value="2">two</num> at standing patter,&mdash;and beyond his board he has no adventitious aids, as in the running patter, so that he must be all the more effective; but the board is pronounced &ldquo;as good as a man.&rdquo; When the standing patterer visits the country, he is accompanied by a mate, and the &ldquo;copy of werses&rdquo; is then announced as being written by an &ldquo;underpaid curate&rdquo; within a day&lsquo;s walk. &ldquo;It tells mostly, sir,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> man; &ldquo;for it&lsquo;s a blessing to us that there always is a journeyman parson what the people knows, and what the patter fits.&rdquo; Sometimes the poetry is attributed to a sister of mercy, or to a popular poetess; very frequently, by the patterers who best understand the labouring classes, to Miss Eliza Cook. Sometimes the verses are written by &ldquo;a sympathising gent. in that parish,&rdquo; but his name wasn&lsquo;t to be mentioned. Another intelligent patterer whom I questioned on the subject, told me that my information was correct. &ldquo;It&lsquo;s just the same in the newspapers,&rdquo; he continued; &ldquo;why the &lsquo;sympathising gent.&rsquo; is the same with us as what in the newspapers is called &ldquo;other intelligence (about any crime), to publish which might defeat the ends of justice.&rdquo; That means, they know nothing at all about it, and can&lsquo;t so much as venture on a guess. I&lsquo;ve known a little about it for the papers, sir,&mdash;it doesn&lsquo;t matter in what line.&rdquo; 
<p>Some standing patterers are brought up to the business from childhood. Some take to it through loss of character, or through their inability to obtain a situation from intemperate habits, and some because &ldquo;a free life suits me best.&rdquo; In a former inquiry into a portion of this subject, I sought a standing patterer, whom I found in a threepenny lodging-house in Mintstreet, Southwark. On my inquiring what induced him to adopt, or pursue, that line of life, he said:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>It was distress that <num value="1">first</num> drove me to it. I had learnt to make willow bonnets, but that branch of trade went entirely out. So, having a wife and children, I was drove to write out a paper that I called &lsquo;The People&lsquo;s Address to the King on the Present State of the Nation.&rsquo; I got it printed, and took it into the streets and sold it. I did very well with it, and made <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day while it lasted. I never was brought up to any mechanical trade. My father was a cler- <pb id="p.234" n="234"> 
<milestone unit=col>
gyman&rdquo; [here he cried bitterly]. &ldquo;It breaks my heart when I think of it. I have as good a wife as ever lived, and I would give the world to get out of my present life. It would be heaven to get away from the place where I am. I am obliged to cheer up my spirits. If I was to give way to it, I shouldn&lsquo;t live long. It&lsquo;s like a little hell to be in the place where we live&rdquo; [crying], &ldquo;associated with the ruffians that we are. My distress of mind is awful, but it won&lsquo;t do to show it at my lodgings&mdash;they&lsquo;d only laugh to see me down-hearted; so I keep my trouble all to myself. Oh, I am heartily sick of this street work&mdash;the insults I have to put up with&mdash;the drunken men swearing at me. Yes, indeed, I am heartily sick of it.</QUOTE>
 
<p>This poor man had some assistance forwarded to him by benevolent persons, after his case had appeared in my letter in the <hi rend=italics>Morning Chronicle.</hi>
This was the means of his leaving the streets, and starting in the &ldquo;cloth-cap trade.&rdquo; He seemed a deserving man. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.169"><head>Experience of a Standing Patterer.</head>

<p>FROM <num value="1">one</num> of this body I received, at the period just alluded to, the following information:&mdash; 
<p>&ldquo;I have taken my <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day (said my informant); but &lsquo;paper&rsquo; selling now isn&lsquo;t half so good as it used to be. People haven&lsquo;t got the money to lay out; for it all depends with the working man. The least we take in a day is, upon an average, sixpence; but taking the good and bad together, I should say we take about <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week. I know there&lsquo;s some get more than that, but then there&lsquo;s many take less. Lately, I know, I haven&lsquo;t taken <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week myself, and people reckon me <num value="1">one</num> of the best patterers in the trade. I&lsquo;m reckoned to have the gift&mdash;that is, the gift of the gab. I never works a last dying speech on any other than the day of execution&mdash;all the edge is taken off of it after that. The last dying speeches and executions are all printed the day before. They&lsquo;re always done on the Sunday, if the murderers are to be hung on the Monday. I&lsquo;ve been and got them myself on the Sunday night, over and over again. The flying stationers goes with the papers in their pockets, and stand under the drop, and as soon as ever it falls, and long before the breath is out of the body, they begin bawling out.&rdquo; [Here my informant gave a further account of the flying stationers under the gallows, similar to what I have given. He averred that they &ldquo;invented every lie likely to go down.&rdquo;] &ldquo;&lsquo;Here you have also an exact likeness,&rsquo; they say, &lsquo;of the murderer, taken at the bar of the Old Bailey!&rsquo; when all the time it is an old wood-cut that&lsquo;s been used for every criminal for the last <num value="40">forty</num> years. I know the likeness that was given of Hocker was the <num value="1">one</num> that was given for Fauntleroy; and the wood-cut of Tawell was <num value="1">one</num> that was given for the Quaker that had been hanged for forgery <num value="20">twenty</num> years before. Thurtell&lsquo;s likeness was done expressly for the &lsquo;papers;&rsquo; and so was the Mannings&rsquo; and Rush&lsquo;s likenesses too. The murders are bought by men, 
<milestone unit=col>
women, and children. Many of the trade people bought a great many of the affair of the Mannings. I went down to Deptford with mine, and did uncommonly well. I sold all off. Gentlefolks won&lsquo;t have anything to do with murders sold in the street; they&lsquo;ve got other ways of seeing all about it. We lay on the horrors, and picture them in the highest colours we can. We don&lsquo;t care what&lsquo;s in the &lsquo;papers&rsquo; in our hands. All we want to do is to sell &lsquo;em; and the more horrible we makes the affairs, the more sale we have. We do very well with &lsquo;loveletters.&rsquo; They are &lsquo;cocks;&rsquo; that is, they are all fictitious. We give it out that they are from a tradesman in the neighbourhood, not a <num value="100">hundred</num> yards from where we are a-standing. Sometimes we say it&lsquo;s a well-known sporting butcher; sometimes it&lsquo;s a highly respectable publican&mdash; just as it will suit the tastes of the neighbourhood. I got my living round Cornwall for <num value="1">one</num> twelvemonth with nothing else than a loveletter. It was headed, &lsquo;A curious and laughable love-letter and puzzle, sent by a sporting gentleman to Miss H&mdash;s&mdash;m, in <hi rend=italics>this</hi> neighbourhood;&rsquo; that suits any place that I may chance to be in; but I always patter the name of the street or village where I may be. This letter, I say, is so worded, that had it fallen into the hands of her mamma or papa, they could not have told what it meant; but the young lady, having so much wit, found out its true meaning, and sent him an answer in the same manner. You have here, we say, the number of the house, the name of the place where she lives (there is nothing of the kind, of course), and the initials of all the parties concerned. We dare not give the real names in full, we tell them; indeed, we do all we can to get up the people&lsquo;s curiosity. I did very well with the &lsquo;Burning of the House of Commons.&rsquo; I happened by accident to put my pipe into my pocket amongst some of my papers, and burnt them. Then, not knowing how to get rid of them, I got a few straws. I told the people that my burnt papers were parliamentary documents that had been rescued from the flames, and that, as I dare not sell them, I would let them have a straw for a penny, and give them <num value="1">one</num> of the papers. By this trick I got rid of my stock twice as fast, and got double the price that I should have done. The papers had nothing at all to do with the House of Commons. Some was &lsquo;Death and the Lady,&rsquo; and &lsquo;Death and the Gentleman,&rsquo; and others were the &lsquo;Political Catechism,&rsquo; and <num value="365">365</num> lies, Scotch, English, and Irish, and each lie as big round as St. Paul&lsquo;s. I remember a party named Jack Straw, who laid a wager, half-a-gallon of beer, that he&lsquo;d bring home the money for <num value="2">two</num> dozen blank papers in <num value="1">one</num> hour&lsquo;s time. He went out into the Oldstreet- road, and began a patter about the political affairs of the nation, and Sir Robert Peel, and the Duke of Wellington, telling the public that he dared not sell his papers, they were treasonable; so he gave them with a straw&mdash;that he sold for <num value="1">one</num> penny. In less than the hour he was sold clean out, and returned and drank the beer. The <pb id="p.235" n="235"> 
<milestone unit=col>
chief things that I work are quarter-sheets of recitations and dialogues. <num value="1">One</num> is &lsquo;Good Advice to Young Men on Choosing their Wives.&rsquo; I have done exceedingly well with that&mdash;it&lsquo;s a good moral thing. Another is the &lsquo;Drunkard&lsquo;s Catechism;&rsquo; another is &lsquo;The Rent Day; or, the Landlord gathering his Rents.&rsquo; This is a dialogue between the landlord and his tenant, beginning with &lsquo;Good morning, Mrs. Longface; have you got my rent ready, ma&lsquo;am?&rsquo; The next <num value="1">one</num> is &lsquo;The Adventures of Larry O&lsquo;Flinn.&rsquo; It&lsquo;s a comic story, and a very good got-up thing. Another is &lsquo;A Hint to Husbands and Wives;&rsquo; and &lsquo;A Pack of Cards turned into a Bible, a Prayer-book, and an Almanack.&rsquo; These cards belonged to Richard Middleton, of the <num value="60">60th</num> regiment of foot, who was taken a prisoner for playing at cards in church during divine service. But the best I do is &lsquo;The Remarkable Dream of a Young Man of loose character, who had made an agreement to break into a gentleman&lsquo;s house at <num value="12">twelve</num> at night on Whitsun Monday, but, owing to a little drink that he took, he had a remarkable dream, and dreamed he was in hell. The dream had such influence on his mind that he refused to meet his comrade. His comrade was taken up for the burglary, found guilty, and executed for it. This made such an impression on the young man&lsquo;s mind that he became a reformed character.&rsquo; There is a very beautiful description of hell in this paper,&rdquo; said my informant, &ldquo;that makes it sell very well among the old women and the apprentice lads, for the young man was an apprentice himself. It&lsquo;s all in very pretty poetry, and a regular &lsquo;cock.&rsquo; The papers that I work chiefly are what are called &lsquo;the standing patters;&rsquo; they&lsquo;re all of &lsquo;em stereotype, and some of them a <num value="100">hundred</num> years old. We consider the &lsquo;death hunters&rsquo; are the lowest grade in the trade. We can make most money of the murders while they last, but they don&lsquo;t last, and they merely want a good pair of lungs to get them off. But it&lsquo;s not every <num value="1">one</num>, sir, that can work the standing patters. Many persons I&lsquo;ve seen try at it and fail. <num value="1">One</num> old man I knew tried the &lsquo;Drunkard&lsquo;s Catechism&rsquo; and the &lsquo;Soldier&lsquo;s Prayer-book and Bible.&rsquo; He could manage to patter these because they&lsquo;ll almost work themselves; but &lsquo;Old Mother Clifton&rsquo; he broke down in. I heard him do it in Sun-street and in the Blackfriars-road; but it was such a dreadful failure&mdash;he couldn&lsquo;t humour it a bit&mdash;that, thinks I to myself, you&lsquo;ll soon have to give up, and sure enough he&lsquo;s never been to the printer&lsquo;s since. He&lsquo;d a very poor audience, chiefly boys and girls, and they were laughing at him because he made so many blunders in it. A man that&lsquo;s never been to school an hour can go and patter a dying speech or &lsquo;A Battle between <num value="2">Two</num> Ladies of Fortune.&rsquo; They require no scholarship. All you want is to stick a picture on your hat, to attract attention, and to make all the noise you can. It&lsquo;s all the same when they does an &lsquo;Assassination of Louis Philippe,&rsquo; or a &lsquo;Diabolical Attempt on the Life 
<milestone unit=col>
of the Queen&rsquo;&mdash;a good stout pair of lungs and plenty of impudence is all that is required. But to patter &lsquo;Bounce, the Workhouse Beadle, and the Examination of the Paupers before the Poorlaw Commissioners,&rsquo; takes a good head-piece and great gift of the gab, let me tell you. It&lsquo;s just the same as a play-actor. I can assure you I often feel very nervous. I begin it, and walk miles before I can get confidence in myself to make the attempt. I got rid of <num value="2">two</num> quire last night. I was up among the gentlemen&lsquo;s servants in Crawford-street, Baker-street, and I had a very good haul out of the grown--up people. I cleared <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> altogether. I did that from <num value="7">seven</num> till <num value="9">nine</num> in the evening. It&lsquo;s all chancework. If it&lsquo;s fine, and I can get a crowd of grown--up people round me, I can do very well, but I can&lsquo;t do anything amongst the boys. There&lsquo;s very little to be done in the day-time. I begin at <num value="10">ten</num> in the day, and stop out till <num value="1">one</num>. After that I starts off again at <num value="5">five</num>, and leaves off about <num value="10">ten</num> at night. Marylebone, Paddington, and Westminster I find the best places. The West-end is very good the early part of the week, for any thing that&lsquo;s genteel, such as the &lsquo;Rich Man and his Wife quarrelling because they have no Family.&rsquo; Our customers there are principally the footmen, the grooms, and the maidservants. The east end of the town is the best on Friday and Saturday evenings. I very often go to Limehouse on Friday evening. Most part of the dock-men are paid then, and anything comic goes off well among them. On Saturdays I go to the New-cut, Ratcliff-highway, the Brill, and such places. I make mostly <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> clear on a Saturday night. After <num value="19">nineteen</num> years&rsquo; experience of the patter and paper line in the streets, I find that a foolish nonsensical thing will sell twice as fast as a good moral sentimental <num value="1">one</num>; and, while it lasts, a good murder will cut out the whole of them. It&lsquo;s the best selling thing of any. I used at <num value="1">one</num> time to patter religious tracts in the street, but I found no encouragement. I did the &lsquo;Infidel Blacksmith&rsquo;&mdash;that would not sell. &lsquo;What is Happiness? a Dialogue between Ellen and Mary&rsquo;&mdash;that was no go. No more was the &lsquo;Sorrows of Seduction.&rsquo; So I was driven into the comic standing patters.&rsquo; 
<p>The more recent &ldquo;experiences&rdquo; of standing patterers, as they were detailed to me, differ so little in subject, or anything else, from what I have given concerning running patterers, that to cite them would be a repetition. 
<p>From the best information to be obtained, I have no doubt that there are always at least <num value="20">20</num> standing patterers&mdash;sometimes they are called &ldquo;boardmen&rdquo;&mdash;at work in London. Some of them &ldquo;run&rdquo; occasionally, but an equal number or more, of the regular &ldquo;runners&rdquo; resort now and then to the standing patter, so the sum is generally kept up. 
<p>Notwithstanding the drawbacks of bad weather, which affects the standing, and does not affect the running, patterer; and notwithstanding the more frequent interruptions of the police, I am of opinion that the standing patterer earns <pb id="p.236" n="236"> 
<milestone unit=col>
on an average <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week more than his running brother. His earnings too are often all his own; whereas the runners are a &lsquo;school,&rsquo; and, their gains divided. More running patterers become, on favourable occasions, stationary, with boards, perhaps in the proportion of <num value="5">five</num> to <num value="4">four</num>, than the stationary become itinerant. <num value="1">One</num> standing patterer told me, that, during the excitement about the Sloanes, he cleared full <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a day for more than a week; but at other times he had cleared only <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> in a whole week, and he had taken nothing when the weather was too wet for the standing work, and there was nothing up to &ldquo;run&rdquo; with. 
<p>If, then, <num value="20">20</num> standing patterers clear <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
weekly, each, the year through&mdash;&ldquo;taking&rdquo; <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
weekly&mdash;we find that <num value="780">780</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is yearly expended in the standing patter of London streets. 
<p>The capital required for the start of the standing is greater than that needed by the running patterer. The painting for a board costs <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; the board and pole, with feet, to which it is attached, <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; and stock-money, <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; in all, <num value="11">11</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>

<div2 type=section id="c.15.170"><head>Of Political Litanies, Dialogues, etc.</head>

<p>To &ldquo;work a litany&rdquo; in the streets is considered <num value="1">one</num> of the higher exercises of professional skill on the part of the patterer. In working this, a clever patterer&mdash;who will not scruple to introduce anything out of his head which may strike him as suitable to his audience&mdash;is very particular in his choice of a mate, frequently changing his ordinary partner, who may be good &ldquo;at a noise&rdquo; or a ballad, but not have sufficient acuteness or intelligence to patter politics as if he understood what he was speaking about. I am told that there are not <num value="12">twelve</num> patterers in London whom a critical professor of street elocution will admit to be capable of &lsquo;working a catechism&rsquo; or a litany. &ldquo;Why, sir,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> patterer, &ldquo;I&lsquo;ve gone out with a mate to work a litany, and he&lsquo;s humped it in no time.&rdquo; To &lsquo;hump,&rsquo; in street parlance, is equivalent to &lsquo;botch,&rsquo; in more genteel colloquialism. &ldquo;And when a thing&lsquo;s humped,&rdquo; my informant continued, &ldquo;you can only &lsquo;call a go.&rsquo;&rdquo; To &lsquo;call a go,&rsquo; signifies to remove to another spot, or adopt some other patter, or, in short, to resort to some change or other in consequence of a failure. 
<p>An elderly man, not now in the street trade, but who had &ldquo;pattered off a few papers&rdquo; some years ago, told me that he had heard <num value="3">three</num> or <num value="4">four</num> old hands&mdash;&ldquo;now all dead, for they&lsquo;re a short-lived people&rdquo;&mdash;talk of the profits gained and the risk ran by giving Hone&lsquo;s parodies on the Catechism, Litany, St. Athanasius&rsquo; Creed, &amp;c. in the streets, after the <num value="3">three</num> consecutive trials and the <num value="3">three</num> acquittals of Hone had made the parodies famous and Hone popular. To work them in the streets was difficult, &ldquo;for though,&rdquo; said my informant, &ldquo;there was no new police in them days, there was plenty of officers and constables ready to pull the fellows up, and though Hone was acquitted, a beak that wanted to please the high dons, would find some way of stopping 
<milestone unit=col>
them that sold Hone&lsquo;s things in the street, and so next to nothing could be done that way, but a little was done.&rdquo; The greatest source of profit, I learned from the reminiscences of the same man, was in the parlours and tap-rooms of public-houses, where the patterers or reciters were well paid &ldquo;for going through their catechisms,&rdquo; and sometimes, that there might be no interruption, the door was locked, and even the landlord and his servants excluded. The charge was usually <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a copy, but <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> was not refused. 
<p>During Queen Caroline&lsquo;s trial there were the like interruptions and hindrances to similar performances; and the interruptions continued during the passing of the Catholic Emancipation Bill until about the era of the Reform Bill, and then the hindrance was but occasional. &ldquo;And perhaps it was our own fault, sir,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> patterer, &ldquo;that we was then molested at all in the dialogues and catechisms and things; but we was uncommon bold, and what plenty called sarcy, at that time: we was so.&rdquo; 
<p>Thus this branch of a street profession continued to be followed, half surreptitiously, until after the subsidence of the political ferment consequent on the establishment of a new franchise and the partial abolition of an old <num value="1">one</num>. The calling, however, has never been popular among street purchasers, and I believe that it is sometimes followed by a street-patterer as much from the promptings of the pride of art as from the hope of gain. 
<p>The street-papers in the dialogue form have not been copied nor derived from popular productions&mdash;but even in the case of Political Litanies and Anti-Corn-law Catechisms and Dialogues are the work of street authors. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> intelligent man told me, that properly to work a political litany, which referred to ecclesiastical matters, he &ldquo;made himself up,&rdquo; as well as limited means would permit, as a bishop! and &ldquo;did stunning, until he was afraid of being stunned on skilly.&rdquo; Of the late papers on the subject of the Pope, I cite the <num value="1">one</num> which was certainly the best of all that appeared, and concerning which indignant remonstrances were addressed to some of the newspapers. The &ldquo;good child&rdquo; in the patter, was a tall bulky man; the examiner (also the author), was rather diminutive:&mdash; 
<text><body><head>The old English Bull John v. the Pope&lsquo;s Bull of of Rome.</head>

<p>My good Child as it is necessary at this very important crisis; when, that good pious and very reasonable old gentleman Pope Pi-ass the nineth has promised to favor us with his presence, and the pleasures of Popery&mdash;and trampled on the rights and privilages which, we, as Englishmen, and Protestants, have engaged for these last <num value="300">three hundred</num> years&mdash; Since Bluff, king Hal. began to take a dislike to the broad brimmed hat of the venerable Cardinal Wolsey, and proclaimed himself an heretic; It is necessary I say, for you, and all of you, to be perfect in your Lessons so as you may be able to verbly chastize this saucy prelate, his newly made Cardinal Foolishman, and the whole host of Puseites and protect our beloved Queen, our Church, and our Constitution. 
<p><hi rend=italics>Q.</hi> Now my boy can you tell me what is your Name? 
<p><hi rend=italics>A.</hi> B&mdash;&mdash; Protestant. <pb id="p.237" n="237"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<p><hi rend=italics>Q.</hi> How came you by that name? 
<p><hi rend=italics>A.</hi> At the time of Harry the stout, when Popery was in a galloping consumption the people protested against the surpremacy and instalence of the Pope; and his Colleges had struck deep at the hallow tree of superstition I gained the name of Protestant, and proud am I, and ever shall be to stick to it till the day of my death. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Let us say.</QUOTE>

<p>From all Cardinals whether wise or foolish. Oh! Queen Spare us. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Spare us, Oh Queen.</QUOTE>

<p>From the pleasure of the Rack, and the friendship of the kind hearted officers of the Inquisition. Oh! Johnny hear us. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Oh! Russell hear us.</QUOTE>

<p>From the comforts of being frisled like a devil&lsquo;d kindney. Oh! Nosey save us. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Hear us Oh Arthur.</QUOTE>

<p>From such saucy Prelates, as Pope Pi-ass. Oh! Cumming&lsquo;s save us. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Save us good Cumming.</QUOTE>

<p>And let us have no more Burnings in smithfield, no more warm drinks in the shape of boiled oil, or, molten lead, and send the whole host of Pusyites along with the Pope, Cardinals to the top of mount Vesuvius there to dine off of hot lava, so that we may live in peace &amp; shout long live our Queed, and No Popery!</text>

<p>For some pitches the foregoing was sufficient, for a street auditory &ldquo;hates too long a patter;&rdquo; but where a favourable opportunity offered, easily tested by the pecuniary beginnings, the &ldquo;Lesson of the Day&rdquo; was given in addition, and was inserted after the <num value="2">second</num> &ldquo;Answer&rdquo; in the foregoing parody, so preceding the &ldquo;Let us say:&rdquo; 
<text><body><head>The Lesson of the Day.</head>

<p>You seem an intelligent lad, so I think you are quite capable of Reading with me the Lessons for this day&lsquo;s service. 
<p>Now the Lesson for the day is taken from all parts of the Book of Martyr&lsquo;s, beginning at just where you like. 
<p>It was about the year <datestruct value="1835"><year reg="1835">1835</year></datestruct>, that a certain renagade of the name of Pussy&mdash;I beg his pardon, I mean Pusey, like a snake who stung his master commenced crawling step by step, from the master; he was bound to serve to worship a puppet, arrayed in a spangle and tincel of a romish showman. 
<p>And the pestelance that he shed around spread rapidly through the minds of many unworthy members of our established Church; even up to the present year, <datestruct value="1850"><year reg="1850">1850</year></datestruct>, inasmuch that St Barnabus, of Pimlico, unable to to see the truth by the aid of his occulars, mounted <measure value="4l." type=currency><num value="4">four</num> pounds</measure> of long sixes in the mid-day, that he might see through the fog of his own folly, by which he was surrounded. 
<p>And Pope Pi-ass the nineth taking advantage of the hubub, did create unto himself a Cardinal in the person of <num value="1">one</num> Wiseman of Westminster. 
<p>And Cardinal broadbrim claimed <num value="4">four</num> counties in England as his dioces, and his master the Pope claimed as many more as his sees, but the people of England could not see that, so they declared aloud they would see them blowed <num value="1">first</num>. 
<p>So when Jack Russell heard of his most impudent intentions, he sent him a Letter saying it was the intention of the people of England never again to submit to their infamous mumerys for the burnings in Smithfield was still fresh in their memory. 
<p>And behold great meetings were held in different parts of England where the Pope was burnt in effigy, like unto a Yarmouth Bloater, as a token of respect for him and his followers. 
<p>And the citizens of London were stanch to a man, and assembled together in the Guildhall of our mighty City and shouted with stentarian lungs, long live the Queen and down with the Pope, the sound of which might have been heard even unto the vatican of Rome. 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>And when his holyness the Pope heard that his power was set at naught, his nose became blue even as a bilberry with rage and declared Russell and Cummings or any who joined in the No Popery cry, should ever name the felisity of kissing his pious great toe. 
<QUOTE rend=center>Thus Endeth the Lesson.</QUOTE></text>
 
<p>In the course of my inquiries touching this subject I had more than once occasion to observe that an acute patterer had always a reason, or an excuse for anything. <num value="1">One</num> quick-witted Irishman, whom I knew to be a Roman Catholic, was &ldquo;working&rdquo; a &ldquo;patter against the Pope,&rdquo; (not the <num value="1">one</num> I have given), and on my speaking to him on the subject, and saying that I supposed he did it for a living, he replied: &ldquo;That&lsquo;s it then, sir. You&lsquo;re right, sir, yes. I work it just as a Catholic lawyer would plead against a Catholic paper for a libel on Protestants&mdash; though in his heart he knew the paper was right &mdash;and a Protestant lawyer would defend the libel hammer and tongs. Bless you, sir, you&lsquo;ll not find much more honour that way among us (laughing) than among them lawyers; not much.&rdquo; The readiness with which the sharpest of those men plead the doings not only of tradesmen, but of the learned and sacred professions, to justify themselves, is remarkable. 
<p>Sometimes a dialogue is of a satirical nature. <num value="1">One</num> man told me that the &ldquo;Conversation between Achilles and the Wellington Statue,&rdquo; of which I give the concluding moiety, was &ldquo;among the best,&rdquo; (he meant for profit), &ldquo;but no great thing.&rdquo; My informant was Achilles&mdash;or, as he pronounced it, Atchilees&mdash;and his mate was the statue, or &ldquo;man on the horse.&rdquo; The <num value="2">two</num> lines, in the couplet form, which precede every <num value="2">two</num> paragraphs of dialogue, seem as if they represent the speakers wrongfully. The answer should be attributed, in each case, to Achilles. 
<p>
 
<text><body><p>The hoarse voice it came from the statue of Achilles And &lsquo;twas answer&lsquo;d thus by the man on the horse. 
<p>&ldquo;Little man of little mind havn&lsquo;t I now got iron blinds, and bomb-proof rails when danger assails, a cunning devised job, to keep out an unruly mob, with high and ambitious views and remarkable queer shoes; I say, Old Nakedness, I say, come and see my frontage over the way, but I believe you can&lsquo;t get out after <num value="10">ten</num>! 
<p>No, you&lsquo;re as near where you are as at Quatre Bras, I hear a great deal what the public think and feel, plain as the nose on your face, we&lsquo;re deemed a national disgrace; they grumble at your high-ness, and at my want of shyness, and say many unpleasant things of Ligny and Marchienne! 
<p>The hoarse voice it came from the statue of Achilles And &lsquo;twas answer&lsquo;d thus by the man on the horse. 
<p>Ah! its a few days since the Nive, where Soult found me all alive, and the grand toralloo I made at Bordeaux; wasn&lsquo;t I in a nice mess, when Boney left Elba and left no address, besides <num value="150">150</num> other jobs with the chill off I could bring to view. 
<p>But then people will say, poor unfortunate Ney, and that you were dancing at a ball, and not near Hogumont at all, and that the job of St. Helena might have been done rather cleaner, and it was a shameful go to send Sir Hudson Lowe, and that you took particular care of No. <num value="1">1</num>, at Waterloo. 
<p>The hoarse voice it came from the statue of Achilles And &lsquo;twas answer&lsquo;d thus by the man on the horse. 
<p>Why flog &lsquo;em and &lsquo;od &lsquo;rot em, who said &lsquo;Up Guards and at &lsquo;em!&rdquo; and you know that nice treat I received in Downing Street, when hooted by a <num value="1000">thousand</num> or near, defended by an old grenadier, so no whopping I got, <pb id="p.238" n="238"> 
<milestone unit=col>
good luck to his old tin pot, oh! there&lsquo;s a deal of brass in me I&lsquo;ll allow. 
<p>Its prophecied you&lsquo;ll break down, they&lsquo;re crying it about town, and many jokes are past, that you&lsquo;re brought to the scaffold at last, and they say I look black, because I&lsquo;ve no shirt to my back, and its getting broad daylight, I vow! 
<p>The hoarse voice it came from the statue of Achilles But &lsquo;twas answer&lsquo;d thus by the man on the horse. 
<p><closer><signed><name>H. V. HOOKER</name>.</signed></closer></text>
 
<p>Of parodies other than the sort of compound of the Litany and other portions of the Church Service, which I have given, there are none in the streets&mdash;neither are there political duets. Such productions as parodies on popular songs, &ldquo;Cab! cab! cab!&rdquo; or &ldquo;Trip! trip! trip!&rdquo; are now almost always derived, for street-service, from the concert-rooms. But they relate more immediately to ballads, or street song; and not to patter. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.171"><head>Of &ldquo;Cocks,&rdquo; Etc.</head>

<p>THESE &ldquo;literary forgeries,&rdquo; if so they may be called, have already been alluded to under the head of the &ldquo;Death and Fire Hunters,&rdquo; but it is necessary to give a short account of a few of the best and longest know nof those stereotyped; no new cocks, except for an occasion, have been printed for some years. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> of the stereotyped cocks is, the &ldquo;Married Man Caught in a Trap.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> man had known it sold &ldquo;for years and years,&rdquo; and it served, he said, when there was any police report in the papers about sweethearts in coal-cellars, &amp;c. The illustration embraces <num value="2">two</num> compartments. In <num value="1">one</num> a severe-looking female is assaulting a man, whose hat has been knocked off by the contents of a water-jug, which a very stout woman is pouring on his head from a window. In the other compartment, as if from an adjoining room, <num value="2">two</num> women look on encouragingly. The subject matter, however, is in no accordance with the title or the embellishment. It is a love-letter from John S&mdash;n to his most &ldquo;adorable Mary.&rdquo; He expresses the ardour of his passion, and then twits his adored with something beyond a flirtation with Robert E&mdash;, a &ldquo;decoyer of female innocence.&rdquo; Placably overlooking this, however, John S&mdash;n continues:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>My dearest angel consent to my request, and keep me no longer in suspense&mdash;nothing, on my part, shall ever be wanting to make you happy and comfortable. My apprenticeship will expire in <num value="4">four</num> months from hence, when I intend to open a shop in the small ware line, and your abilities in dress-making and selfadjust- ing stay-maker, and the assistance of a few female mechanics, we shall be able to realize an independency.</QUOTE>
 
<p>&ldquo;Many a turn in seductions talked about in the papers and not talked about nowhere,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> man, &ldquo;has that slum served for, besides other things, such as love-letters, and confessions of a certain lady in this neighbourhood.&rdquo; 
<p>Another old cock is headed, &ldquo;Extraordinary and Funny Doings in this Neighbourhood.&rdquo; The illustration is a young lady, in an evening dress, sitting with an open letter in her hand, on a sort of garden-seat, in what appears to be a churchyard. After a smart song, enforcing the 
<milestone unit=col>
ever-neglected advice that people should &ldquo;look at home and mind their own business,&rdquo; are <num value="2">two</num> letters, the <num value="1">first</num> from R. G.; the answer from S. H. M. The gentleman&lsquo;s epistle commences:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Madam, 
<p>The love and tenderness I have hitherto expressed for you is false, and I now feel that my indifference towards you increases every day, and the more I see you the more you appear ridiculous in my eyes and contemptible&mdash; I feel inclined &amp; in every respect disposed &amp; determined to hate you. Believe me, I never had any inclination to offer you my hand.</QUOTE>
 
<p>The lady responds in a similar strain, and the twain appear very angry, until a foot-note offers an explanation: &ldquo;By reading every other line of the above letters the true meaning will be found.&rdquo; 
<p>Of this class of cocks I need cite no other specimens, but pass on to <num value="1">one</num> of another species&mdash;the &ldquo;Cruel and Inhuman Murder Committed on the Body of Capt. Lawson.&rdquo; The illustration is a lady, wearing a coronet, stabbing a gentleman, in full dress, through the top button of his waistcoat. The narrative commences:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>WITH surprise we have learned that this neighbourhood for a length of time was amazingly alarmed this day by a crowd of people carrying the body of Mr. James Lawless, to a doctor while streams of blood besmeared the way in such a manner that the cries of Murder re-echoed the sound of numerous voices. It appears that the cause of alarm, originated through a court-ship attended with a solemn promise of marriage between him and miss Lucy Guard, a handsome young Lady of refined feelings with the intercourse of a superior enlightened mind she lived with her aunt who spared neither pain nor cost to improve the talents of miss G. those <num value="7">seven</num> years past, since the death of her mother in Ludgate Hill, London, and bore a most excellent character until she got entangled by the delumps alcurement of Mr. L.</QUOTE>
 
<p>The writer then deplores Miss Guard&lsquo;s fall from virtue, and her desertion by her betrayer, &ldquo;on account of her fortune being small.&rdquo; Capt. Lawson, or Mr. James Lawless, next woos a wealthy City maiden, and the banns are published. What follows seems to me to be a rather intricate detail:&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>We find that the intended bride learned that Miss Guard, held certain promissory letters of his, and that she was determined to enter an action against him for a breach of promise, which moved clouded Eclipse over the extacy of the variable miss Lawless who knew that Miss G had Letters of his sufficient to substantiate her claims in a court.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Lawson visits Miss Guard to wheedle her out of his letters, but &ldquo;she drew a large carving-knife and stabbed him under the left breast.&rdquo; At the latest account the man was left without hope of recovery, while &ldquo;the valiant victress&rdquo; was &ldquo;ordered to submit to judicial decorum in the <num value="19">nineteenth</num> year of her age.&rdquo; The murders and other atrocities for which this &ldquo;cock&rdquo; has been sponsor, are&mdash;I was informed emphatically&mdash;a thundering lot! 
<p>I conclude with another cock, which may be called a narrative &ldquo;on a subject,&rdquo; as we have &ldquo;ballads on a subject&rdquo; (afterwards to be described), but with this difference, that the narrative is fictitious, and the ballad must be founded <pb id="p.239" n="239"> 
<milestone unit=col>
on a real event, however embellished. The highest newspaper style, I was told, was aimed at. Part of the production reads as if it had done service during the Revolution of <datestruct VALUE="1848-02--"><month reg="02">February</month>, <year reg="1848">1848</year></datestruct>. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Express from Paris. Supposed Death of LOUIS NAPOLEON. We stop the press to announce, That Luis Napoleon has been assasinated, by some it is said he is shot dead, by others that he is only wounded in the right arm. 
<p>We have most important intelligence from Paris. That capital is in a state of insurrection. The vivacious people, who have herefore defeated the goverment by paving-stones, have again taken up those missiles. On Tuesday the Ministers forbade the reform banquet, and the prefect of police published a proclamation warning the people to respect the laws, which he declared were violated, and he meant to enforce them. But the people dispised the proclamation and rejected his authority. They assembled in great multitudes round the Chambers of Deputies, and forced their way over the walls. They were attacked by the troops and dispersed, but, re-assembled in various quarters. They showed their hatred of M. Guizot by demolishing his windows and attempting to force an entrance into his hotel, but were again repulced by the troops. All the military in Paris, and all the National Guard, have been summoned to arms, and every preparation made on the part of the government to put down the people. 
<p>The latter have raised barricades in various places, and have unpaved the streets, overturned omnibusses, and made preparations for a vigorous assault, or a protracted resistance. 
<p><num value="5">Five</num> o&lsquo;Closk&mdash;At this momont the Rue St. Honore is blockaded by a detachment dragoons, who fill the market-place near the Rue des Petits Champs, and are charging the people sword in hand, carriages full of deople are being taken to the hospitals. 
<p>In fact the maddest excitement reigns throughout the capital. 
<p>Half past <num value="6">Six</num>.&mdash;During the above we have instituted enquiries at the Foreign office, they have not received any inteligence of the above report, if it has come, it must have been by pigeon express. We have not given the above in our columns with a view of its authenticity, any further information as soon as obtained shall be immediately announced to the public.</QUOTE>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.172"><head>Of &ldquo;Strawing.&rdquo;</head>

<p>I have already alluded to &ldquo;strawing,&rdquo; which can hardly be described as quackery. It is rather a piece of mountebankery. Many a quack&mdash;confining the term to its most common signification, that of a &ldquo;quack doctor&rdquo;&mdash;has faith in the excellence of his own nostrums, and so proffers that which he believes to be curative: the strawer, however, sells what he 
<hi rend=italics>knows</hi> is not what he represents it. 
<p>The strawer offers to <hi rend=italics>sell</hi> any passer by in the streets a straw and to <hi rend=italics>give</hi> the purchaser a paper which he <hi rend=italics>dares not</hi> sell. Accordingly as he judges of the character of his audience, so he intimates that the paper is political, libellous, irreligious, or indecent. 
<p>I am told that as far back as <num value="25">twenty-five</num> or <num value="26">twenty-six</num> years, straws were sold, but only in the country, with leaves from the <hi rend=italics>Republican</hi>, a periodical published by Carlile, then of Fleetstreet, which had been prosecuted by the government; but it seems that the trade died away, and was little or hardly known again until the time of the trial of Queen Caroline, and then but sparingly. The straw sale reached its 
<milestone unit=col>
highest commercial pitch at the era of the Reform Bill. The most successful trader in the article is remembered among the patterers as &ldquo;Jack Straw,&rdquo; who was oft enough represented to me as the original strawer. If I inquired further, the answer was: &ldquo;He was the <num value="1">first</num> in my time.&rdquo; This Jack Straw was, I am told, a fine-looking man, a natural son of Henry Hunt, the blacking manufacturer. He was described to me as an inveterate drunkard and a very reckless fellow. <num value="1">One</num> old hand was certain that this man was Hunt&lsquo;s son, as he himself had &ldquo;worked&rdquo; with him, and was sometimes sent by him when he was &ldquo;in trouble,&rdquo; or in any strait, to <num value="32">32</num>, Broadwall, Blackfriars, for assistance, which was usually rendered. (This was the place where Hunt&lsquo;s &ldquo;Matchless Blacking&rdquo; and &ldquo;Roasted Corn&rdquo; were vended.) Jack Straw&lsquo;s principal &ldquo;pitch&rdquo; was at Hyde Park Corner, &ldquo;where,&rdquo; said the man whom I have mentioned as working with him, &ldquo;he used to come it very strong against Old Nosey, the Hyde Park bully as he called him. To my knowledge he&lsquo;s made <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, and he&lsquo;s made <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> on a night. O, it didn&lsquo;t matter to him what he sold with his straws, religion or anything. There was no <num value="3">three</num>-pennies (threepenny newspapers) then, and he had had a gentleman&lsquo;s education, and knew what to say, and so the straws went off like smoke.&rdquo; The articles which this man &ldquo;durst not sell&rdquo; were done up in paper, so that no <num value="1">one</num> could very well peruse them on the spot, as a sort of stealth was implied. On my asking Jack Straw&lsquo;s coworker if he had ever drank with him, &ldquo;Drank with him!&rdquo; he answered, &ldquo;Yes, many a time. I&lsquo;ve gone out and pattered, or chaunted, or anything, to get money to buy him <num value="2">two</num> glasses of brandy&mdash;and good brandy was very dear then&mdash;before he could start, for he was all of a tremble until he had his medicine. If I couldn&lsquo;t get brandy, it was the best rum, &lsquo;cause he had all the tastes of a gentleman. Ah! he&lsquo;s been dead some years, sir, but where he died I don&lsquo;t know. I only heard of his death. He was a nice kindly fellow.&rdquo; 
<p>The <hi rend=italics>ruse</hi> in respect of strawing is not remarkable for its originality. It was an old smuggler&lsquo;s trick to <hi rend=italics>sell</hi> a sack and <hi rend=italics>give</hi> the keg of contraband spirit placed within it and padded out with straw so as to resemble a sack of corn. The hawkers, prior to <datestruct value="1826--"><year reg="1826">1826</year></datestruct>, when Mr. Huskisson introduced changes into the Silk Laws, <hi rend=italics>gave</hi>
&ldquo;real Ingy handkerchiefs&rdquo; (sham) to a customer, and <hi rend=italics>sold</hi> him a knot of tape for about <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
The price of a true Bandana, then prohibited, and sold openly in the draper&lsquo;s shops, was about <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> The East India Company imported about a million of Bandanas yearly; they were sold by auction for exportation to Hamburgh, &amp;c., at about <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> each, and were nearly all smuggled back again to England, and disposed of as I have stated. 
<p>It is not possible to give anything like statistics as to the money realised by strawing. A well-informed man calculated that when the <pb id="p.240" n="240"> 
<milestone unit=col>
trade was at its best, or from <datestruct value="1832--"><year reg="1832">1832</year></datestruct> to <datestruct value="1836--"><year reg="1836">1836</year></datestruct>, there might be generally <num value="50">fifty</num> working it in the country and <num value="20">twenty</num> in London; they did not confine themselves, however, to strawing, but resorted to it only on favourable opportunities. Now there are none in London&mdash;their numbers diminished gradually&mdash;and very rarely any in the country. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.173"><head>Of the Sham indecent Street-Trade.</head>

<p>THIS is <num value="1">one</num> of those callings which are at once repulsive and ludicrous; repulsive, when it is considered under what pretences the papers are sold, and ludicrous, when the disappointment of the gulled purchaser is contemplated. 
<p>I have mentioned that <num value="1">one</num> of the allurements held out by the strawer was that his paper&mdash;the words used by Jack Straw&mdash;could &ldquo;not be admitted into families.&rdquo; Those following the &ldquo;sham indecent trade&rdquo; for a time followed his example, and professed to sell straws and give away papers; but the London police became very observant of the sale of straws&mdash;more especially under the pretences alluded to&mdash;and it has, for the last <num value="10">ten</num> years, been rarely pursued in the streets. 
<p>The plan now adopted is to sell the sealed packet itself, which the &ldquo;patter&rdquo; of the streetseller leads his auditors to believe to be some improper or scandalous publication. The packet is some coloured paper, in which is placed a portion of an old newspaper, a Christmas carol, a religious tract, or a slop-tailor&lsquo;s puff (given away in the streets for the behoof of another class of gulls). She enclosed paper is, however, never indecent. 
<p>From a man who had, not long ago, been in this trade, I had the following account. He was very anxious that nothing should be said which would lead to a knowledge that he was my informant. After having expressed his sorrow that he had ever been driven to this trade from distress, he proceeded to justify himself. He argued&mdash;and he was not an ignorant man&mdash;that there was neither common sense nor common justice in interfering with a man like him, who, &ldquo;to earn a crust, pretended to sell what <hi rend=italics>shopkeepers</hi>, that must pay church and all sorts of rates, sold without being molested.&rdquo; The word &ldquo;shopkeepers&rdquo; was uttered with a bitter emphasis. There are, or were, he continued, shops &mdash;for he seemed to know them all&mdash;and some of them had been carried on for years, in which shameless publications were not only sold, but exposed in the windows; and why should he be considered a greater offender than a shopkeeper, and be knocked about by the police? There are, or lately were, he said, such shops in the Strand, Fleet-street, a court off Ludgate-hill, Holborn, Drury-lane, Wych-street, the courts near Drury-lane Theatre, Haymarket, Highstreet, Bloomsbury, St. Martin&lsquo;s-court, May&lsquo;s buildings, and elsewhere, to say nothing of Holywell-street! Yet <hi rend=italics>he</hi> must be interfered with! 
<p>[I may here remark, that I met with no street-sellers who did not disbelieve, or affect to 
<milestone unit=col>
disbelieve, that they were really meddled with by the police for obstructing the thoroughfare. They either hint, or plainly state, that they are removed solely to please the shop-keepers. Such was the reiterated opinion, real or pretended, of my present informant.] 
<p>I took a statement from this man, but do not care to dwell upon the subject. The trade, in the form I have described, had been carried on, he thought, for the last <num value="6">six</num> years. At <num value="1">one</num> time, <num value="20">20</num> men followed it; at present, he believed there were only <num value="6">6</num>, and they worked only at intervals, and as opportunities offered: some going out, for instance, to sell almanacs or memorandum books, and, when they met with a favourable chance, offering their sealed packets. My informant&lsquo;s customers were principally boys, young men, and old gentlemen; but old gentlemen chiefly when the trade was new. This street-seller&lsquo;s &ldquo;great gun,&rdquo; as he called it, was to make up packets, as closely resembling as he could accomplish it, those which were displayed in the windows of any of the shops I have alluded to. He would then station himself at some little distance from <num value="1">one</num> of those shops, and, if possible, so as to encounter those who had stopped to study the contents of the window, and would represent&mdash;broadly enough, he admitted, when he dared&mdash;that he could sell for <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> what was charged <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, or <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, or whatever price he had seen announced, &ldquo;in that very neighbourhood.&rdquo; He sometimes ventured, also, to mutter something, unintelligibly, about the public being imposed upon! On <num value="1">one</num> occasion, he took <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> in the street in about <num value="2">two</num> hours. On another evening he took <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> in the street and was called aside by <num value="2">two</num> old gentlemen, each of whom told him to come to an address given (at the West-end), and ask for such and such initials. To <num value="1">one</num> he sold <num value="2">two</num> packets for <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; to the other, <num value="5">five</num> packets, each <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&mdash;or <num value="11">11</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> in <num value="1">one</num> evening. The packets were in different coloured papers, and had the impressions of a large seal on red wax at the back; and he assured the old gents., as he called them, <num value="1">one</num> of whom, he thought, was &ldquo;silly,&rdquo; that they were all different. &ldquo;And very likely,&rdquo; he said, chucklingly, &ldquo;they were different; for they were made out of a lot of missionary tracts and old newspapers that I got dirt cheap at a &lsquo;waste&rsquo; shop. I should like to have seen the old gent.&lsquo;s face, as he opened his <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> worth, <num value="1">one</num> after another!&rdquo; This trade, however, among old gentlemen, was prosperous for barely a month: &ldquo;It got blown then, sir, and they wouldn&lsquo;t buy any more, except a very odd <num value="1">one</num>.&rdquo; 
<p>This man&mdash;and he believed it was the same with all the others in the trade&mdash;never visited the public-houses, for a packet would soon have been opened and torn there, which, he said, people was ashamed to do in the public streets. As well as he could recollect, he had never sold a single packet to a girl or a woman. Drunken women of the town had occasionally made loud comments on his calling, and offered 
