to purchase; but on such occasions, fearful of a disturbance, he always hurried away. 
<p>I have said that the straw trade is now confined to the country, and I give a specimen of the article vended there, by the patterer in the sham indecent trade. It was purchased of a man, who sold it folded in the form of a letter, and is addressed, &ldquo;On Royal Service. By Express. Private. To Her Royal Highness, Victoria, Princess Royal. Kensington Palace, London. Entered at Stationer&lsquo;s Hall.&rdquo; The man who sold it had a wisp of straw round his neck, and introduced his wares with the following patter: 
<p>&ldquo;I am well aware that many persons here present will say what an absurd idea&mdash;the idea of selling straws for a halfpenny each, when there are so many lying about the street; but the reason is simply this: I am not allowed by the authorities to sell these papers, so I give them away and sell my straws. There are a variety of figures in these papers for gentlemen; some in the bed, some on the bed, some under the bed.&rdquo; The following is a copy of the document thus sold:&mdash; 
