<p>Of Thurtell I could obtain no accounts&mdash;&ldquo;it was so long ago;&rdquo; but the sale, I was told, was enormous. Reckoning that each copy was sold for <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> (the regular price in the country, where the great sale is,) the money expended for such things amounts to upwards of <num value="48500">48,500</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> in the case of the <num value="6">six</num> murderers above given. All this number was printed and got up in London; a few &ldquo;broad-sheets&rdquo; concerning Rush were printed also in Norwich. 
<p>Touching the issue of &ldquo;cocks,&rdquo; a person connected with the trade calculated for me, from data at his command, that <num value="3456">3,456</num> copies were struck of weekly, and sold in the streets, in the metropolis; and reckoning them at only a <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
each, we have the sum of <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> spent every week in this manner. At this rate, there must be <num value="179712">179,712</num> copies of &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; printed in a year, on which the public expend no less than <num value="374">374</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>

<p>Of the style of illustrations usually accompanying this class of street literature the <num value="2">two</num> large engravings here given are <hi rend=italics>fac similes</hi>&mdash; while the smaller ones are faithful copies of the average embellishments to the halfpenny ballads. On another occasion I shall speak at length on &ldquo;Street-Art.&rdquo; 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.200"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Conundrums.</head>

<p>AMONG the more modern street sales are &ldquo;conundrums,&rdquo; generally vended, both in the shops and the streets, as &ldquo;Nuts to Crack,&rdquo; when not in the form of books. This is another of the &ldquo;broad-sheets,&rdquo; and is sufficiently clever and curious in its way. 
<p>In the centre, at the top, is the &ldquo;Wonderful Picture,&rdquo; with the following description: &ldquo;This Picture when looked at from a particular point of view, will not only appear perfect in all respects and free from distortion, but the figures will actually appear to stand out in relief from the paper.&rdquo; The wonderful picture, which is a rude imitation of a similar toy picture sold in a box, &ldquo;with eye-piece complete,&rdquo; at the shops, presents a distorted view of a churchspire, a light-house, a donjon-keep, castellated buildings backed by mountains, a moat on which are <num value="2">two</num> vessels, an arch surmounted by a Britannia, a palm-tree (I presume), and a rampart, or pier, or something that way, on which are depicted <num value="2">two</num> figures, with the gestures of elocutionists. The buildings are elongated, like shadows at sunset or sunrise. What may be the &ldquo;particular point of view&rdquo; announced in the description of the Wonderful Picture, is not described in the &ldquo;Nuts,&rdquo; but the following explanation is given in a little book, published simultaneously, and entitled, &ldquo;The Nutcrackers, a Key to Nuts to Crack, or Enigmatical Repository:&rdquo; 
<p>&ldquo;THE WONDERFUL PICTURE.&mdash;Cut out a piece of cardboard <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num> inches long, make a round hole about the size of a pea in the top of it; place this level with the right-hand side of the Engraving and just <num value="1.50">1 1/2</num> inches distant from it, then apply your eye to the little hole and look at the picture, and you will find that a beautiful symmetry pervades the landscape, there is not the slightest appearance of distortion, and the different 
<milestone unit=col>
parts appear actually to stand up in relief on the paper.&rdquo; 
<p>Below the &ldquo;Wonderful Picture&rdquo; are other illustrations; and the border of the broadsheet presents a series of what may be called pictorial engravings. The <num value="1">first</num> is, 
<FIGURE id="Fig.285"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE>
<p>
<FIGURE id="Fig.285.1"><head>D I O C C <num value="1">1</num>.&mdash;Lately presented to a &ldquo;Wise man&rdquo; by a usurper.</head></figure>

<p>The answer being evidently &ldquo;Diocese.&rdquo; No. <num value="26">26</num> is 
<FIGURE id="Fig.285.2"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE>

<FIGURE id="Fig.285.3"><head>A <num value="4">4</num> <num value="26">26</num>.&mdash;The Child&lsquo;s &ldquo;Tidy.&rdquo;</head></figure>
 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Pinafore&rdquo; is the solution. Of the next &ldquo;hieroglyphic&rdquo;&mdash;for a <num value="2">second</num> title to the &ldquo;Nuts&rdquo; tells of &ldquo;<num value="200">200</num> Hieroglyphics, Enigmas, Conundrums, Curious Puzzles, and other Ingenious Devices,&rdquo;&mdash;I cannot speak very highly. It consists of &ldquo;AIMER,&rdquo; (a figure of a hare at full speed,) and &ldquo;EKA.&rdquo; Answer.&mdash;&ldquo;America.</QUOTE>
 
<p>In the body of the broad-sheet are the Enigmas, &amp;c., announced; of each of which I give a specimen, to show the nature of this street performance or entertainment. Enigma <num value="107">107</num> is&mdash; 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>I&lsquo;ve got no wings, yet in the air 
<L>I often rise and fall; 
<L>I&lsquo;ve got no feet, yet clogs I wear, 
<L>And shoes, and boots, and all.</quote>

<p>As the answer is foot-ball, the <num value="2">two</num> last lines should manifestly have been placed <num value="1">first</num>. 
<p>The &ldquo;Conundrums&rdquo; are next in the arrangement, and I cite <num value="1">one</num> of them: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Why are there, strictly speaking, only <num value="325">325</num> days in the year?</QUOTE>
 
<p>&ldquo;Because,&rdquo; is the reply, &ldquo;<num value="40">forty</num> of them are lent and never returned.&rdquo; The &ldquo;Riddles&rdquo; follow in this portion of the &ldquo;Nuts to Crack.&rdquo; Of these, <num value="1">one</num> is not very difficult to be solved, though it is distinguished for the usual grammatical confusion of tenses: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>A man has <num value="3">three</num> daughters, and each of these have a brother. How many children had he?</QUOTE>
 
<p>The &ldquo;Charades&rdquo; complete the series. Of these I select <num value="1">one</num> of the best: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>I am a word of letters <num value="7">seven</num>, 
<L>I&lsquo;m sinful in the sight of heaven, 
<L>To every virtue I&lsquo;m opposed, 
<L>Man&lsquo;s weary life I&lsquo;ve often closed. 
<L>If to me you prefix <num value="2">two</num> letters more, 
<L>I mean exactly what I meant before.</quote>

<p>The other parts of the letter-press consist of &ldquo;Anagrams,&rdquo; &ldquo;Transpositions,&rdquo; &amp;c. 
<p>When a clever patterer &ldquo;works conundrums&rdquo; &mdash;for the trade is in the hands of the pattering class&mdash;he selects what he may consider the best, and reads or repeats them in the street, sometimes with and sometimes without the answer. But he does not cripple the probable quickness <pb id="p.286" n="286"> 
<milestone unit=col>
of his sale by a slavish adherence to what is in type. He puts the matter, as it were, personally. &ldquo;What gentleman is it,&rdquo; <num value="1">one</num> man told me he would ask, &ldquo;in this street, that has&mdash; 
<p>&lsquo;Eyes like saucers, a back like a box, A nose like a pen-knife, and a voice like a fox?&rsquo; 
<p>You can learn for a penny. Or sometimes I&lsquo;ll go on with the patter, thus,&rdquo; he continued, &ldquo;What lady is it that we have all seen, and who can say truly&mdash; 
<p>&lsquo;I am brighter than day, I am swifter than light, And stronger than all the momentum of might?&rsquo; 
<p>More than once people have sung out &lsquo;the Queen,&rsquo; for they seem to think that the momentum of might couldn&lsquo;t fit any <num value="1">one</num> else. It&lsquo;s &lsquo;thought&rsquo; as is the answer, but it wouldn&lsquo;t do to let people think it&lsquo;s anything of the sort. It must seem to fit <hi rend=italics>somebody.</hi> If I see a tailor&lsquo;s name on a door, as soon as I&lsquo;ve passed the corner of the street, and sometimes in the same street, I&lsquo;ve asked&mdash; 
<p>&lsquo;Why is Mr. So-and-so, the busy tailor of this (or the next street) never at home?&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Because he&lsquo;s always cutting out.&rsquo; I have the same questions for other tradesmen, and for gentlemen and ladies in this neighbourhood, and no gammon. All for a penny. Nuts to Crack, a penny. A pair of Nutcrackers to crack &lsquo;em, only <num value="1">one</num> penny.&rdquo; 
<p>Sometimes this man, who perhaps is the smartest in the trade, will take a bolder flight still, and when he knows the residence of any professional or public man, he will, if the allusion be complimentary, announce his name, or &mdash;if there be any satire&mdash;indicate by a motion of the head, or a gesture of the hand, the direction of his residence. My ingenuous, and certainly ingenious, informant obliged me with a few instances:&mdash;&ldquo;In Whitechapel parish I&lsquo;ve said&mdash;it ain&lsquo;t in the print, it was only in the patter&mdash;&lsquo;Why won&lsquo;t the Reverend Mr. Champneys lay up treasures on earth?&rsquo;&mdash;&lsquo;Because he&lsquo;d rather lay up treasures in heaven.&rsquo; That&lsquo;s the reverend gentleman not far from this spot; but in this sheet&mdash;with nearly <num value="100">100</num> engravings by the <num value="1">first</num> artists, only a penny&mdash;I have other questions for other parsons, not so easy answered; nuts as is hard to crack. &lsquo;Why is the Reverend Mr. Popjoy,&rsquo; or the Honourable Lawyer Bully, or Judge Wiggem,&mdash;and then I just jerks my thumb, sir, if it&lsquo;s where I know or think such people live &mdash;&lsquo;Why is the Reverend Mr. Popjoy (or the others) like <hi rend=italics><num value="2">two</num></hi> balloons, <num value="1">one</num> in the air to the east, and the &lsquo;tother in the air to the west, in this parish of St. George&lsquo;s, Hanover-square?&rsquo; There&lsquo;s no such question, and as it&lsquo;s a sort of a &lsquo;cock,&rsquo; of course there&lsquo;s no answer. I don&lsquo;t know <num value="1">one</num>. But a gentleman&lsquo;s servant once sung out: &lsquo;&lsquo;cause he&lsquo;s uppish.&rsquo; And a man in a leather apron once said: &lsquo;He&lsquo;s a raising the wind,&rsquo; which was nonsense. But I like that sort of interruption, and have said&mdash;&lsquo;You&lsquo;ll not find <hi rend=italics>that</hi> answer in the Nutcrackers,&rsquo; only a penny&mdash;and, Lord knows, I told the truth when 
<milestone unit=col>
I said so, and it helps the sale. No fear of any <num value="1">one</num>&lsquo;s finding out all what&lsquo;s in the sheet before I&lsquo;m out of the &lsquo;drag.&rsquo; Not a bit. And you must admit that any way it&lsquo;s a cheap pennorth.&rdquo; That it is a cheap harmless pennyworth is undeniable. 
<p>The street-sale of conundrums is carried on most extensively during a week or <num value="2">two</num> before Christmas; and on summer evenings, when the day&lsquo;s work is, or ought to be, over even among the operatives of the slop employers. As the conundrum patterer requires an audience, he works the quieter streets, preferring such as have no horse-thoroughfare&mdash;as in some of the approaches from the direction of Golden-square to Regent-street. The trade is irregularly pursued, none following it all the year; and from the best information I could acquire, it appears that <num value="15">fifteen</num> men may be computed as working conundrums for <num value="2">two</num> months throughout the <num value="12">twelve</num>, and clearing <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> weekly, per individual. The cost of the &ldquo;Nuts to Crack&rdquo; (when new) is <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a doz. to the seller; but old &ldquo;Nuts&rdquo; often answer the purpose of the street-seller, and may be had for about half the price; the cost of the &ldquo;Nutcrackers&rdquo; <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> It may be calculated, then, that to realize the <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> must be taken. This shows the street expenditure in &ldquo;Nuts to Crack&rdquo; and &ldquo;Nut-crackers&rdquo; to be <num value="90">90</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> yearly. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.201"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Comic Exhibi- Tions, Magical Delusions, &amp;c.</head>

<p>THE street sale of &ldquo;Comic Exhibitions&rdquo; (properly so called) is, of course, as modern as the last autumn and winter; and it is somewhat curious that the sale of any humorous, or meant to be humorous sheet of engravings, is now becoming very generally known in the street sale as a &ldquo;Comic Exhibition.&rdquo; Among these&mdash;as I have before intimated&mdash;are many caricatures of the Pope, the Church of Rome, Cardinal Wiseman, the Church of England, the Bishop of London (or any bishop or dignitary), or of any characteristic of the conflicting creeds. In many of these, John Bull figures personally, and so does the devil. 
<p>The Comic Exhibition (proper) is certainly a very cheap pennyworth. No. <num value="1">1</num> is entitled, &ldquo;The Ceremonial of the Opening of the Great Exhisition, in <datestruct value="1851--"><year reg="1851">1851</year></datestruct>, with Illustrations of the Contributions of All Nations.&rdquo; The &ldquo;contributions,&rdquo; however, are reserved for Nos. <num value="2">2</num> and <num value="3">3</num>. <num value="2">Two</num> larger &ldquo;cuts,&rdquo; at the head of the broad-sheet, may be considered geographical, as regards the <num value="1">first</num>, and allegorical as regards the <num value="2">second</num>. &ldquo;Table Bay&rdquo; presents a huge feeder (evidently), and the &ldquo;Cape of Good Hope&rdquo; is a spare man obsequiously bowing to the table and its guest in good hope of a dinner. Of the Sandwich Islands and of Hung(a)ry, the &ldquo;exhibition&rdquo; is of the same description. The <num value="2">second</num> larger cut shows the Crystal Palace ascending by the agency of a balloon, a host of people of all countries looking on. Then comes the <pb id="p.287" n="287"> 
<milestone unit=col>
&lsquo;Procession from Palace-yard to Hyde Park.&rdquo; The <num value="1">first</num> figure in this procession is described as &ldquo;Beefeaters piping hot and well puffed out,&rdquo; though there is but <num value="1">one</num> beefeater, with head larger than his body and legs ridiculously, small (as have nearly all the sequent figures), smoking a pipe as if it were a trombone, duly followed by &ldquo;Her Majesty&lsquo;s Spiritual Bodyguard&rdquo; (<num value="5">five</num> beefeaters, drunk), and by &ldquo;Prince Albert blowing his own trumpet&rdquo; (from the back of a very sorry steed), with &ldquo;Mops and brooms,&rdquo; and a &ldquo;Cook-oo&rdquo; (a housemaid and cook) as his supporters. Then follow figures, grotesque enough, of which the titles convey the character: &ldquo;A famous Well-in-Town;&rdquo; &ldquo;Nae Peer-ye;&rdquo; &ldquo;Humorous Estimates&rdquo; (Mr. Hume); &ldquo;A Jew-d&rsquo; esprit&rdquo; (Mr. D&lsquo;Israeli); &ldquo;An exemplification of Cupidity in Pummicestone&rdquo; (Lord Palmerston); &ldquo;Old Geese&rdquo; and &ldquo;Young Ducks&rdquo; (old and angrylooking and young and pretty women); &ldquo;Some gentlemen who patronise Moses in the Minories&rdquo; (certainly no credit to the skill of a tailor); &ldquo;A Jew Lion&rdquo; (M. Jullien); &ldquo;Fine high screams&rdquo; (ice-creams) and &ldquo;Capers&rdquo; (chorister boys and ballet-girls); &ldquo;Hey-day, you don&lsquo;t take advantage here&rdquo; (Joseph Ady); and &ldquo;Something to give the milk a head&rdquo; (a man with a horse&lsquo;s head on a tray). These, however, are but a portion of the figures. The Comic Exhibition-sheet contains <num value="90">ninety</num> such figures, independent of those in the <num value="2">two</num> cuts mentioned as headings. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Galleries of Comicalities,&rdquo; or series of figures sometimes satirically, sometimes grotesquely given without any aim at satire, are also sold by the same parties, and are often announced as a &ldquo;Threepenny gallery for a penny!&mdash;and dirt cheap at threepence. As big as a newspaper.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Another broad-sheet sold this winter in the streets is entitled, &ldquo;Optical and Magical Delusions,&rdquo; and was announced as &ldquo;Dedicated to and Prepared for his Royal Highness the Prince of Wales&mdash;the only original copy.&rdquo; The engravings are <num value="6">six</num> in number, and are in <num value="3">three</num> rows, each accompanying engraving being reversed from its fellow: where the head is erect on <num value="1">one</num> side, it is downward on the other. The <num value="1">first</num> figure is a short length of a very plain woman, while on the opposite side is that of a very plain man, both pleased and smirking in accordance with a line below: &ldquo;O what joy when our lips shall meet!&rdquo; &ldquo;Cat-a-gorical&rdquo; is a spectacled and hooded cat. &ldquo;Dog-matical&rdquo; is a dog with the hat, wig, and cane once held proper to a physician. &ldquo;Cross purposes&rdquo; is an austere lady in a monster cap, while her opposite husband is pointing bitterly to a long bill. The purport of these figures is shown in the following 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>DIRECTIONS&mdash;Paste all over the Back of the sheet, and put a piece of thick paper between, to stiffen it, then fold it down the centre, so that the marginal lines fall exactly at the back of each other, (which may be ascertained by holding it to the light)&mdash;press it quite flat&mdash;when cut separate they will make <num value="3">three</num> cards&mdash; shave them close to the margin&mdash;then take a needle- 
<milestone unit=col>
full of double thread and pass it through the dot at each end of the card; cut the thread off about <num value="3">three</num> inches long. By twisting the threads between your fore fingers and thumbs, so as to spin the card round backwards and forwards with a rapid motion, the figures will appear to connect and form a pleasing delusion.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Then there are the &ldquo;Magical Figures,&rdquo; or rude street imitations of Dr. Paris&rsquo; ingenious toy, called the &ldquo;Thaumascope.&rdquo; Beside these are what at the <num value="1">first</num> glance appear mere black, and very black, marks, defining no object; but a closer examination shows the outlines of a face, or of a face and figure. Of such there are sometimes <num value="4">four</num> on a broad-sheet, but they are also sold separately, both in the streets and the small stationers&rsquo; shops. When the white or black portion of the paper is cut away (for both colours are so prepared), what remains, by a disposition of the light, throws a huge shadow of a grotesque figure on the wall, which may be increased or diminished according to the motions of the exhibitor. The shadow-figures sold this winter by <num value="1">one</num> of my informants were of Mr. and Mrs. Manning, the Queen, Prince Albert, the Princess Royal, and the Prince of Wales; &ldquo;but you see, sir,&rdquo; observed the man, &ldquo;the Queen and the Prince does for any father and mother&mdash;for she hasn&lsquo;t her crown on&mdash;and the Queen&lsquo;s kids for anybody&lsquo;s kids.&rdquo; 
<p>I mention these matters more particularly, as it certainly shows something of a change in the winter-evenings&rsquo; amusements of the children of the working-classes. The principal street customers for these penny papers were mechanics, who bought them on their way home for the amusement of their families. Boys, however, bought almost as many. 
<p>The sale of these papers is carried on by the same men as I have described working conundrums. A superior patterer, of course, shows that his magical delusions and magical figures combine all the wonders of the magic lantern and the dissolving views, &ldquo;and all for <num value="1">one</num> penny.&rdquo; The trade is carried on only for a short time in the winter as regards the magical portion; and I am informed that, including the &ldquo;Comic Exhibitions,&rdquo; it extends to about half of the sum taken for conundrums, or to about <num value="45">45</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.202"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Play-Bills.</head>

<p>The sellers of play-bills carry on a trade which is exceedingly uncertain, and is little remunerative. There are now rather more than <num value="200">200</num> people selling play-bills in London, but the number has sometimes been as high as <num value="400">400</num>. &ldquo;Yes, indeed,&rdquo; a theatrical gentleman said to me, &ldquo;and if a dozen more theatres were opened to-morrow, why each would have more than its <num value="20">twenty</num> bill-sellers the very <num value="1">first</num> night. Where they come from, or what they are, I haven&lsquo;t a notion.&rdquo; 
<p>The majority of the play-bill sellers are either old or young, the sexes being about equally engaged in this traffic. Some of them have followed the business from their childhood. I met with very few indeed who knew anything of <pb id="p.288" n="288"> 
<milestone unit=col>
theatres beyond the names of the managers and of the principal performers, while some do not even enjoy that small modicum of knowledge, and some can neither read nor write. The boys often run recklessly alongside the cabs which are conveying persons to the theatre, and so offer their bills for sale. <num value="1">One</num> of these youths said to me, when I spoke of the danger incurred, &ldquo;The cabman knows how to do it, sir, when I runs and patters; and so does his hoss.&rdquo; An intelligent cabman, however, who was in the habit of driving parties to the Lyceum, told me that these lads clung to his cab as he drove down to Wellington-street in such a way, for they seemed never to look before them, that he was in constant fear lest they should be run over. Ladies are often startled by a face appearing suddenly at the cab window, &ldquo;and thro&rsquo; my glass,&rdquo; said my informant, &ldquo;a face would look dirtier than it really is.&rdquo; And certainly a face gliding along with the cab, as it were, no accompanying body being visible, on a winter&lsquo;s night, while the sound of the runner&lsquo;s footsteps is lost in the noise of the cab, has much the effect of an apparition. 
<p>I did not hear of <num value="1">one</num> person who had been in any way connected with the stage, even as a supernumerary, resorting to play-bill selling when he could not earn a shilling within the walls of a theatre. These bill-sellers, for the most part, confine themselves, as far as I could ascertain, to that particular trade. The youths say that they sometimes get a job in errand-going in the daytime, but the old men and women generally aver they can do nothing else. An officer, who, some years back, had been on duty at a large theatre, told me that at that time the women bill-sellers earned a trifle in running errands for the women of the town who attended the theatres; but, as they were not permitted to send any communication into the interior of the house, their earnings that way were insignificant, for they could only send in messages by any other &ldquo;dress woman&rdquo; entering the theatre subsequently. 
<p>In the course of my inquiries last year, I met with a lame woman of <num value="68">sixty-eight</num>, who had been selling play-bills for the last <num value="12">twelve</num> years. She had been, for <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="8">eight</num> months before she adopted that trade, the widow of a poor mechanic, a carpenter. She had <num value="1">first</num> thought of resorting to that means of a livelihood owing to a neighbouring old woman having been obliged to relinquish her post from sickness, when my informant &ldquo;succeeded her.&rdquo; In this way, she said, many persons &ldquo;succeeded&rdquo; to the business, as the recognised old hands were jealous of and uncivil to any additional new comers, but did not object to a &ldquo;successor.&rdquo; These parties generally know each other; they murmur if the Haymarket hands, for instance, resort to the Lyceum for any cause, or <hi rend=italics>vice vers&acirc;</hi>, thus overstocking the business, but they offer no other opposition. The old woman further informed me that she commenced selling play-bills at Astley&lsquo;s, and then realized a profit of <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> per week. When the old Amphitheatre was burnt down, 
<milestone unit=col>
she went to the Victoria; but &ldquo;business was not what it was,&rdquo; and her earnings were from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week less; and this, she said, although the Victoria was considered <num value="1">one</num> of the most profitable stations for the play-bill seller, the box-keeper there seldom selling any bill in the theatre. &ldquo;The boxes,&rdquo; too, at this house, more frequently buy them outside. Another reason why &ldquo;business&rdquo; was better at the Victoria than elsewhere was represented to me, by a person familar with the theatres, to be this: many go to the Victoria who cannot read, or who can read but imperfectly, and they love to &ldquo;make-believe&rdquo; they are &ldquo;good scholards&rdquo; by parading the consulting of a play-bill! 
<p>On my visit the bill-sellers at the Victoria were <num value="2">two</num> old women (each a widow for many years), <num value="2">two</num> young men, besides <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num>, though there are sometimes as many as <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="7">seven</num> children. The old women &ldquo;fell into the business&rdquo; as successors by virtue of their predecessors&rsquo; leaving it on account of sickness. The children were generally connected with the older dealers. The young men had been in this business from boyhood; some sticking to the practice of their childhood unto manhood, or towards old age. The number at the Victoria is now, I am informed, <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> more, as the theatre is often crowded. The old woman told me that she had known <num value="2">two</num> and even <num value="4">four</num> visitors to the theatre club for the purchase of a bill, and then she had sometimes to get farthings for them. 
<p>A young fellow&mdash;who said he believed he was only eighteen, but certainly looked older&mdash;told me that he was in the habit of selling play-bills, but not regularly, as he sometimes had a job in carrying a board, or delivering bills at a corner, &ldquo;or the likes o&rsquo; that;&rdquo;&mdash;he favoured me with his opinion of the merits of the theatres he was practically acquainted with as regarded their construction for the purposes of the bill-seller. His mother, who had been dead a few years, had sold bills, and had put him into the business. His ambition seemed to be to become a general bill-sticker. He could not write but could read very imperfectly. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Vy, you see, sir,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;there&lsquo;s sets off. At the Market (Haymarket), now, there&lsquo;s this: there&lsquo;s only <num value="1">one</num> front, so you may look sharp about for there goes, boxes, pit, and gallery. The &lsquo;Delphis as good that way, and so is the Surrey, but them <num value="1">one</num>&lsquo;s crowded too much. The Lyceum&lsquo;s built shocking orkered. Vy, the boxes is in <num value="1">one</num> street, and the pit in another, and the gallery in another! It&lsquo;s true, sir. The pit&lsquo;s the best customer in most theatres, I think. Ashley&lsquo;s and the Wick is both spoiled that way&mdash;Ashley&lsquo;s perticler&mdash;as the gallery&lsquo;s a good step from the pit and boxes; at the Wick it&lsquo;s round the corner. But the shilling gallery aint so bad at Ashley&lsquo;s. Sadler&lsquo;s Wells I never tried, it&lsquo;s out of the way, and I can&lsquo;t tell you much about the &lsquo;Lympic or the Strand. The Lane is middling. I don&lsquo;t know that either plays or actors makes much difference to me. Perhaps it&lsquo;s rather vorser <pb id="p.289" n="289"> 
<milestone unit=col>
ven it&lsquo;s anything werry prime, as everybody seems to know every think about it aforehand. No, sir, I can&lsquo;t say, sir, that Mr. Macready did me much good. I sometimes runs along by a cab because I&lsquo;ve got a sixpence from a swell for doing it stunnin&lsquo;, but werry seldom, and I don&lsquo;t much like it; though ven you&lsquo;re at it you don&lsquo;t think of no fear. I makes <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or rather more a week at bill-selling, and as much other vays. I never saw a play but once at the Wick. I&lsquo;d rather be at a Free and Heasy. I don&lsquo;t know as I knows any of the actors or actresses, either hes or shes.</QUOTE>
 
<p>The sellers of play-bills purchase their stock of the printer, at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the <num value="100">hundred</num>, or in that proportion for half or quarter-hundreds. If a smaller quantity be purchased, the charge is usually <num value="13">thirteen</num> for <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; though they used to be only <num value="12">twelve</num> for <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> These sellers are among the poorest of the poor; after they have had <num value="1">one</num> meal, they do not know how to get another. They reside in the lowest localities, and some few are abandoned and profligate in character. They reckon it a good night to earn <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> clear, but upon an average they clear but <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> per week. They lose sometimes by not selling out their nightly stock. What they have left, they are obliged to sell for waste-paper at <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> per lb. Christmas, Easter, and Whitsuntide are generally their best times&mdash;they will then make <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
per night clear. The printer of the play-bills prints but a certain number, the demand being nearly ascertained week by week. These are all sold (by the printer or some person appointed) to the regular customers, in preference to others, but the &ldquo;irregulars&rdquo; can get supplied though often not without trouble. The profit on all sold is rather more than cent. per cent. As I have intimated, when some theatres are closed, the bill-sellers are driven to others; and as the demand is necessarily limited, a superflux of sellers affects the profits, and then <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> is considered a good week&lsquo;s work. During the opera season, I am told, a few mechanics, out of work, will sell bills there and books of the opera, making about <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week, and doing better than the regular hands, as they have a better address and are better clad. 
<p>Taking the profits at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week at cent. per cent. on the outlay, and reckoning <num value="200">200</num> sellers, including those at the saloons, concert-rooms, &amp;c., we find that <num value="60">60</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is now expended weekly on play-bills purchased in the streets of London. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.203"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Periodicals, Pamphlets, Tracts, Books, Etc.</head>

<p>THESE street-sellers are a numerous body, and the majority of them show a greater degree of industry and energy than is common to many classes of street-folk. They have been for the most part connected with the paper, newspaper, or publishing trade, and some of them have &ldquo;known better days.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> intelligent man I met with, a dealer in &ldquo;waste&rdquo; (paper), had been brought up as a compositor, but late hours and glaring gas-lights in the printing-office 
<milestone unit=col>
affected his eyes, he told me; and as a half-blind compositor was about of as little value, he thought, as a &ldquo;horse with a wooden leg,&rdquo; he abandoned his calling for out-of-door labour. Another had been a gun-smith, and when out of his apprenticeship was considered a &ldquo;don hand at hair triggers, for hair triggers were more wanted then,&rdquo; but an injury to his right hand and arm had disabled him as a mechanic, and he had recourse to the streets. A <num value="3">third</num> had been an ink-maker&lsquo;s &ldquo;young man,&rdquo; and had got to like the streets by calling for orders, and delivering bottles of ink, at the shops of the small stationers and chandlers, and so he had taken to them for a living. Of the bookstall- keepers I heard of <num value="1">one</num> man who had died a short time before, and who &ldquo;once had been in the habit of buying better books for his own pleasure than he had afterwards to sell for his bread.&rdquo; Of the book-stall proprietors, I have afterwards spoken more fully. 
<p>All the street-sellers in question are what street estimation pronounces to be educated men; they can all, as far as I could ascertain, read and write, and some of them were &ldquo;keenish politicians, both free-traders, and against free-trade when they was a-talking of the better days when they was young.&rdquo; Nearly all are married men with families. 
<p>The divisions into which these street traffickers may be formed are &mdash; Odd Numbersellers &mdash; Steamboat Newsvendors &mdash; Railway Newsvendors, (though the latter is now hardly a street traffic),&mdash;the Sellers of <num value="2">Second</num> Editions (which I have already given as a portion of the patterers)&mdash;Board-workers (also previously described, and for the same reason)&mdash;Tract-sellers (of whom I have given the number, character, &amp;c., and who are regarded by the other streetsellers as the idlers, beggars, and pretenders of the trade),&mdash;the Sellers of Childrens&rsquo; Books and Song Books&mdash;Book-auctioneers, and Bookstall- keepers. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.204"><head>Of the Street-Sale of Back Numbers.</head>

<p>THIS trade is carried on by the same class of patterers as work race-cards, <num value="2">second</num> editions, &amp;c. The collectors of waste-paper frequently find back numbers of periodicals in &ldquo;a lot&rdquo; they may have purchased at a coffee-shop. These they sell to warehousemen who serve the streetsellers. The largest lot ever sold at <num value="1">one</num> time was some <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="7">seven</num> years ago, of the <hi rend=italics>Pictorial Times</hi>, at least a ton weight. A dealer states&mdash; 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I lost the use of this arm ever since I was <num value="3">three</num> months old. My mother died when I was <num value="10">ten</num> years of age, and after that my father took up with an Irishwoman, and turned me and my youngest sister (she was <num value="2">two</num> years younger than me) out into the streets. My youngest sister got employment at my father&lsquo;s trade, but I couldn&lsquo;t get no work because of my crippled arm. I walked about, till I fell down in the streets for want. At last, a man, who had a sweetmeat-shop, took pity on me. His wife made the sweetmeats, and minded <pb id="p.290" n="290"> 
<milestone unit=col>
the shop while he went out a juggling in the streets, in the Ramo Samee line. He told me as how, if I would go round the country with him and sell a few prints while he was a juggling in the public-houses, he&lsquo;d find me in wittles, and pay my lodging. I joined him, and stopped with him <num value="2">two</num> or <num value="3">three</num> year. After that I went to work for a werry large waste--paper dealer. He used to buy up all the old back numbers of the cheap periodicals and penny publications, and send me out with them to sell at a farden&rsquo; a piece. He used to give me <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> out of every shilling, and I done very well with that, till the periodicals came so low, and so many on &lsquo;em, that they wouldn&lsquo;t sell at all. Sometimes I could make <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> on a Saturday night and a Sunday morning, a-selling the odd numbers of periodicals,&mdash; such as tales; &lsquo;Tales of the Wars,&rsquo; &lsquo;Lives of the Pirates,&rsquo; &lsquo;Lives of the Highwaymen,&rsquo; &amp;c. I&lsquo;ve often sold as many as <num value="2000">2,000</num> numbers on a Saturday night in the New-cut, and the most of them was works about thieves, and highwaymen, and pirates. Besides me, there was <num value="3">three</num> others at the same business. Altogether, I dare say my master alone used to get rid of <num value="10000">10,000</num> copies of such works on a Saturday night and a Sunday morning. Our principal customers was young men. My master made a good bit of money at it. He had been about eighteen years in the business, and had begun with <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
I was with him <num value="15">fifteen</num> year, on and off, and at the best time. I used to earn my <num value="30">30</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week full at that time. But then I was foolish, and didn&lsquo;t take care of my money. When I was at the &lsquo;odd number business,&rsquo; I bought a peepshow, and left the trade to go into that line.</QUOTE>
 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.205"><head>Of the Sale of Waste Newspapers at Billingsgate.</head>

<p>THIS trade is so far peculiar that it is confined to Billingsgate, as in that market alone the demand supplies a livelihood to the man who carries it on. His principal sale is of newspapers to the street-fishmongers, as a large surface of paper is required for the purposes of a fish-stall. The &ldquo;waste&rdquo; trade&mdash;for &ldquo;waste&rdquo; and not &ldquo;waste-paper&rdquo; is the word always applied&mdash;is not carried on with such facility as might be expected, for I was assured that &ldquo;waste&rdquo; is so scarce that only a very insufficient supply of paper can at present be obtained. &ldquo;I hope things will change soon, sir,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> collector, gravely to me, &ldquo;or I shall hardly be able to keep myself and my family on my waste.&rdquo; 
<p>This difficulty, however, does not affect such a street-seller as the man at Billingsgate, who buys of the collectors&mdash;&ldquo;collecting,&rdquo; however, a portion himself at the neighbouring coffeeshops, public-houses, &amp;c.; for the wants of a regular customer must, by some means or other, be supplied. 
<p>The Billingsgate paper-seller carries his paper round, offering it to his customers, or to those he wishes to make purchasers; some fishmongers, 
<milestone unit=col>
however, obtain their &ldquo;waste&rdquo; <num value="1">first</num>-hand from the collectors, or buy it at a news-agent&lsquo;s. 
<p>The retail price varies from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="3.50">3 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the pound, but <num value="3.50">3 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> is only given for &ldquo;very clean and prime, and perhaps uncut,&rdquo; newspapers; for when a newsvendor has, as it is called, &ldquo;over-stocked&rdquo; himself, he sells the uncut papers at last to the collector, or the &ldquo;waste&rdquo; consumer. This happens, I was told, <num value="20">twenty</num> times as often with the &ldquo;weeklys&rdquo; as the &ldquo;dailys;&rdquo; for, said my informant, &ldquo;suppose it&lsquo;s a wet Sunday morning&mdash;and all newsvendors as does pray, prays for wet Sundays, because then people stays at home and buys a paper, or some number, to read and pass away the time. Well, sir, suppose it&lsquo;s a soaker in the morning, the newsman buys a good lot, an extra <num value="9">nine</num>, or <num value="2">two</num> extra nines, or the like of that, and then may be, after all, it comes out a fine day, and so he&lsquo;s over-stocked; in which case there&lsquo;s some for the waste.&rdquo; 
<p>When they consider it a favourable opportunity, the workers carry waste to offer to the Billingsgate salesmen; but the chief trade is in the hands of the regular frequenter of the market. 
<p>From the best information I could cbtain, it appears that from <num value="70">70</num> to <measure value="100l." type=currency><num value="100">100</num> pounds</measure> weight of &ldquo;waste&rdquo;&mdash;about <num value="3">three</num>-fourths being newspapers, of which some are foreign&mdash;is supplied to Billingsgate market and its visitants. <num value="2">Two</num> numbers of the <hi rend=italics>Times</hi>, with their supplements, <num value="1">one</num> paper-buyer told me, &ldquo;when cleverly damped, and they&lsquo;re never particularly dry,&rdquo; will weigh about a pound. The average price is not less than <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a pound, or from that to <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> A single paper is <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> At <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> per pound, and <measure value="85l." type=currency><num value="85">85</num> pounds</measure> a day, upwards of <num value="275">275</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is spent yearly in waste paper at Billingsgate, in the street or open-air purchase alone. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.206"><head>Of the Sale of Periodicals on the Steam- Boats and Steam-Boat Piers.</head>

<p>IN this traffic are engaged about <num value="20">20</num> men, &ldquo;when the days are light until <num value="8">eight</num> o&lsquo;clock;&rdquo; from <num value="10">10</num> to <num value="15">15</num>, if the winter be a hard winter; and if the river steamers are unable to run&mdash; none at all. This winter, however, there has been no cessation in the running of the &ldquo;boats,&rdquo; except on a few foggy days. The steam-boat paper-sellers are generally traders on their own account (all, I believe, have been connected with the newsvendors&rsquo; trade); some few are the servants of newsvenders, sent out to deal at the wharfs and on board the boats. 
<p>The trade is not so remunerative that any payment is made to the proprietors of the boats or wharfs for the privilege of selling papers there (as in the case of the railways), but it is necessary to &ldquo;obtain leave,&rdquo; from those who have authority to give it. 
<p>The steam-boat paper-seller steps on board a few minutes before the boat starts, when there are a sufficient number of voyagers assembled. He traverses the deck and dives into the cabins, offering his &ldquo;papers,&rdquo; the titles of which he <pb id="p.291" n="291"> 
<milestone unit=col>
announces: &ldquo;Punch, penny Puch, <hi rend=italics>real</hi> Punch, last number for <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&mdash;comic sheets, a penny&mdash; all the London periodicals &mdash; Guide to the Thames.&rdquo; 
<p>From <num value="1">one</num> of these frequenters of steam-boats for the purposes of his business, I had the following account: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I was a news-agent&lsquo;s boy, sir, near a pier, for <num value="3">three</num> or <num value="4">four</num> year, then I got a start for myself, and now I serve a pier. It&lsquo;s not such a trade as you might think, still it&lsquo;s bread and cheese and a drop of beer. I go on board to sell my papers. It&lsquo;s seldom I sell a newspaper; there&lsquo;s no call for it on the river, except at the foreign-going ships&mdash;a few as is sold to them&mdash;but I don&lsquo;t serve none on &lsquo;em. People reads the news for nothing at the coffee-shops when they breakfasts, I s&lsquo;pose, and goes on as if they took in the <hi rend=italics>Times, Chron</hi>, and &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>Tiser</hi>&mdash;pubs. we calls the &lsquo;<hi rend=italics>Tiser</hi>&mdash;all to their own cheek. It&lsquo;s penny works I sell the most of; indeed, it&lsquo;s very seldom I offer anything else, &lsquo;cause it&lsquo;s little use. Penny Punches is fair sale, and I calls it &lsquo;Punch&rsquo;&mdash;just Punch. It&lsquo;s dead now, I believe, but there&lsquo;s old numbers; still they&lsquo;ll be done in time. The real Punch&mdash;I sell from <num value="6">six</num> to <num value="12">twelve</num> a week&mdash;I call that there as the reel Punch. Galleries of Comicalities is a middling sale; people take them home with them, I think. Guides to the Thames is good in summer. They&lsquo;re illustrated; but people sometimes grumbles and calls them catchpennies. It ain&lsquo;t my fault if they&lsquo;re not all that&lsquo;s expected, but people expects everything for <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> Joe Millers and &lsquo;Stophelees&rdquo; (Mephistopheles) &ldquo;I&lsquo;ve sold, and said they was oppositions to Punch; that&lsquo;s a year or more back, but they was old, and to be had cheap. I sell Lloyd&lsquo;s and Reynolds&lsquo;s pennies &mdash;fairish, both of them; so&lsquo;s the Family Herald and the London Journal&mdash;very fair. I don&lsquo;t venture on any <num value="3">three</num>-halfpenny books on anything like a spec., acause people says at once: &lsquo;A penny&mdash;I&lsquo;ll give you a penny.&rsquo; I sell <num value="7">seven</num> out of <num value="8">eight</num> of what I do sell to gents.; more than that, perhaps; for you&lsquo;ll not often see a woman buy nothing wots intended to improve her mind. A young woman, like a maid of all work, buys sometimes and looks hard at the paper; but I sometimes thinks it&lsquo;s to show she can read. A summer Sunday&lsquo;s my best time, out and out. There&lsquo;s new faces then, and <num value="1">one</num> goes on bolder. I&lsquo;ve known young gents. buy, just to offer to young women, I&lsquo;m pretty well satisfied. It&lsquo;s a introduction. <hi rend=italics>I have</hi> met with real gentlemen. They&lsquo;ve looked over all I offered for sale and then said: &lsquo;Nothing I want, my good fellow, but here&lsquo;s a penny for your trouble.&rsquo; I wish there was more of them. I do sincerely. Sometimes I&lsquo;ve gone on board and not sold <num value="1">one</num> paper. I buy in the regular way, <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for a dozen (sometimes <num value="13">thirteen</num> to the dozen) of penny pubs. I don&lsquo;t know what I make, for I keep no count; perhaps a sov. in a good week and a half in another.</QUOTE>
 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>I am informed that the average earnings of these traders, altogether, may be taken at <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
weekly; calculating that <num value="12">twelve</num> carry on the trade the year through, we find that (assuming each man to sell at <num value="33">thirty-three</num> per cent. profit&mdash;though in the case of old works it will be cent. per cent.) upwards of <num value="1500">1,500</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> are expended annually in steam-boat papers. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.207"><head>Of the Sale of Newspapers, Books, &amp;C., at the Railway Stations.</head>

<p>ALTHOUGH the sale of newspapers at the railway termini, &amp;c., cannot strictly be classed as a street-sale, it is so far an open-air traffic as to require some brief notice, and it has now become a trade of no small importance. 
<p>The privilege of selling to railway-passengers, within the precincts of the terminus, is disposed of by tender. At present the newsvendor on the North-Western Line, I am informed, pays to the company, for the right of sale at the Eustonsquare terminus, and the provincial stations, as large a sum as <num value="1700">1,700</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> per annum. The amount usually given is of course in proportion to the number of stations, and the traffic of the railway. 
<p>The purchaser of this exclusive privilege sends his own servants to sell the newspapers and books, which he supplies to them in the quantity required. The men thus engaged are paid from <num value="20">20</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="30">30</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week, and the boys receive from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> weekly, but rarely <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>

<p>All the morning and evening papers are sold at the Station, but of the weekly press, those are sent for sale which in the manager&lsquo;s judgment are likely to sell, or which his agent informs him are &ldquo;asked for.&rdquo; It is the same with the weekly unstamped publications. The reason seems obvious; if there be more than can be sold, a dead loss is incurred, for the surplusage, as regards newspapers, is only saleable as waste paper. 
<p>The books sold at railways are nearly all of the class best known as &ldquo;light reading,&rdquo; or what some account light reading. The price does not often exceed <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; and among the books offered for sale in these places are novels in <num value="1">one</num> volume, published at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&mdash;sometimes in <num value="2">two</num> volumes, at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> each; &ldquo;monthly parts&rdquo; of works issued in weekly numbers; shilling books of poetry; but rarely political or controversial pamphlets. <num value="1">One</num> man, who understood this trade, told me that &ldquo;a few of the pamphlets about the Pope and Cardinal Wiseman sold at <num value="1">first</num>; but in a month or <num value="6">six</num> weeks, people began to say, &lsquo;A shilling for that! I&lsquo;m sick of the thing.&rsquo;&rdquo; 
<p>The large sum given for the privilege of an exclusive sale, shows that the number of books and papers sold at railway stations must be very considerable. But it must be borne in mind, that the price, and consequently the profit on the daily newspapers, sold at the railways, is greater than elsewhere. None are charged less than <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, the regular price at a news-agent&lsquo;s shop being <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, so that as the cost price is <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
 <pb id="p.292" n="292"> 
<milestone unit=col>
the profit is double. Nor is it unusual for a passenger by an early train, who grows impatient for his paper, to cry out, &ldquo;A shilling for the <hi rend=italics>Times!</hi>&rdquo; This, however, is only the case, I am told, with those who start very early in the morning; for the daily papers are obtained for the railway stations from among the earliest impressions, and can be had at the accustomed price as early as <num value="6">six</num> o&lsquo;clock, although, if there be exciting news and a great demand, a larger amount may be given. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.208"><head>Of the Street Booksellers.</head>

<p>THE course of my inquiry now leads me to consider <num value="1">one</num> of the oldest, and certainly not least important of the street traffics&mdash;that of the book-stalls. Of these there are now about <num value="20">twenty</num> in the London streets, but in this number I include only those which are <hi rend=italics>properly</hi>
street-stalls. Many book-stalls, as in such a locality as the London-road, are appendages to shops, being merely a display of wares outside the bookseller&lsquo;s premises; and with these I do not now intend to deal. 
<p>The men in this trade I found generally to be intelligent. They have been, for the most part, engaged in some minor department of the bookselling or newspaper trade, in the regular way, and are unconnected with the street-sellers in other lines, of whose pursuits, habits, and characters, they seem to know nothing. 
<p>The street book-stalls are most frequent in the thoroughfares which are well-frequented, but which, as <num value="1">one</num> man in the trade expressed himself, are not so &ldquo;shoppy&rdquo; as others&mdash;such as the City-road, the New-road, and the Old Kent-road. &ldquo;If there&lsquo;s what you might call a recess,&rdquo; observed another street bookstall- keeper, &ldquo;<hi rend=italics>that&lsquo;s</hi> the place for us; and you&lsquo;ll often see us along with flower-stands and pinners-up.&rdquo; The stalls themselves do not present any very smart appearance; they are usually of plain deal. If the stock of books be sufficiently ample, they are disposed on the surface of the stall, &ldquo;fronts up,&rdquo; as I heard it described, with the titles, when lettered on the back, like as they are presented in a library. If the &ldquo;front&rdquo; be unlettered, as is often the case with the older books, a piece of paper is attached, and on it is inscribed the title and the price. Sometimes the description is exceeding curt, as, &ldquo;Poetry,&rdquo; &ldquo;French,&rdquo; &ldquo;Religious,&rdquo; &ldquo;Latin&rdquo; (I saw an odd volume, in Spanish, of Don Quixote, marked &ldquo;Latin,&rdquo; but it was at a shop-seller&lsquo;s stall,) &ldquo;Pamphlets,&rdquo; and such like; or where it seems to have been thought necessary to give a somewhat fuller appellation, such titles are written out as &ldquo;Locke&lsquo;s Understanding,&rdquo; &ldquo;Watts&lsquo;s Mind,&rdquo; or &ldquo;Pope&lsquo;s Rape.&rdquo; If the stock be rather scant, the side of the book is then shown, and is either covered with white paper, on which the title and price are written, or &ldquo;brushed,&rdquo; or else a piece of paper is attached, with the necessary announcement. 
<p>Sometimes these announcements are striking 
<milestone unit=col>
enough, as where a number of works of the same size have been bound together (which used to be the case, I am told, more frequently than it is now); or where there has been a series of stories in <num value="1">one</num> volume. <num value="1">One</num> such announcement was, &ldquo;Smollett&lsquo;s Peregrine Pickle Captain Kyd Pirate Prairie Rob of the Bowl Bamfyeld Moore Carew <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&rdquo; Alongside this miscellaneous volume was, &ldquo;Wilberforce&lsquo;s Practical View of Christianity, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>;&rdquo; &ldquo;Fenelon&lsquo;s Aventures de T&eacute;l&eacute;maque, plates, <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>;&rdquo; &ldquo;Arres, de Predestinatione, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&rdquo; (the last-mentioned work, which, at the <num value="1">first</num> glance, seems as if it were an odd mixture of French and Latin, was a Latin quarto); &ldquo;Coronis ad Collationem Hagiensem, &amp;c. &amp;c., Gulielmo Amesio.&rdquo; Another work, on another stall, had the following description: &ldquo;Lord Mount Edgecumbe&lsquo;s Opera What is Currency Watts&lsquo;s Scripture History Thoughts on Taxation only <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&rdquo; Another was, &ldquo;Knickerbocker Bacon <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&rdquo; As a rule, however, the correctness with which the work is described is rather remarkable. 
<p>At some few of the street-stalls, and at many of the shop-stalls, are boxes, containing works marked, &ldquo;All <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>,&rdquo; or <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, or <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> Among these are old Court-Guides, Parliamentary Companions, Railway Plans, and a variety of sermons, and theological, as well as educational and political pamphlets. To show the character of the publications thus offered&mdash;not, perhaps, as a rule, but generally enough, for sale&mdash; I copied down the titles of some at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> and <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p><hi rend=italics>All these at</hi> <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&mdash;&lsquo;Letters to the Right Honourable Lord John Russell, on State Education, by Edward Baines, jun.;&rsquo; &lsquo;A Pastoral Letter to the Clergy and Members of the Protestant Episcopal Church in the United States of America;&rsquo; &lsquo;A Letter to the Protestant Dissenters of England and Wales, by the Rev. Robert Ainslie;&rsquo; &lsquo;Friendly Advice to Conservatives;&rsquo; &lsquo;Elementary Thoughts on the Principles of Currency and Wealth, and on the Means of Diminishing the Burthens of the People, by J. D. Basset, Esq., price <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&rsquo;&rdquo; The others were each published at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>

<p><hi rend=italics>All these at</hi> <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&mdash;&lsquo;Poems, by Eleanor Tatlock, <datestruct value="1811--"><year reg="1811">1811</year></datestruct>, <num value="2">2</num> vols., <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>;&rsquo; &lsquo;<num value="2">Two</num> Sermons, on the Fall and Final Restoration of the Jews, by the Rev. John Stuart;&rsquo; &lsquo;Thoughts and Feelings, by Arthur Brooke, <datestruct value="1820--"><year reg="1820">1820</year></datestruct>;&rsquo; &lsquo;The Amours of Philander and Sylvia, being the <num value="3">third</num> and last part of Love-letters between a Nobleman and his Sister. Volume the <num value="2">Second</num>. The <num value="7">Seventh</num> Edition. London.&rsquo;</QUOTE>
 
<p>From a cursory examination of the lastmen- tioned twopenny volume, I could see nothing of the nobleman or his sister. It is <num value="1">one</num> of an inane class of books, originated, I believe, in the latter part of the reign of Charles II. Such publications professed to be (and some few were) records of the court and city scandal of the day, but in general they were works founded on the reputation of the current scandal. In short, to adopt the language of patterers, they were &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; issued by the publishers of that period; and 
<FIGURE id="Fig.292"><HEAD>ZZZ</HEAD></FIGURE>

<FIGURE id="Fig.292.1"><head>This originally was an illustration to &ldquo;Thump em the Drummer,&rdquo; in <num value="1">one</num> of Fairburn&lsquo;s Song-books.</head></figure>
<pb id="p.293" n="293"> 
<milestone unit=col>
they continued to be published until the middle of the eighteenth century, or a little later. I notice this description of literature the more, particularly as it is still frequently to be met with in street-sale. &ldquo;There&lsquo;s oft enough,&rdquo; <num value="1">one</num> street-bookseller said to me, &ldquo;works of that sort making up a &lsquo;lot&rsquo; at a sale, and in very respectable rooms. As if they were make-weights, or to make up a sufficient number of books, and so they keep their hold in the streets.&rdquo; 
<p>As many of my readers may have little, if any, knowledge of this class of street-sold works, I cite a portion of the &ldquo;epistle dedicatory,&rdquo; and a specimen of the style, of &ldquo;Philander and Sylvia,&rdquo; to show the change in street, as well as in general literature, as no such works are now published: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>To the Lord Spencer, My Lord, when a new book comes into the world, the <num value="1">first</num> thing we consider is the dedication; and according to the quality and humour of the patron, we are apt to make a judgment of the following subject. If to a statesman we believe it grave and politic; if to a gownman, law or divinity; if to the young and gay, love and gallantry. By this rule, I believe the gentle reader, who finds your lordship&lsquo;s name prefixed before this, will make as many various opinions of it, as they do characters of your lordship, whose youthful sallies have been the business of so much discourse; and which, according to the relator&lsquo;s sense or good nature, is either aggravated or excused; though the woman&lsquo;s quarrel to your lordship has some more reasonable foundation, than that of your own sex; for your lordship being formed with all the beauties and graces of mankind, all the charms of wit, youth, and sweetness of disposition (derived to you from an illustrious race of heroes) adapting you to the noblest love and softness, they cannot but complain on that mistaken conduct of yours, that so lavishly deals out those agreeable attractions, squandering away that youth and time on many, which might be more advantageously dedicated to some <num value="1">one</num> of the fair; and by a liberty (which they call not being discreet enough) rob them of all the hopes of conquest over that heart which they believe can fix no where; they cannot caress you into ameness; or if you sometimes appear so, they are still upon their guard with you; for like a young lion you are ever apt to leap into your natural wildness; the greatness of your soul disdaining to be confined to lazy repose; though the delicacy of your person and constitution so absolutely require it; your lordship not being made for diversions so rough and fatiguing, as those your active mind would impose upon it.</QUOTE>
 
<p>The last sentence is very long, so that a shorter extract may serve as a specimen of the staple of this book-making: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>To Philander,&mdash;False and perjured as you are, I languish for a sight of you, and conjure you to give it me as soon as this comes to your hands. Imagine not that I have prepared those instruments of revenge that are so justly due to your perfidy; but rather, that I have yet too tender sentiments for you, in spite of the outrage you have done my heart; and that for all the ruin you have made, I still adore you: and though I know you are now another&lsquo;s slave, yet I beg you would vouchsafe to behold the spoils you have made, and allow me this recompense for all, to say&mdash;Here was the beauty I once esteemed, though now she is no more Philander&lsquo;s Sylvia.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Having thus described what may be considered the divisional parts of this stall trade, I proceed to the more general character of the class of books sold. 
<milestone unit=col>

<div2 type=section id="c.15.209"><head>Of the Character of Books of the Street-Sale.</head>

<p>THERE has been a change, and in some respects a considerable change, in the character or class of books sold at the street-stalls, within the last <num value="40">40</num> or <num value="50">50</num> years, as I have ascertained from the most experienced men in the trade. Now sermons, or rather the works of the old divines, are rarely seen at these stalls, or if seen, are rarely purchased. Black-letter editions are very unfrequent at street book-stalls, and it is <num value="20">twenty</num> times more difficult, I am assured, for street-sellers to pick up anything really rare and curious, than it was in the early part of the century. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> reason assigned for this change by an intelligent street-seller was, that black-letter or any ancient works, were almost all purchased by the <num value="2">second</num>-hand booksellers, who have shops and issue catalogues, as they had a prompt sale for them whenever they could pick them up at book-auctions or elsewhere. &ldquo;Ay, indeed,&rdquo; said another book-stall keeper, &ldquo;anything scarce or curious, when it&lsquo;s an old book, is kept out of the streets; if it&lsquo;s not particular decent, sir,&rdquo; (with a grin), &ldquo;why it&lsquo;s reckoned all the more curious,&mdash;that&lsquo;s the word, sir, I know,&mdash; &lsquo;curious.&rsquo; I can tell how many beans make <num value="5">five</num> as well as you or anybody. Why, now, there&lsquo;s a <num value="2">second</num>-hand bookseller not a <num value="100">hundred</num> miles from Holborn&mdash;and a pleasant, nice man he is, and does a respectable business&mdash; and he puts to the end of his catalogue&mdash;they all have catalogues that&lsquo;s in a good way&mdash;<num value="2">two</num> pages that he calls &lsquo;Faceti&aelig;.&rsquo; They&lsquo;re titles and prices of queer old books in all languages&mdash; indecent books, indeed. He sends his catalogues to a many clergymen and learned people; and to any that he thinks wouldn&lsquo;t much admire seeing his &lsquo;Faceti&aelig;,&rsquo; he pulls the last leaf out, and sends his catalogue, looking finished without it. Those last <num value="2">two</num> pages aren&lsquo;t at all the worst part of his trade among buyers that&lsquo;s worth money.&rdquo; 
<p>In <num value="1">one</num> respect a characteristic of this trade is unaltered; I allude to the prevalence of &ldquo;odd volumes&rdquo; at the cheaper stalls,&mdash;not the odd volumes of a novel, but more frequently of <num value="1">one</num> of the essayists&mdash;the &ldquo;Spectator&rdquo; especially. <num value="1">One</num> stall-keeper told me, that if he purchased an old edition of the &ldquo;Spectator,&rdquo; in <num value="8">eight</num> vols., he could more readily sell it in single volumes, at <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each, than sell the <num value="8">eight</num> vols. altogether for <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, or even <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, though this was but <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
a volume. 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>There&lsquo;s nothing in my trade,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> street-bookseller with whom I conversed on the subject, &ldquo;that sells better, or indeed so well, as English classics. I can&lsquo;t offer to draw fine distinctions, and I&lsquo;m just speaking of my own plain way of trade; but <hi rend=italics>I</hi> call English classics such works as the &lsquo;Spectator,&rsquo; &lsquo;Tatler,&rsquo; &lsquo;Guardian,&rsquo; &lsquo;Adventurer,&rsquo; &lsquo;Rambler,&rsquo; &lsquo;Rasellas,&rsquo; &lsquo;The Vicar of Wakefield,&rsquo; &lsquo;Peregrine Pickle,&rsquo; &lsquo;Tom Jones, &lsquo;Goldsmith&lsquo;s His- <pb id="p.294" n="294"> 
<milestone unit=col>
tories of Greece, Rome, and England&rsquo; (they all sell quick), &lsquo;Enfield&lsquo;s Speaker,&rsquo; &lsquo;mixed plays,&rsquo; the &lsquo;Sentimental Journey,&rsquo; no, sir, &lsquo;Tristram Shandy,&rsquo; rather hangs on hand, the &lsquo;Pilgrim&lsquo;s Progress&rsquo; (but it must be sold <hi rend=italics>very</hi>
low), &lsquo;Robinson Crusoe,&rsquo; &lsquo;Philip Quarles,&rsquo; &lsquo;Telemachus,&rsquo; &lsquo;Gil Blas,&rsquo; and &lsquo;Junius&lsquo;s Letters.&rsquo; I don&lsquo;t remember more at this moment, such as are of good sale. I haven&lsquo;t included poetry, because I&lsquo;m speaking of English classics, and of course they must be oldish works to be classics.</QUOTE>
 
<p>Concerning the street sale of poetical works I learned from street book-sellers, that their 
<hi rend=italics>readiest</hi> sale was of volumes of Shakespeare, Pope, Thomson, Goldsmith, Cowper, Burns, Byron, and Scott. &ldquo;You must recollect, sir,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> dealer, &ldquo;that in nearly all those poets there&lsquo;s a double chance for sale at book-stalls. For what with old editions, and new and cheap editions, there&lsquo;s always plenty in the market, and very low. No, I can&lsquo;t say I could sell Milton as quickly as any of those mentioned, nor &lsquo;Hudibras,&rsquo; nor &lsquo;Young&lsquo;s Night Thoughts,&rsquo; nor Prior, nor Dryden, nor &lsquo;Gay&lsquo;s Fables.&rsquo; It&lsquo;s seldom that we have any works of Hood, or Shelley, or Coleridge, or Wordsworth, or Moore at street stalls&mdash;you don&lsquo;t often see them, I think, at booksellers&rsquo; stalls&mdash;for they&lsquo;re soon picked up. Poetry sells very fair, take it altogether.&rdquo; 
<p>Another dealer told me that from <num value="20">twenty</num> to <num value="30">thirty</num> years ago there were at the street-stalls a class of works rarely seen now. He had known them in all parts and had disposed of them in his own way of business. He specified the &ldquo;Messiah&rdquo; (Klopstock&lsquo;s) as of this class, the &ldquo;Death of Abel,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Castle of Otranto&rdquo; (&ldquo;but that&lsquo;s seen occasionally still,&rdquo; he observed), the &ldquo;Old English Baron&rdquo; (&ldquo;and that&lsquo;s seen still too, but nothing to what it were once&rdquo;), the &ldquo;Young Man&lsquo;s Best Companion&rdquo; &ldquo;Zimmerman on Solitude,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Burke on the Sublime and Beautiful&rdquo; (&ldquo;but I have that yet sometimes.&rdquo;) These works were of heavy sale in the streets, and my informant thought they had been thrown into the street-trade because the publishers had not found them saleable in the regular way. &ldquo;I was dead sick of the &lsquo;Death of Abel,&rsquo;&rdquo; observed the man, &ldquo;before I could get out of him.&rdquo; Occasionally are to be seen at most of the stalls, works of which the majority of readers have heard, but may not have met with. Among such I saw &ldquo;Laura,&rdquo; by Capel Lloftt, <num value="4">4</num> vols. <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> &ldquo;Darwin&lsquo;s Botanic Garden,&rdquo; <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> &ldquo;Alfred, an Epic Poem,&rdquo; by H. J. Pye, Poet Laureate, <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> &ldquo;C&oelig;lebs in search of a Wife,&rdquo; <num value="2">2</num> vols. in <num value="1">one</num>, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>

<p>The same informant told me that he had lived near an old man who died <num value="25">twenty-five</num> years ago, or it might be more, with whom he was somewhat intimate. This old man had been all his life familiar with the street trade in books, which he had often hawked&mdash;a trade now almost unknown; his neighbour had heard him say that <num value="50">fifty</num> to <num value="70">seventy</num> years ago, he 
<milestone unit=col>
made his <num value="2">two</num> guineas a week &ldquo;without distressing hisself,&rdquo; meaning, I was told, that he was drinking every Monday at least. This old man used to tell that in his day, the &ldquo;Whole Duty of Man,&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Tale of a Tub,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Pomfret&lsquo;s Poems,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Pamela,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Sir Charles Grandison&rdquo; went off <hi rend=italics>well</hi>, but &ldquo;Pamela&rdquo; the best. &ldquo;And I&lsquo;ve heard the old man say, sir,&rdquo; I was further told, &ldquo;how he had to tread his shoes straight about what books he showed publicly. He sold &lsquo;Tom Paine&rsquo; on the sly. If anybody bought a book and would pay a good price for it, <num value="3">three</num> times as much as was marked, he&lsquo;d <hi rend=italics>give</hi> the &lsquo;Age of Reason&rsquo; in. I never see it now, but I don&lsquo;t suppose anybody would interfere if it was offered. A sly trade&lsquo;s always the best for paying, and for selling too. The old fellow used to laugh and say his stall was quite a godly stall, and he wasn&lsquo;t often without a copy or <num value="2">two</num> of the &lsquo;Anti-Jacobin Review,&rsquo; which was all forChurch and State and all that, though he had &lsquo;Tom Paine&rsquo; in a drawer.&rdquo; 
<p>The books sold at the street-stalls are purchased by the retailers either at the auctions of the regular trade, or at &ldquo;chance,&rdquo; or general auctions, or of the Jews or others who may have bought books cheap under such circumstances. Often, however, the stall-keeper has a market peculiarly his own. It is not uncommon for working men or tradesmen, if they become &ldquo;beaten-down and poor&rdquo; to carry a basket-full of books to a stall-keeper, and say, &ldquo;Here, give me half-a-crown for these.&rdquo; <num value="1">One</num> man had <num value="40">forty</num> parts, each issued at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>, of a Bible, offered to him at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a part, by a mechanic who could not any longer afford to &ldquo;take them in,&rdquo; and was at last obliged to sell off what he had. Of course such things are nearly valueless when imperfect. Very few works are bought for street-stall sale of the regular booksellers. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.210"><head>Of the Experience of a Street Book- Seller.</head>

<p>I now give a statement, furnished to me by an experienced man, as to the nature of his trade, and the class of his customers. Most readers will remember having seen an account in the life of some poor scholar, having read&mdash;and occasionally, in spite of the remonstrances of the stall-keeper&mdash;some work which he was too needy to purchase, and even of his having read it through at intervals. That something of this kind is still to be met with will be found from the following account: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>My customers, sir, are of all sorts,&rdquo; my informant said. &ldquo;They&lsquo;re gentlemen on their way from the City, that have to pass along here by the City-road. Bankers&rsquo; clerks, very likely, or insurance-office clerks, or such like. They&lsquo;re fairish customers, but they often screw me. Why only last month a gentleman I know very well by sight, and I see him pass in his brougham in bad weather, took up an old Latin book&mdash;if I remember right it was an odd volume <pb id="p.295" n="295"> 
<milestone unit=col>
of a French edition of Horace&mdash;and though it was marked only <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, it was long before he would consent to give more than <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> And I should never have got my price if I hadn&lsquo;t heard him say quite hastily, when he took up the book, &lsquo;The very thing I&lsquo;ve long been looking for!&rsquo; Mechanics are capital customers for scientific or trade books, such as suit their business; and so they often are for geography and history, and some for poetry; but <hi rend=italics>they&lsquo;re</hi> not so screwy. I know a many such who are rare ones for searching into knowledge. Women buy very little of me in comparison to men; sometimes an odd novel, in <num value="1">one</num> volume, when its cheap, such as &lsquo;The Pilot,&rsquo; or &lsquo;The Spy,&rsquo; or &lsquo;The Farmer of Inglewood Forest,&rsquo; or &lsquo;The Monk.&rsquo; No doubt some buy &lsquo;The Monk,&rsquo; not knowing exactly what sort of a book it is, but just because it&lsquo;s a romance; but some young men buy it, I know, because they have learned what sort it&lsquo;s like. Old <num value="3">three</num> vol. novels won&lsquo;t sell at all, if they&lsquo;re ever so cheap. Boys very seldom buy of me, unless it&lsquo;s a work about pigeons, or something that way. 
<p>I can&lsquo;t say that odd vols. of Annual Registers are anything but a bad sale, but odd vols. of old Mags. (magazines), a year or half-year bound together, are capital. Old London Mags., or Ladies&rsquo;, or Oxford and Cambridges, or Town and Countrys, or Universals, or Monthly Reviews, or Humourists, or Ramblers, or Europeans, or any of any sort, that&lsquo;s from <num value="40">40</num> to <num value="100">100</num> years old, no matter what they are, go off rapidly at from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each, according to size, and binding, and condition. Odd numbers of Mags. are good for little at a stall. The old Mags. in vols. are a sort of reading a great many are very fond of. Lives of the Princess Charlotte are a ready penny enough. So are Queen Carolines, but not so good. Dictionaries of all kinds are nearly as selling as the old Mags., and so are good Latin books. French are only middling; not so well as you might think.</QUOTE>
 
<p>My informant then gave me a similar account to what I had previously received concerning English classics, and proceeded: &ldquo;Old religious books, they&lsquo;re a fair trade enough, but they&lsquo;re not so plentiful on the stalls now, and if they&lsquo;re black-letter they don&lsquo;t find their way from the auctions or anywhere to any places but the shops or to private purchasers. Mrs. Rowe&lsquo;s &lsquo;Knowledge of the Heart&rsquo; goes off, if old. Bibles, and Prayer-books, and Hymn-books, are very bad.&rdquo; [This may be accounted for by the cheapness of these publications, when new, and by the facilities afforded to obtain them gratuitously.] &ldquo;Annuals are dull in going off; very much so, though <num value="1">one</num> might expect different. I can hardly sell &lsquo;Keepsakes&rsquo; at all. Children&lsquo;s books, such as are out <num value="1">one</num> year at <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> apiece, very nicely got up, sell finely next year at the stalls for from <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> Genteel people buy them of us for presents at holiday times. They&lsquo;ll give an extra penny quite cheerfully if there&lsquo;s &lsquo;Price <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&rsquo; or &lsquo;Price <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>&rsquo; lettered on the back or part of the title-page. School-books in good 
<milestone unit=col>
condition don&lsquo;t stay long on hand, especially Pinnock&lsquo;s. There&lsquo;s not a few people who stand and read and read for half an hour or an hour at a time. It&lsquo;s very trying to the temper when they take up room that way, and prevent others seeing the works, and never lay out a penny theirselves. But they seem quite lost in a book. Well, I&lsquo;m sure I don&lsquo;t know what they are. Some seem very poor, judging by their dress, and some seem shabby genteels. I can&lsquo;t help telling them, when I see them going, that I&lsquo;m much obliged, and I hope that perhaps next time they&lsquo;ll manage to say &lsquo;thank ye,&rsquo; for they don&lsquo;t open their lips once in <num value="20">twenty</num> times. I know a man in the trade that goes dancing mad when he has customers of this sort, who aren&lsquo;t customers. I dare say, <num value="1">one</num> day with another, I earn <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the year through; wet days are greatly against us, for if we have a cover people won&lsquo;t stop to look at a stall. Perhaps the rest of my trade earn the same.&rdquo; This man told me that he was not unfrequently asked, and by respectable people, for indecent works, but he recommended them to go to Holywellstreet themselves. He believed that some of his fellow-traders <hi rend=italics>did</hi> supply such works, but to no great extent. 
<p>An elderly man, who had known the street book-trade for many years, but was not concerned in it when I saw him, told me that he was satisfied he had sold old books, old plays often, to Charles Lamb, whom he described as a stuttering man, who, when a book suited him, sometimes laid down the price, and smiled and nodded, and then walked away with it in his pocket or under his arm, without a word having been exchanged. When we came to speak of dates, I found that my informant&mdash;who had only conjectured that this was Lamb&mdash;was unquestionably mistaken. <num value="1">One</num> of the best customers he ever had for anything old or curious, and in Italian, if he remembered rightly, as well as in English, was the late Rev. Mr. Scott, who was chaplain on board the Victory, at the time of Nelson&lsquo;s death at Trafalgar. &ldquo;He had a living in Yorkshire, I believe it was,&rdquo; said the man, &ldquo;and used to come up every now and then to town. I was always glad to see his white head and rosy face, and to have a little talk with him about books and trade, though it wasn&lsquo;t always easy to catch what he said, for he spoke quick, and not very distinct. But he was a pleasant old gentleman, and talked to a poor man as politely as he might to an admiral. He was very well known in my trade, as I was then employed.&rdquo; 
<p>The same man once sold to a gentleman, he told me, and he believed it was somewhere about <num value="25">twenty-five</num> years ago, if not more, a Spanish or Portuguese work, but what it was he did not know. It was marked <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, being a goodsized book, but the stall-keeper was tired of having had it a long time, so that he gladly would have taken <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> for it. The gentleman in question handed him half-a-crown, and, as he had not the change, the purchaser said: &ldquo;O, <pb id="p.296" n="296"> 
<milestone unit=col>
don&lsquo;t mind; it&lsquo;s worth far more than halfa- crown to me.&rdquo; When this liberal customer had walked away, a gentleman who had been standing at the stall all the time, and who was an occasional buyer, said, &ldquo;Do you know him?&rdquo; and, on receiving an answer in the negative, he rejoined, &ldquo;That&lsquo;s Southey.&rdquo; 
<p>Another stall-keeper told me that his customers&mdash;some of whom he supplied with any periodical in the same way as a newsvendor&mdash; had now and then asked him, especially &ldquo;the ladies of the family,&rdquo; who glanced, when they passed, at the contents of his stall, why he had not newer works? &ldquo;I tell them,&rdquo; said the stall-keeper, &ldquo;that they haven&lsquo;t become cheap enough yet for the streets, but that they would come to it in time.&rdquo; After some conversation about his trade, which only confirmed the statements I have given, he said laughingly, &ldquo;Yes, indeed, you all come to such as me at last. Why, last night I heard a song about all the stateliest buildings coming to the ivy, and I thought, as I listened, it was the same with authors. The best that the best can do is the book-stall&lsquo;s food at last. And no harm, for he&lsquo;s in the best of company, with Shakespeare, and all the great people.&rdquo; 
<p>Calculating <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> weekly as the average earnings of the street book-stall keepers&mdash;for further information induces me to think that the street bookseller who earned <num value="18">18</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week regularly, cleared it by having a &ldquo;tidy pitch&rdquo;&mdash;and reckoning that, to clear such an amount, the bookseller takes, at least, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> <num value="11">11</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> weekly, we find <num value="5460">5,460</num> guineas yearly expended in the purchase of books at the purely street-stalls, independently of what is laid out at the open-air stalls connected with book-shops. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.211"><head>Of Street Book-auctioneers.</head>

<p>THE sale of books by auction, in the streets, is now inconsiderable and irregular. The &ldquo;auctioning&rdquo; of books&mdash;I mean of new books&mdash;some of which were published principally with a view to their sale by auction, was, <num value="30">thirty</num> to <num value="40">forty</num> years ago, systematic and extensive. It was not strictly a street-sale. The auctioneer offered his books to the public, <num value="9">nine</num> cases out of <num value="10">ten</num>, in town, in an apartment (now commonly known as a &ldquo;mock-auction room&rdquo;), which was so far a portion of the street that access was rendered easier by the removal of the door and window of any room on a ground-floor, and some of the bidders could and did stand in the street and take part in the proceedings. In the suburbs&mdash; which at that period were not so integral a portion of the metropolis as at present&mdash;the book-auction sales were carried on strictly in the open air, generally in front of a public-house, and either on a platform erected for the purpose, or from a covered cart; the books then being deposited in the vehicle, and the auctioneer standing on a sort of stage placed on the propped--up shafts. In the country, however, the auction was often carried on in an inn. 
<p>The works thus sold were generally standard 
<milestone unit=col>
works. The poems were those of Pope, Young, Thomson, Goldsmith, Falconer, Cowper, &amp;c. The prose writings were such works as &ldquo;The Pilgrim&lsquo;s Progress,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Travels of Mr. Lemuel Gulliver,&rdquo; &ldquo;Johnson&lsquo;s Lives of the Poets,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Vicar of Wakefield,&rdquo; the most popular of the works of Defoe, Fielding, and Smollett, and &ldquo;Hervey&lsquo;s Meditations among the Tombs&rdquo; (at <num value="1">one</num> time highly popular). These books were not correctly printed, they were printed, too, on inferior paper, and the frontispiece&mdash;when there <hi rend=italics>was</hi> a frontispiece&mdash;was often ridiculous. But they certainly gave to the public what is called an &ldquo;impetus&rdquo; for reading. Some were published in London (chiefly by the late Mr. Tegg, who at <num value="1">one</num> time, I am told, himself &ldquo;offered to public competition,&rdquo; by auction, the works he published); others were printed in Edinburgh, Aberdeen, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, Ipswich, Bungay, &amp;c. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> of my informants remembered being present at a street-sale, about <num value="20">twenty</num> or <num value="30">thirty</num> years ago; he perfectly remembered, however, the oratory of the auctioneer, of whom he purchased some books. The sale was in <num value="1">one</num> of the streets in Stoke Newington, a door or <num value="2">two</num> from a thoroughfare. My informant was there&mdash;as he called it&mdash;&ldquo;accidentally,&rdquo; and knew little of the neighbourhood. The auctioneer stood at the door of what appeared to have been a coachhouse, and sold his books, which were arranged within, very rapidly: &ldquo;Byron,&rdquo; he exclaimed; &ldquo;Lord Byron&lsquo;s latest and best po&lsquo;ms. Sixpence! Sixpence! Eightpence! I take penny bids under a shilling. Eightpence for the poems written by a lord&mdash;Gone! Yours, sir&rdquo; (to my informant). The auctioneer, I was told, &ldquo;spoke very rapidly, and clipped many of his words.&rdquo; The work thus sold consisted of some of Byron&lsquo;s minor poems. It was in the pamphlet form, and published, I have no doubt, surreptitiously; for there was, in those days, a bold and frequent piracy of any work which was thought distasteful to the Government, or to which the Court of Chancery might be likely to refuse the protection of the law of copyright. 
<p>The auctioneer went on: &ldquo;Coop&lsquo;r&mdash;Coop&lsquo;r! Published at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, as printed on the back. Superior to Byron&mdash;Coop&lsquo;r&lsquo;s &lsquo;Task.&rsquo; No bidders? Thank you, sir. <num value="1">One</num>-and-<num value="6">six</num>,&mdash; your&lsquo;s, sir. Young&mdash;&lsquo;Young&lsquo;s Night Thoughts. Life, Death, and Immortality,&rsquo;&mdash;great subjects. London edition, marked <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> Going!&mdash;last bidder&mdash;<measure value="2s." type=currency><num value="2">two</num> shillings</measure>&mdash;gone!&rdquo; The purchaser then complained that the frontispiece&mdash;a man seated on a tombstone&mdash;was exactly the same as to a copy he had of &ldquo;Hervey&lsquo;s Meditations,&rdquo; but the auctioneer said it was impossible. 
<p>I have thus shown what <hi rend=italics>was</hi> the style and nature of the address of the street bookauc- tioneer, formerly, to the public. If it were not strictly &ldquo;patter,&rdquo; or &ldquo;pompous oration,&rdquo; it certainly partook of some of the characteristics of patter. At present, however, the street bookauctioneer may be described as a true patterer. 
<p>It will be seen from the account I have <pb id="p.297" n="297"> 
<milestone unit=col>
given, that the books were then really &ldquo;sold by auction&rdquo;&mdash;knocked down to the highest bidder. This however was, and is not always the case. Legally to sell by auction, necessitates the obtaining of a licence, at an annual cost of <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi>; and if the bookseller conveys his stock of books from place to place, a hawker&lsquo;s licence is required as well,&mdash;which entails an additional expenditure of <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> The itinerant bookseller evades, or endeavours to evade, the payment for an auctioneer&lsquo;s licence, by &ldquo;putting-up&rdquo; his books at a high price, and <hi rend=italics>himself</hi> decreasing the terms, instead of offering them at a low price, and allowing <hi rend=italics>the public</hi> to make a series of &ldquo;advances.&rdquo; Thus, a book may be offered by a street-auctioneer at half-a-crown&mdash;<measure value="2s." type=currency><num value="2">two</num> shillings</measure>&mdash;eighteenpence&mdash;a shilling&mdash;tenpence, and the moment any <num value="1">one</num> assents to a specified sum, the volume handed to him; so that there is no competition&mdash;no bidding by the public <num value="1">one</num> in advance of another. Auction, however, is resorted to as often as the bookseller dares. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> experienced man in the book-stall trade calculated that <num value="20">twenty</num> years ago there might be <num value="12">twelve</num> book-auctioneers in the streets of London, or rather, of its suburbs. <num value="1">One</num> of these was a frequenter of the Old Kent-road; another, &ldquo;Newington way;&rdquo; and a <num value="3">third</num> resorted to &ldquo;any likely pitch in Pimlico&rdquo;&mdash;all selling from a sort of van. Of these <num value="12">twelve</num>, however, my informant thought that there were never more than <num value="6">six</num> in London at <num value="1">one</num> time, as they were all itinerant; and they have gradually dwindled down to <num value="2">two</num>, who are now not half their time in town. These <num value="2">two</num> traders are brothers, and sell their books from a sort of platform erected on a piece of waste-ground, or from a barrow. The works they sell are generally announced as new, and are often uncut. They are all recommended as explanatory of every topic of the day, and are often set forth as &ldquo;spicy.&rdquo; <num value="3">Three</num> or <num value="4">four</num> years ago, a gentleman told me how greatly he was amused with the patter of <num value="1">one</num> of these men, who was selling books at the entrance of a yard full of caravans, not far from the School for the Blind, Lambeth. <num value="1">One</num> work the street-auctioneer announced at the top of his voice, in the following terms, as far as a good memory could retain them: &ldquo;&lsquo;The Rambler!&rsquo; Now you rambling boys&mdash;now you young devils, that&lsquo;s been staring those pretty girls out of countenance&mdash;here&lsquo;s the very book for you, and more shame for you, and perhaps for me too; but I must sell&mdash;I must do business. If any lady or gen&lsquo;lman &lsquo;ll stand treat to a glass of brandy and water, &lsquo;warm with,&rsquo; I&lsquo;ll tell more about this &lsquo;Rambler&rsquo;&mdash;I&lsquo;m too bashful, as it is. Who bids? <measure value="15d." type=currency><num value="15">Fifteen</num>-pence</measure>&mdash; thank&lsquo;ee, sir. Sold again!&rdquo; The &ldquo;Rambler&rdquo; was Dr. Johnson&lsquo;s! 
<p>The last time <num value="1">one</num> of my informants heard the &ldquo;patter&rdquo; of the smartest of the <num value="2">two</num> brothers, it was to the following effect: &ldquo;Here is the &lsquo;History of the Real Flying Dutchman,&rsquo; and <hi rend=italics>no</hi> mistake; no fiction, I assure you, upon 
<milestone unit=col>
my honour. Published at <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&mdash;who bids halfa-crown? Sixpence; thank you, sir. Ninepence; going&mdash;going! Any more?&mdash;gone!&rdquo; 
<p>A book-stall-keeper, who had sold goods to a book-auctioneer, and attended the sales, told me he was astonished to hear how his own books&mdash;&ldquo;old new books,&rdquo; he called them, were set off by the auctioneer: &ldquo;Why, there was a vol. lettered &lsquo;Pamphlets,&rsquo; and I think there <hi rend=italics>was</hi>
something about Jack Sheppard in it, but it was all odds and ends of other things, I know. &lsquo;Here&lsquo;s the <hi rend=italics>real</hi> Jack Sheppard,&rsquo; sings out the man, &lsquo;and no gammon!&rsquo; The real edition&mdash;no spooniness here, but set off with other interesting histories, valuable for the rising generation and all generations. This is the real Jack. This will 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L part=f>put you up to the time o&rsquo; day, 
<L>Nix, my dolly pals, <hi rend=italics>bid</hi> away.</quote>
 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>Then he went on: &lsquo;Goldsmith&lsquo;s History of England. Continued by the <num value="1">first</num> writers of the day&mdash;to the very last rumpus in the palace, and no mistake. Here it is; genuine.&rsquo; Well, sir,&rdquo; the stall-keeper continued, &ldquo;the man didn&lsquo;t do well; perhaps he cleared <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> or a little more that evening on books. People laughed more than they bought. But it&lsquo;s no wonder the trade&lsquo;s going to the dogs &mdash; they&lsquo;re not allowed to have a pitch now; I shouldn&lsquo;t be surprised if they was not <hi rend=italics>all</hi> driven out of London next year. It&lsquo;s contrary to Act of Parliament to get an honest living in the streets now-a-days.</QUOTE>
 
<p>A man connected with the street book-trade considered that if <num value="1">one</num> of these auctioneers earned a guinea in London streets in the <num value="6">six</num> days it was a &ldquo;good week.&rdquo; Half-a-guinea was nearer the average, he thought, &ldquo;looking at the weather and everything.&rdquo; What amount is expended to enable this street-dealer to earn his guinea or half-guinea, is so uncertain, from the very nature of an auction, that I can obtain no data to rely upon. 
<p>The itinerant book-auctioneer is now confined chiefly to the provincial towns, and especially the country markets. The reason for this is correctly given in the statement above cited. The street-auction requires the gathering of so large a crowd that the metropolitan police consider the obstruction to the public thoroughfares warrants their interference. The <num value="2">two</num> remaining book--auctioneers in London generally restrict their operations to the outskirts&mdash;the small space which fronts &ldquo;the George Inn&rdquo; in the Commercial-road, and which lays a few yards behind the main thoroughfare, and similar suburban &ldquo;retreats&rdquo; being favourite &ldquo;pitches.&rdquo; The trade is, as regards profits, far from bad&mdash;the books sold consisting chiefly of those picked up in cheap &ldquo;lots&rdquo; at the regular auctions; so that what fetches <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> in the streets has generally been purchased for less than a penny. The average rate of profit may be taken at <num value="250">250</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> per cent. at the least. Exorbitant however as this return may appear, still it should be remembered <pb id="p.298" n="298"> 
<milestone unit=col>
that the avocation is <num value="1">one</num> that can be pursued only occasionally, and that solely in fine weather. Books are now more frequently sold in the London streets from barrows. This change of traffic has been forced upon the streetsellers by the commands of the police&mdash;that the men should &ldquo;keep moving.&rdquo; Hence the well-known light form of street conveyance is now fast superseding not only the bookauc- tioneer, but the book--stall in the London streets. Of these book-barrowmen there is now about <num value="50">fifty</num> trading regularly in the metropolis, and taking on an average from <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.212"><head>Of the Street-Sale of Song-Books, and of Children&lsquo;s Books.</head>

<p>The sale of song-books in the streets, at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> and at <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each, is smaller than it was <num value="2">two</num> years ago. <num value="1">One</num> reason that I heard assigned was that the penny song-books&mdash;styled &ldquo;The Universal Songbook,&rdquo; &ldquo;The National,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Bijou,&rdquo; &amp;c.&mdash; were reputed to be so much alike (the same songs under a different title), that people who had bought <num value="1">one</num> book were averse to buy another. &ldquo;There&lsquo;s the &lsquo;Ross&rsquo; and the &lsquo;Sam Hall&rsquo; songbook,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> man, &ldquo;the &lsquo;eighteenth series,&rsquo; and I don&lsquo;t know what; but I don&lsquo;t like to venture on working them, though they&lsquo;re only a penny. There&lsquo;s lots to be seen in the shopwindows; but they might be stopped in the street, for they an&lsquo;t decent&mdash;&rsquo;specially the flash ones.&rdquo; 
<p><num value="1">One</num> of the books which a poor man had found the most saleable is entitled, &ldquo;The Great Exhibition Song-book; a Collection of the Newest and Most Admired Songs. Embellished with upwards of <num value="100">one Hundred</num> Toasts and Sentiments.&rdquo; The toasts and sentiments are given in small type, as a sort of border to the <num value="32">thirty-two</num> pages of which the book consists. The toast on the title-page is as follows: 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>I&lsquo;ll toast England&lsquo;s daughters, let all fill their glasses, 
<L>Whose beauty and virtue the whole world surpasses.</quote>

<p>To show the nature of the songs in street demand, I cite those in the book: &ldquo;The Gathering of the Nations,&rdquo; &ldquo;Bloom is on the Rye,&rdquo; &ldquo;Wilt thou Meet me there, Love?&rdquo; &ldquo;Minna&lsquo;s Tomb,&rdquo; &ldquo;I&lsquo;ll Love thee ever Dearly&rdquo; (Arnold), &ldquo;When Ph&oelig;bus wakes the Rosy Hours,&rdquo; &ldquo;Money is your Friend,&rdquo; &ldquo;Julia and Caspar&rdquo; (G. M. Lewis), &ldquo;That pretty word, Yes&rdquo; (E. Mackey), &ldquo;Farewell, Forget me Not,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Queen and the Navy&rdquo; (music published by H. White, Great Marlborough-street), &ldquo;I resign Thee every Token&rdquo; (music published by Duff and Co.), &ldquo;Sleep, gentle Lady;&rdquo; a serenade (H. J. Payne), &ldquo;The Warbling Waggoner,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Keepsake,&rdquo; &ldquo;A Sequel to the Cavalier,&rdquo; &ldquo;There&lsquo;s room enough for All&rdquo; (music at Mr. Davidson&lsquo;s), &ldquo;Will you Come to the Dale?&rdquo; &ldquo;Larry O&lsquo;Brian,&rdquo; &ldquo;Woman&lsquo;s Love,&rdquo; &ldquo;Afloat on the Ocean&rdquo; (sung by Mr. Weiss, in the Opera of the &ldquo;Heart of Mid Lothian,&rdquo; music published by Jefferys, Soho-square), &ldquo;Together, Dearest, let us Fly&rdquo; (sung by Mr. Braham, in the Opera of the &ldquo;Heart of Mid Lothian,&rdquo; music published 
<milestone unit=col>
by Jefferys, Soho-square), &ldquo;The Peremptory Lover&rdquo; (Tune&mdash;&ldquo;John Anderson, my Joe&rdquo;). There are <num value="47">forty-seven</num> songs in addition to those whose titles I have quoted, but they are all of the same character. 
<p>The penny song-books (which are partly indecent), and entitled the &ldquo;Sam Hall&rdquo; and &ldquo;Ross&rdquo; Songsters, are seldom or never sold in the streets. Many of those vended in the shops outrage all decency. Some of these are styled the &ldquo;Coal-Hole Companion,&rdquo; &ldquo;Cider-Cellar Songs,&rdquo; &ldquo;Captain Morris&lsquo;s Songs,&rdquo; &amp;c. (the filthiest of all.) These are generally marked <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and sold at <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; and have a coloured folded frontispiece. They are published chiefly by H. Smith, Holywell-street. The titles of some of the songs in these works are sufficient to indicate their character. &ldquo;The Muff,&rdquo; &ldquo;The <num value="2">Two</num> Miss Thys,&rdquo; &ldquo;George Robins&lsquo;s Auction,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Woman that studied the Stars,&rdquo; &ldquo;A Rummy Chaunt&rdquo; (frequently with no other title), &ldquo;The Amiable Family,&rdquo; &ldquo;Joe Buggins&rsquo; Wedding,&rdquo; &ldquo;Stop the Cart,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Mot that can feel for another,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Irish Giant,&rdquo; &ldquo;Taylor Tim,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Squire and Patty.&rdquo; 
<p>Some titles are unprintable. 
<p>The children&lsquo;s books in best demand in the street-trade, are those which have long been popular: &ldquo;Cinderella,&rdquo; &ldquo;Jack the Giantkiller,&rdquo; &ldquo;Baron Munchausen,&rdquo; &ldquo;Puss and the <num value="7">Seven</num>-leagued Boots,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Sleeping Beauty,&rdquo; &ldquo;The <num value="7">Seven</num> Champions of Christendom,&rdquo; &amp;c. &amp;c. &ldquo;There&lsquo;s plenty of &lsquo;Henry and Emmas,&rsquo;&rdquo; said a penny bookseller, &ldquo;and &lsquo;A Present for Christmas,&rsquo; and &lsquo;Pictorial Alphabets,&rsquo; and &lsquo;Good Books for Good Boys and Girls;&rsquo; but when people buys really for their children, they buys the old stories&mdash;at least they does of me. I&lsquo;ve sold &lsquo;Penny Hymns&rsquo; (hymn-books) sometimes; but when they&lsquo;re bought, or &lsquo;Good Books&rsquo; is bought, it&lsquo;s from charity to a poor fellow like me, more than anything else.&rdquo; 
<p>The trade, both in songs and in children&lsquo;s books, is carried on in much the same way as I have described of the almanacks and memorandum-books, but occasionally the singers of ballads sell books. Sometimes poor men, old or infirm, offer them in a tone which seems a whine for charity rather than an offer for sale, &ldquo;Buy a penny book of a poor old man&mdash; very hungry, very hungry.&rdquo; Children do the same, and all far more frequently in the suburbs than in the busy parts of the metropolis. Those who purchase really for the sake of the books, say, <num value="1">one</num> street-seller told me, &ldquo;Give me something that&lsquo;ll interest a child, and set him a-thinking. They can&lsquo;t understand&mdash;poor little things!&mdash;your fine writing; do you understand that?&rdquo; Another man had said, &ldquo;Fairy tales! bring me nothing but fairies; they set children a-reading.&rdquo; The price asked is most frequently a penny, but some are offered at a halfpenny, which is often given (without a purchase) out of compassion, or to be rid of importunity. The profit is at least cent. per cent. <pb id="p.299" n="299"> 
<milestone unit=col>

<div2 type=section id="c.15.213"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of account-Books.</head>

<p>THE sale of account-books is in the hands of about the same class of street-sellers as the stationery, but <num value="1">one</num> man in the trade thought the regular hands were more trusted, if anything, than street-stationers. &ldquo;People, you see,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;won&lsquo;t buy their &lsquo;accounts&rsquo; of 
<hi rend=italics>raff;</hi> they won&lsquo;t have them of any but respectable people.&rdquo; The books sold are bought at <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
the dozen, or <num value="4.50">4 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece, up to <num value="70">70</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the dozen, or <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, or <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a piece. It is rarely, however, that the street account-bookseller gives <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and very rarely that he gives as much as <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
for his account-books. His principal sale is of the smaller &ldquo;waste,&rdquo; or &ldquo;day-books,&rdquo; kept by the petty traders; the average price of these being <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="9">9</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> The principal purchasers are the chandlers, butchers, &amp;c., in the quieter streets, and more especially &ldquo;a little way out of town, where there ain&lsquo;t so many cheap shops.&rdquo; A man, now a street-stationer, with a &ldquo;fixed pitch,&rdquo; had carried on the account-book trade until an asthmatic affliction compelled him to relinquish it, as the walking became impossible to him, and he told me that the street-trade was nothing to what it once was. &ldquo;People,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;aren&lsquo;t so well off, I think, sir; and they&lsquo;ll buy half a quire of outside foolscap, or outside post, for from <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and stitch it together, and rule it, and make a book of it. Rich tradesmen do that, sir. I bought of a stastioner some years back, and he told me that he was a relation of a rich grocer, and had befriended him in his (the grocer&lsquo;s) youth, but he wouldn&lsquo;t buy account-books, for he said, the make-shift books that his shopman stitched together for him opened so much easier. People never want a good excuse for acting shabby.&rdquo; 
<p>There are now, I am informed, <num value="12">twelve</num> men selling account-books daily, which they carry in a covered basket, or in a waterproof bag, or, in fine weather, under the arm. Some of these street-sellers are not itinerant when there is a congregation of people for business, or indeed for any purpose; at other times they &ldquo;keep moving.&rdquo; The fixed localities are, on market days, at Smithfield and Mark-lane: and to Hungerford-market, an old man, unable to &ldquo;travel,&rdquo; resorts daily. The chief trade, however, is in carrying, or hawking these accountbooks from door to door. A man, &ldquo;having a connection,&rdquo; does best &ldquo;on a round;&rdquo; if he be known, he is not distrusted, and sells as cheap, or rather cheaper, than the shop-keepers. 
<p>The <num value="12">twelve</num> account-book sellers (with connections) may clear <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a day each, taking, for the realisation of such profit, <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> per diem. Thus <num value="1310">1,310</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> will be taken by these streetsellers in the course of a year. The capital required to start is, stock-money, <num value="15">15</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>; basket, <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d</hi><*> waterproof bag, <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d</hi>; <num value="21">21</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> in all. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.214"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Guide-Books, &amp;C.</head>

<p>THIS trade, as regards a street-sale, has only 
<milestone unit=col>
been known for <num value="9">nine</num> or <num value="10">ten</num> years, and had its origination in the exertions of Mr. Hume, M.P., to secure to persons visiting the national exhibitions the advantage of a cheap catalogue. The guide-books were only sold, prior to this time, <hi rend=italics>within</hi> any public exhibition; and the profits&mdash;as is the case at present&mdash;were the perquisite of some official. When the sale was a monopoly, the profit must have been considerable, as the price was seldom less than <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and frequently <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> The guide-books, or, as they are more frequently called, catalogues, are now sold by men who stand at the entrance, the approaches, at a little distance on the line, or at the corners of the adjacent streets, at the following places:&mdash;the National Gallery, the Vernon Gallery, the British Museum, Westminster Abbey, the House of Lords, the Society of Arts (occasionally), the Art-Union (when open &ldquo;free&rdquo;), Greenwich Hospital, the Dulwich Gallery, Hampton Court, Windsor Castle, and Kew Gardens. 
<p>At any temporary exhibition, also, the same trade is carried on&mdash;as it was largely when the &ldquo;designs,&rdquo; &amp;c., for the decoration of the New Houses of Parliament were exhibited in Westminster Hall. There are, of course, very many other catalogues, or explanatory guides, sold to the visitors of other exhibitions, but I speak only of the <hi rend=italics>street</hi>-sale. 
<p>There are now, at the National Gallery, <num value="3">three</num> guidebook-sellers plying their trade in the streets; <num value="8">eight</num> at the British Museum; <num value="2">two</num> at Westminster Abbey; <num value="1">one</num> at the House of Lords, but only on Saturdays, when the House is shown, by orders obtained gratuitously at the Lord Chamberlain&lsquo;s office, or &ldquo;when appeals are on;&rdquo; <num value="1">one</num> at the Vernon Gallery; <num value="2">two</num> at Dulwich (but not regularly, as there are none at present), <num value="2">two</num> at Hampton Court, &ldquo;<num value="1">one</num> near each gate;&rdquo; and <num value="1">one</num>, and sometimes <num value="3">three</num>, at Windsor (generally sent out by a shopkeeper there). There used to be <num value="1">one</num> at the Thames Tunnel, but &ldquo;it grew so bad at last,&rdquo; I was told, &ldquo;that a rat couldn&lsquo;t have picked up his grub at it&mdash;let alone a man.&rdquo; 
<p>Among all these sellers I heard statements of earning a most wretched pittance, and all attributed it to the same cause. By the National Gallery is a board, on which is an announcement that the only authorized catalogue of the works of art can be obtained in the hall. There are similar announcements at other public places. <num value="1">One</num> man who had been in this street trade, but had abandoned it, spoke of these &ldquo;boards,&rdquo; as he called them, with intense bitterness. &ldquo;They&lsquo;re the ruin of any trade in the streets,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;You needn&lsquo;t think because I&lsquo;m out of it now, that I have a pleasure in abusing the regulations; no, sir, I look at it this way. Mr. Hume had trouble enough, I know, to get the public a cheap catalogue, and poor men were allowed to earn honest bread by selling them in the streets, and honest bread they would earn still, if it weren&lsquo;t for the board. I declare solemnly a man can&lsquo;t <pb id="p.300" n="300"> 
<milestone unit=col>
get a living at the trade. The publishers can&lsquo;t prepare their catalogues without leave, and when they&lsquo;ve got leave, and do prepare and print them, why isn&lsquo;t a man allowed to sell them in the streets, as I&lsquo;ve sold <num value="2">second</num> editions of the 
<hi rend=italics>Globe</hi> without ever the office putting out a notice that the only authorized copy was to be had within? God bless your soul, sir, it&lsquo;s shocking, shocking, poor men being hindered every way. Anybody that looks on the board looks on us as cheats and humbugs, and thinks that our catalogues are all takes-in. But I&lsquo;ve heard gentlemen, that I&lsquo;m sure knew what they were talking about, say, in case they&lsquo;d bought in the street <num value="1">first</num>, and then seen the board and bought within after, so as to be sure of the real thing&mdash;I&lsquo;ve heard gentlemen, say, sir,&mdash;&lsquo;Why what we got in the street is the best after all.&rsquo; Free trade! There&lsquo;s plenty said about free trade, but that board, sir, or call it what you please, gives a monopoly against us. What I have said, when I was starving on catalogues, is this: Kick us out of the streets, commit us for selling catalogues, as rogues and vagabonds; or give us a fair chance. If we <hi rend=italics>may</hi> sell, why is the only authorised catalogue sold only within? I wish Mr. Hume, or Mr. Cobden, either, only understood the rights of the matter &mdash;it&lsquo;s of no account to me myself now&mdash;and I think they&lsquo;d soon set it to rights. Free trade! Over the left, and with more hooks than <num value="1">one</num>.&rdquo; 
<p>I have no doubt that this representation and this opinion would have been echoed by the street catalogue-sellers, but they were evidently unwilling to converse freely on this branch of the subject, knowing the object for which I questioned them, and that publicity would follow. I attribute this reluctance chiefly to the fact that, all these poor men look forward to the opening of the Great Exhibition with earnest hope and anxiety that the influx of visiters will add greatly to their sale and profits; and they are unwilling to jeopardise their privilege of sale. 
<p><num value="1">One</num> man told me that he believed, from his own knowledge, for he had not always &ldquo;sold outside,&rdquo; that the largest buyers of these publications were country people, sight-seeing in London, for they bought the book not only as an explanatory guide, but to preserve as a memento of their visit. Such customers, however, I heard from several quarters, the moment they saw a &ldquo;notice&rdquo; as to the only authorised copy, looked upon the street-sellers as a systematised portion of the London sharpers, seeking whom they might devour, and so bought their catalogues &ldquo;within.&rdquo; 
<p>The best customers in the streets for the catalogues are, I am assured, the working-classes, who visit the national exhibitions on a holiday. &ldquo;I&lsquo;ve oft enough heard them say,&rdquo; <num value="1">one</num> man stated, &ldquo;&lsquo;I&lsquo;d rather pay a poor man <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> any day, when I can spare it, than rich people <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> I know what it is to fight for a crust.&rsquo;&rdquo; 
<p>At the National Gallery, the street-sold catalogues are <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; in the hall, the 
<milestone unit=col>
authorised copy is sold at <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> and <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> At the British Museum, the street-charges are <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> and <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; there were <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> catalogues of this institution, but they have been discontinued for the last half-year, being found too meagre. At the Vernon Gallery, the charge is <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>; but the <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
guide-book to the National Gallery contains also an account of the pictures in the Vernon Gallery. At Westminster Abbey the price is <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and the same at the House of Lords. At Hampton-court it is <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and at the same rate as regards the other places mentioned. At Hampton-court, I was told, the street-sellers were not allowed to approach the palace nearer than a certain space. <num value="1">One</num> man told me that he was threatened with being &ldquo;had in for trespassing, and Mr. G&mdash;&mdash;would make him wheel a roller. Of course,&rdquo; the man continued, &ldquo;there&lsquo;s an authorised catalogue there.&rdquo; 
<p>The best sale of catalogues in the streets was at the exhibition of the works of art for the Houses of Parliament. The sellers, then&mdash; about <num value="20">20</num> in number, among whom were <num value="4">four</num> women&mdash;cleared <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> and <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each daily. At present, I am assured, that a good week is considered <num value="1">one</num> in which <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> is made, but that <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
is more frequently the weekly earning. It must be borne in mind, that at the <num value="2">two</num> places most resorted to&mdash;the National Gallery and the British Museum&mdash;the street sale is only for <num value="4">four</num> days in the week at the <num value="1">first</num> mentioned, and <num value="3">three</num> days at the <num value="2">second</num>. &ldquo;You may think that more is made,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> man, &ldquo;but it isn&lsquo;t. Sweeping a good crossing is far better, far. Bless your soul, only stand a few minutes looking on, any day, and see what numbers and numbers of people pass in and out of a free admission place without ever laying out <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
Why, only last Monday and Wednesday (<datestruct VALUE="-03-17"><month reg="03">March</month> <day reg=17>17</day></datestruct> and <num value="19">19</num>, both very rainy days) I took only <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
I didn&lsquo;t <hi rend=italics>take</hi> more than <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, and I leave you to judge the living I shall <hi rend=italics>clear</hi> out of that; and I know that the man with the catalogue at another place, didn&lsquo;t take <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> It&lsquo;s sad work, sir, as you stand in the wet and cold, with no dinner for yourself, and no great hope of taking <num value="1">one</num> home to your family.&rdquo; 
<p>These street-sellers contrive, whenever they can, to mix up other avocations with catalogue selling, as the public institutions close early. <num value="1">One</num>, on every occasion, sells <num value="2">second</num> editions of the newspapers; another has &ldquo;odd turns at portering;&rdquo; a <num value="3">third</num> sells old umbrellas in the streets; some sold exhibition cards in the Park, on Sundays, until the sale was stopped; another sells a little stationery; and nearly the whole of them resort, on favourable opportunities, to the sale of &ldquo;books of the play,&rdquo; or of &ldquo;the opera.&rdquo; 
<p>Reckoning that there are regularly <num value="16">sixteen</num> street-sellers of guide-books&mdash;they do not interfere with each other&lsquo;s stations&mdash;and that each clears <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> weekly, we find <measure value="832l." type=currency>&pound; <num value="832">832</num></measure> expended in this street traffic. I have calculated only on the usual bookseller&lsquo;s allowance of <num value="25">25</num> per cent., <pb id="p.301" n="301"> 
<milestone unit=col>
though, in some instances, these sellers are supplied on lower terms&mdash;besides having, in some of the catalogues, <num value="13">thirteen</num> to the dozen; but the amount specified does not exceed the mark. 
<p>The greatest number of these guide-books which I heard of as having been sold, in any <num value="1">one</num> day, was <num value="4">four</num> dozen, disposed of on a fine Whit-Monday, and for these the street-seller only took <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="8">8</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> There are, I was informed, half as many more &ldquo;threepennies&rdquo; as &ldquo;sixpennies&rdquo; sold, and <num value="3">three</num> times as many &ldquo;pennies&rdquo; as the other <num value="2">two</num> together. 
<p>The capital required to start is what may suffice to &ldquo;lay in&rdquo; a stock of books&mdash;<num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> generally. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.215"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Fine arts.</head>

<p>THESE traders may be described as partaking more of the characteristics of the street stationers than of the &ldquo;paper-workers,&rdquo; as they are not patterers. The trade is less exclusively than the &ldquo;paper-trade&rdquo; in the hands of men. Those carrying on this branch of the street-traffic may be divided into the sellers of pictures in frames, and of engravings (of all kinds), in umbrellas. Under this head may also be ranked the street-artists (though this is a trade associated with street-life rather than forming an integrant part of it), I allude more particularly to the illustrated &ldquo;boards&rdquo; which are prepared for the purposes of the streetpat- terers, and are adapted for no other use. The same artist that executes the greater portion of the street-art, also prepares the paintings which decorate the exterior of shows. There are also the writers of manuscript music, and the makers and sellers of &ldquo;images&rdquo; of all descriptions, but this branch of the subject I shall treat under the head of the street-Italians. Under the same curious head I shall also speak of the artists whose skill produces the street-sold medallions, in wax or plaster, they being of the same class as the &ldquo;image&rdquo; men. In both &ldquo;images&rdquo; and &ldquo;casts&rdquo; and &ldquo;moulded&rdquo; productions of all kinds the change and improvement that have taken place, from the pristine rudeness of &ldquo;green parrots&rdquo; is most remarkable and creditable to the taste of working people, who are the chief purchasers of the smaller articles. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.216"><head>Of Street art.</head>

<p>THE artists who work for the street-sellers are less numerous than the poets for the same trade. Indeed, there is now but <num value="1">one</num> man who can be said to be <hi rend=italics>solely</hi> a street-artist. The inopportune illustration of ballads of which specimens have already been given&mdash;or of any of the street papers&mdash;are the work of cheap wood-engravers, who give the execution of these orders to their boys. But it is not often that illustrations are prepared expressly for anything but what I have described as &ldquo;Gallows literature.&rdquo; Of these, samples have also been furnished. The <num value="1">one</num> of a real murder, and the other of a fabulous 
<milestone unit=col>
<num value="1">one</num>, or &ldquo;cock,&rdquo; together with a sample (in the case of Mr. Patrick Connor) of the portraits given in such productions. The cuts for the heading of ballads are very often such as have been used for the illustration of other works. and are &ldquo;picked up cheap.&rdquo; 
<p>The artist who works especially for the street trade&mdash;as in the case of the man who paints the patterers&rsquo; boards&mdash;must address his art plainly to the eye of the spectator. He must use the most striking colours, be profuse in the application of scarlet, light blue, orange&mdash;not yellow I was told, it ain&lsquo;t a good candlelight colour&mdash; and must leave nothing to the imagination. Perspective and back-grounds are things of but minor consideration. Everything must be sacrificed for effect. 
<p>These paintings are in water colours, and are rubbed over with a solution of some gum-resin to protect them from the influence of rainy weather. <num value="2">Two</num> of the subjects most in demand of late for the patterers&rsquo; boards were &ldquo;the Sloanes&rdquo; and &ldquo;the Mannings.&rdquo; The treatment of Jane Wilbred was &ldquo;worked&rdquo; by <num value="20">twenty</num> boardmen, each with his &ldquo;illustration&rdquo; of the subject. The illustrations were in <num value="6">six</num> &ldquo;compartments.&rdquo; In the <num value="1">first</num> Mr. and Mrs. Sloane are &ldquo;picking out&rdquo; the girl from a line of workhouse children. She is represented as plump and healthy, but with a stupid expression of countenance. In another compartment, Sloane is beating the girl, then attenuated and wretched-looking, with a shoe, while his wife and Miss Devaux (a name I generally heard pronounced among the street-people as it is spelt to an English reader) look approvingly on. The next picture was Sloane compelling the girl to swallow filth. The <num value="4">fourth</num> represented her as in the hospital, with her ribs protruding from her wasted body &mdash;&ldquo;just as I&lsquo;ve worked Sarah Simpole,&rdquo; said a patterer, &ldquo;who was confined in a cellar and fed on &lsquo;tato peels. Sarah was a cock, sir, and a ripper.&rdquo; Then came the attack of the people on Sloane, <num value="1">one</num> old woman dressed after the fashion of Mrs. Gamp, &ldquo;prodding&rdquo; him with a huge and very green umbrella. The <num value="6">sixth</num> and last was, as usual, the trial. 
<p>I have described the &ldquo;Sloanes&rsquo; board&rdquo; <num value="1">first</num>, as it may be more fresh in the remembrance of any reader observant of such things. In the &ldquo;Mannings&rsquo; board&rdquo; there were the same number of compartments as in the Sloanes&rsquo;; showing the circumstances of the murder, the discovery of the body of Connor, the trial, &amp;c. <num value="1">One</num> standing patterer, who worked a Mannings&rsquo; board, told me that the picture of Mrs. Manning, beautifully &ldquo;dressed for dinner&rdquo; in black satin, with &ldquo;a low front,&rdquo; firing a pistol at Connor, who was &ldquo;washing himself,&rdquo; while Manning, in his shirt sleeves, looked on in evident alarm, was greatly admired, especially out of town. &ldquo;The people said,&rdquo; observed the patterer, &ldquo;&lsquo;O, look at him a-washing hisself; he&lsquo;s a doing it so nattral, and ain&lsquo;t a-thinking he&lsquo;s a-going to be murdered. But was he really so ugly as that? Lor! such a beautiful woman to have to do with <pb id="p.302" n="302"> 
<milestone unit=col>
him.&rsquo; You see, sir, Connor weren&lsquo;t flattered, and perhaps Mrs. Manning was. I have heard the same sort of remarks both in town and country. I patters hard on the women such times, as I points them out on my board in murders or any crimes. I says: &lsquo;When there&lsquo;s mischief a woman&lsquo;s always the <num value="1">first</num>. Look at Mrs. Manning there on that werry board&mdash;the work of <num value="1">one</num> of the <num value="1">first</num> artists in London&mdash;it&lsquo;s a faithful likeness, taken from life at <num value="1">one</num> of her examinations, look at <hi rend=italics>her.</hi> She fires the pistol, as you can see, and her husband was her tool.&rsquo; I said, too, that Sloane was Mrs. Sloane&lsquo;s tool. It answers best, sir, in my opinion, going on that patter. The men likes it, and the women doesn&lsquo;t object, for they&lsquo;ll say: &lsquo;Well, when a woman is bad, she <hi rend=italics>is</hi> bad, and is a disgrace to her sex.&rsquo; There&lsquo;s the board before them when I runs on that line of patter, and when I appeals to the &lsquo;lustration, it seems to cooper the thing. They 
<hi rend=italics>must</hi> believe their eyes.&rdquo; 
<p>When there is &ldquo;a run&rdquo; on any particular subject, there are occasionally jarrings&mdash;I was informed by a &ldquo;boardman&rdquo;&mdash;between the artist and his street-customers. The standing patterers want &ldquo;something more original&rdquo; than their fellows, especially if they are likely to work in the same locality, while the artist prefers a faithful copy of what he has already executed. The artist, moreover, and with all reasonableness, will say: &ldquo;Why, you must have the facts. Do you want me to make Eliza Chestney killing Rush?&rdquo; The matter is often compromised by some change being introduced, and by the characters being differently dressed. <num value="1">One</num> man told me, that in town and country he had seen Mrs. Jermy shot in the following costumes, &ldquo;in light green welwet, sky-blue satin, crimson silk, and vite muslin.&rdquo; It was the same with Mrs. Manning. 
<p>For the last <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="8">eight</num> years, I am told, the artist in question has prepared all the boards in demand. Previously, the standing patterers prepared their own boards, when they fancied themselves capable of such a &ldquo;reach of art,&rdquo; or had them done by some unemployed painter, whom they might fall in with at a lodging-house, or elsewhere. This is rarely done now, I am told; not perhaps more than <num value="6">six</num> times in a twelvemonth, and when done it is most frequently practised of &ldquo;cock-boards;&rdquo; for, as was said to me, &ldquo;if a man thinks he&lsquo;s getting up a fakement likely to take, and wants a board to help him on with it, he&lsquo;ll try and keep it to hisself, and come out with it quite fresh.&rdquo; 
<p>The charge of the popular street-artist for the painting of a board is <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> or <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, according to the simplicity or elaborateness of the details; the board itself is provided by the artist&lsquo;s employer. The demand for this peculiar branch of street art is very irregular, depending entirely upon whether anything be &ldquo;up&rdquo; or not; that is, whether there has or has not been perpetrated any act of atrocity, which has riveted, as it is called, the public attention. And so great is the uncertainty felt by the street-folk, whether &ldquo;the 
<milestone unit=col>
most beautiful murder will take or not,&rdquo; that it is rarely the patterer will order, or the artist will speculate, in anticipation of a demand, upon preparing the painting of any event, until satisfied that it has become &ldquo;popular.&rdquo; A deed of more than usual daring, deceit, or mystery, may be at once hailed by those connected with murder-patter, as &ldquo;<num value="1">one</num> that will do,&rdquo; and some speculation may be ventured upon; as it was, I am informed, in the cases of Tawell, Rush, and the Mannings; but these are merely exceptional. Thus, if the artist have a dozen boards ordered &ldquo;for this <num value="10">ten</num> days, he may have <num value="2">two</num>, or <num value="1">one</num>, or none for the next <num value="10">ten</num>;&rdquo; so uncertain, it appears, is all that depends, without intrinsic merit, on mere popular applause. 
<p>I am unable to give&mdash;owing to the want of account-books, &amp;c., which I have so often had to refer to as characteristic of street-people&mdash; a precise account of the average number of boards thus prepared in a year. Perhaps it may be as close to the fact as possible to conclude that the artist in question, who, unlike the majority of the street-poets, is not a street-seller, but works, as a professional man, <hi rend=italics>for</hi> but not <hi rend=italics>in</hi>
the streets, realises on his boards a profit of <num value="7">7</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> weekly. The pictorial productions for street-shows will be more appropriately described in the account of street-performers and showmen. 
<p>This artist, as I have shown concerning some of the street-professors of the sister art of poesy, has the quality of knowing how to adapt his works exactly to the taste of his patrons the sellers, and of their patrons, the buyers in the streets. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.217"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Engravings, Etc., in Umbrellas, Etc.</head>

<p>THE sale of &ldquo;prints,&rdquo; &ldquo;pictures,&rdquo; and &ldquo;engravings&rdquo;&mdash;I heard them designated by each term&mdash;in umbrellas in the streets, has been known, as far as I could learn from the streetfolk for some <num value="15">fifteen</num> years, and has been general from <num value="10">ten</num> to <num value="12">twelve</num> years. In this traffic the umbrella is inverted and the &ldquo;stock&rdquo; is disposed within its expanse. Sometimes narrow tapes are attached from rib to rib of the umbrella, and within these tapes are placed the pictures, <num value="1">one</num> resting upon another. Sometimes a few pins are used to attach the larger prints to the cotton of the umbrella, the smaller ones being &ldquo;fitted in at the side&rdquo; of the bigger. &ldquo;Pins is best, sir, in my opinion,&rdquo; said a little old man, who used to have a &ldquo;print umbrella&rdquo; in the New Cut; &ldquo;for the public has a more unbrokener display. I used werry fine pins, though they&lsquo;s dearer, for people as has a penny to spare likes to see things nice, and big pins makes big holes in the pictures.&rdquo; 
<p>This trade is most pursued on still summer evenings, and the use of an inverted umbrella seems so far appropriate that it can only be so used, in the street, in <hi rend=italics>dry</hi> weather. &ldquo;I used to keep a sharp look-out, sir,&rdquo; said the same informant, &ldquo;for wind or rain, and many&lsquo;s the time them devils o&rsquo; boys&mdash;God forgive me, <pb id="p.303" n="303"> 
<milestone unit=col>
they&lsquo;s on&lsquo;y poor children&mdash;but they <hi rend=italics>is</hi> devils&mdash; has come up to me and has said&mdash;<num value="1">one</num> in particler, standin&lsquo; afore the rest: &lsquo;It&lsquo;ll thunder in <num value="5">five</num> minutes, old bloke, so hup with yer humbereller, and go &lsquo;ome; hup with it jist as it is; it&lsquo;ll show stunnin; and sell as yer goes.&rsquo; O, they&lsquo;re a shocking torment, sir; nobody can feel it like people in the streets,&mdash;shocking.&rdquo; 
<p>The engravings thus sold are of all descriptions. Some have evidently been the frontispieces of sixpenny or lower-prieed works. These works sometimes fall into hands of the &ldquo;waste collectors,&rdquo; and any &ldquo;illustrations&rdquo; are extracted from the letter-press and are disposed of by the collectors, by the gross or dozen, to those warehousemen who supply the small shopkeepers and the street-sellers. Sometimes, I was informed, a number of engravings, which had for a while appeared as &ldquo;frontispieces&rdquo; were issued for sale separately. Many of these were and are found in the &ldquo;street umbrellas;&rdquo; more especially the portraits of popular actors and actresses. &ldquo;Mr. J. P. Kemble, as Hamlet&rdquo;&mdash; &ldquo;Mr. Fawcett, as Captain Copp&rdquo;&mdash;&ldquo;Mr. Young, as Iago&rdquo;&mdash;&ldquo;Mr. Liston, as Paul Pry&rdquo;&mdash;&ldquo;Mrs. Siddons, as Lady Macbeth&rdquo;&mdash; &ldquo;Miss O&lsquo;Neil, as Belvidera,&rdquo; &amp;c., &amp;c. In the course of an inquiry into the subject nearly a year and a half ago, I learned from <num value="1">one</num> &ldquo;umbrella man&rdquo; that, <num value="6">six</num> or <num value="7">seven</num> years previously, he used to sell more portraits of &ldquo;Mr. Edmund Kean, as Richard III.,&rdquo; than of anything else. Engravings, too, which had <num value="1">first</num> been admired in the &ldquo;Annuals&rdquo;&mdash;when halfa-guinea was the price of the &ldquo;Literary Souvenir,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Forget-me-not,&rdquo; &ldquo;Friendship&lsquo;s Offering,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Bijou,&rdquo; &amp;c., &amp;c.&mdash;are frequently found in these umbrellas; and amongst them are not unfrequently seen portraits of the aristocratic beauties of the day, from &ldquo;waste&rdquo; &ldquo;Flowers of Loveliness&rdquo; and old &ldquo;Court Magazines,&rdquo; which &ldquo;go off very fair.&rdquo; The majority of these street-sold &ldquo;engravings&rdquo; are &ldquo;coloured,&rdquo; in which state the street-sellers prefer them, thinking them much more saleable, though the information I received hardly bears out their opinion. 
<p>The following statement, from a middle-aged woman, further shows the nature of the trade, and the class of customers: 
<p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><p>I&lsquo;ve sat with an umbrella,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;these <num value="7">seven</num> or <num value="8">eight</num> years, I suppose it is. My husband&lsquo;s a penny lot-seller, with just a middling pitch&rdquo; [the vendor of a number of articles, sold at a penny &ldquo;a lot&rdquo;] &ldquo;and in the summer I do a little in engravings, when I&lsquo;m not minding my husband&lsquo;s &lsquo;lots,&rsquo; for he has sometimes a day, and oftener a night, with portering and packing for a tradesman, that&lsquo;s known him long. Well, sir, I think I sell most &lsquo;coloured.&rsquo; &lsquo;Master Toms&rsquo; wasn&lsquo;t bad last summer. &lsquo;Master Toms&rsquo; was pictures of cats, sir&mdash;you must have seen them&mdash;and I had them different colours. If a child looks on with its father, very likely, it&lsquo;ll want &lsquo;pussy,&rsquo; and if the child cries for it, it&lsquo;s almost a sure sale, and 
<milestone unit=col>
more, I think, indeed I&lsquo;m sure, with men than with women. Women knows the value of money better than men, for men never understand what housekeeping is. I have no children, thank God, or they might be pinched, poor things. &lsquo;Miss Kitties&rsquo; was the same sale. Toms is hes, and Kitties is she cats. I&lsquo;ve sometimes sold to poor women who was tiresome; they must have just what would fit over their mantel-pieces, that was papered with pictures.&rdquo; [My readers may remember that some of the descriptions I have given, long previous to the present inquiry, of the rooms of the poor, fully bear out this statement.] &ldquo;I seldom venture on anything above <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, I mean to sell at <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> I&lsquo;ve had Toms and Kitties at <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> though. &lsquo;Fashions&rsquo; isn&lsquo;t worth umbrella room; the poorest needlewoman won&lsquo;t be satisfied with them from an umbrella. &lsquo;Queens&rsquo; and &lsquo;Alberts&rsquo; and &lsquo;Wales&lsquo;s&rsquo; and the other children isn&lsquo;t near so good as they was. There&lsquo;s so many &lsquo;fine portraits of Her Majesty,&rsquo; or the others, given away with the <num value="1">first</num> number of this or of that, that people&lsquo;s overstocked. If a working-man can buy a newspaper or a number, why of course he may as well have a picture with it. They gave away glasses of gin at the opening of that baker&lsquo;s shop there, and it&lsquo;s the same doctrine&rdquo; [The word she used]. &ldquo;I never offer penny theatres, or comic exhibitions, or anything big; they spoils the look of the umbrella, and makes better things look mean. I sell only to working people, I think; seldom to boys, and seldomer to girls; seldom to servant-maids and hardly ever to women of the town. I <hi rend=italics>have</hi> taken <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> from <num value="1">one</num> of them though. I think boys buy pictures for picture books. I never had what I suppose was old pictures. To a few old people, I&lsquo;ve known, &lsquo;Children&rsquo; sell fairly, when they&lsquo;re made plump, and red cheeked, and curly haired. They sees a resemblance of their grandchildren, perhaps, and buys. Young married people does so too, but not so oft, I think. I don&lsquo;t remember that ever I have made more than <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> on an evening. I don&lsquo;t sell, or very seldom indeed, at other times, and only in summer, and when its fine. If I clear <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> I counts that a good week. It&lsquo;s a great help to the lot-selling. I seldom clear so much. Oftener <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi></QUOTE>
 
<p>The principal sale of these &ldquo;pictures,&rdquo; in the streets, is from umbrellas. Occasionally, a street-stationer, or even a miscellaneous lotseller, when he has met with a cheap lot, especially of portraits of ladies, will display a collection of prints, pyramidally arranged on his stall,&mdash;but these are exceptions. Sometimes, too, an &ldquo;umbrella print-seller&rdquo; will have a few &ldquo;pictures in frames,&rdquo; on a sort of stand alongside the umbrella. 
<p>The pictures for the umbrellas are bought at the warehouse, or the swag-shops, of which I have before spoken. At these establishments &ldquo;prints&rdquo; are commonly supplied from <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> the dozen. The street-sellers buy at <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
and <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the dozen, to sell at a <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a piece; and <pb id="p.304" n="304"> 
<milestone unit=col>
at <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to sell at <num value="0.50">1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d. None</hi> of the pictures thus sold are prepared expressly for the streets. 
<p>In so desultory and&mdash;as <num value="1">one</num> intelligent streetseller with whom I conversed on the subject described it&mdash;so <hi rend=italics>weathery</hi> a trade, it is difficult to arrive at exact statistics. From the best data at my command, it may be computed, that for <num value="12">twelve</num> weeks of the year, there are <num value="30">thirty</num> umbrella print-sellers (all exceptional traders therein included) each clearing <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> weekly, and taking <num value="12">12</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> Thus it appears that <num value="216">216</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is yearly expended in the streets in this purchase. Many of the sellers are old or infirm; <num value="1">one</num> who was among the most prosperous before the changes in the streets of Lambeth, was dwarfish, and was delighted to be thought &ldquo;a character.&rdquo; 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.218"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Pictures in Frames.</head>

<p>FROM about <datestruct value="1810--"><year reg="1810">1810</year></datestruct>, or somewhat earlier, down to <datestruct value="1830--"><year reg="1830">1830</year></datestruct>, or somewhat later, the street-sale of pictures in frames was almost entirely in the hands of the Jews. The subjects were then nearly all scriptural: &ldquo;The Offering up of Isaac;&rdquo; &ldquo;Jacob&lsquo;s Dream;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Crossing of the Red Sea;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Death of Sisera;&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Killing of Goliath from the Sling of the youthful David.&rdquo; But the Jew traders did not at all account it necessary to confine the subjects of their pictures to the records of the Old&mdash;their best trade was in the illustrations of the New Testament. Perhaps the &ldquo;Stoning of St. Stephen&rdquo; was their most saleable &ldquo;picture in a frame.&rdquo; There were also &ldquo;The Nativity;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Slaying of the Children, by order of Herod&rdquo; (with the quotation of St. Matthew, chap. ii. verse <num value="17">17</num>, &ldquo;Then was fulfilled that which was spoken by Jeremy the prophet&rdquo;); &ldquo;The Sermon on the Mount;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Beheading of John the Baptist;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Entry of Christ into Jerusalem;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Raising of Lazarus;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Betrayal on the part of Judas;&rdquo; &ldquo;The Crucifixion;&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Conversion of St. Paul.&rdquo; There were others, but these were the principal subjects. All these pictures were coloured, and very deeply coloured. St. Stephen was stoned in the lightest of sky-blue short mantles. The pictures were sold in the streets of London, mostly in the way of hawking; but <num value="10">ten</num> times as extensively, I am told, in the country, as in town. Indeed, at the present time, many a secluded village alehouse has its parlour walls decorated with these scriptural illustrations, which seem to have superseded 
<QUOTE rend=blockquote><L>The pictures placed for ornament and use; 
<L>The <num value="12">twelve</num> good rules; the royal game of goose,</quote>
mentioned by Goldsmith as characteristic of a village inn. These &ldquo;Jew pictures&rdquo; are now yielding to others. 
<p>Most of these articles were varnished, and <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>
or <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> each was frequently the price asked, <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> being taken &ldquo;if no better could be done,&rdquo; and sometimes <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> A smaller amount per single picture was always taken, if a set 
<milestone unit=col>
were purchased. These productions were prepared principally for street-sale and for hawkers. The frames were narrower and meaner-looking than in the present street-pictures of the kind; they were stained like the present frames, in imitation of maple, but far less skilfully. Sometimes they were a black japan; sometimes a sorry imitation of mahogany. 
<p>In the excitement of the Reform Bill era, the street-pictures in frames most in demand were Earl Grey, Earl Spencer&lsquo;s (or Lord Althorp), Lord Brougham&lsquo;s, and Lord John Russell&lsquo;s. O&lsquo;Connell&lsquo;s also &ldquo;sold well,&rdquo; as did William IV. &ldquo;Queen Adelaide,&rdquo; I was told, &ldquo;went off middling, not much more than half as good as William.&rdquo; Towards the close of King William&lsquo;s life, the portraits of the Princess Victoria of Kent were of good sale in the streets, and her Royal Highness was certainly represented as a young lady of undue plumpness, and had hardly justice done to her portraiture. The Duchess of Kent, also, I was informed, &ldquo;sold fairish in the streets.&rdquo; In a little time, the picture in a frame of the Princess Victoria of Kent, with merely an alteration in the title, became available as Queen Victoria I., of Great Britain and Ireland. Since that period, there have been the princes and princesses, her Majesty&lsquo;s offspring, who present a strong family resemblance. 
<p>The street pictures, so to speak, are not unfrequently of a religious character. Pictures of the Virgin and Child, of the Saviour seated at the Last Supper, of the Crucifixion, or of the different saints, generally coloured. The principal purchasers of these &ldquo;religious pictures&rdquo; are the poorer Irish. I remember seeing, in the course of an inquiry among streetperformers last summer, the entire wall of a poor street-dancer&lsquo;s <num value="1">one</num> room, except merely the space occupied by the fireplace, covered with small coloured pictures in frames, the whole of which, the proprietor told me, with some pride, he had picked up in the streets, according as he could spare a few pence. Among them were a crucifix (of bone), and a few medallions, of a religious character, in plaster or wax. This man was of Italian extraction; but I have seen the same thing in the rooms of the Roman Catholic Irish, though never to the same extent. 
<p>The general subjects now most in demand for street-sale are, &ldquo;Lola Montes,&rdquo; &ldquo;Louis Philippe and his Queen,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Sailor&lsquo;s Return,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Soldier&lsquo;s Return,&rdquo; and the &ldquo;Parting&rdquo; of the same individuals, Smugglers, in different situations, Poachers also; &ldquo;Turpin&lsquo;s Ride to York,&rdquo; the divers feats attributed to Jack Sheppard (but less popular than &ldquo;Turpin&lsquo;s Ride,&rdquo;) &ldquo;Courtship,&rdquo; &ldquo;Marriage&rdquo; (the <num value="1">one</num> a couple caressing, and the other bickering), &ldquo;Father Mathew&rdquo; (in very black large boots), &ldquo;Napoleon Bonaparte crossing the Alps,&rdquo; and his &ldquo;Farewell to his Troops at Fontainebleau,&rdquo; &ldquo;Scenes of Piracy.&rdquo; None of these subjects are modern; &ldquo;Lola Montes&rdquo; (a bold-faced woman, in a riding- <pb id="p.305" n="305"> 
<milestone unit=col>
habit), being the newest. &ldquo;Why,&rdquo; said <num value="1">one</num> man familiar with the trade, &ldquo;there hasn&lsquo;t been no Louis Napoleon in a frame-picture for the streets, nor Cobdens, nor Feargus O&lsquo;Connors, nor Sir John Franklins; what is wanted for us is something exciting.&rdquo; 
<p>The prices of frame-pictures (as I sometimes heard them called) made expressly for streetsale, vary from <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a pair. The <num value="1">1</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> a pair are about <num value="6">six</num> inches by <num value="4">four</num>, very rude, and on thin paper, and with frames made of lath-wood (stained), but put together very compactly. The cheaper sorts are of prints bought at the swag-shops, or of waste-dealers, sometimes roughly coloured, and sometimes plain. The greatest sale is of those charged from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> to <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>
the pair. 
<p>Some of the higher-priced pictures are painted purposely for the streets, but are always copies of some popular engraving, and their sale is not a <num value="20">twentieth</num> of the others. These frame-pictures were, and are, generally got up by a family, the girls taking the management of the paper-work, the boys of the wood. The parents have, many of them, been paper-stainers. This division of labour is <num value="1">one</num> reason of the exceeding cheapness of this street branch of the fine arts. These working artists&mdash;or whatever they are to be called&mdash;also prepare and frame for street-sale the plates given away in the <num value="1">first</num> instance with a number of a newspaper or a periodical, and afterwards &ldquo;to be had for next to nothing.&rdquo; The prevalence of such engravings has tended greatly to diminish the sale of the pictures prepared expressly for the streets. 
<p><num value="10">Ten</num> years ago this trade was <num value="10">ten</num> times greater than it is now. The principal sale still is, and always was, at the street-markets on Saturday evenings. They are sold piled on a small stall, or carried under the arm. To sell <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> worth on a Saturday night is an extraordinary sale, and <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> is a bad <num value="1">one</num>, and the frame-picturer must have &ldquo;middling patter to set them off at all. &lsquo;Twopence a pair!&rsquo; he&lsquo;ll say; &lsquo;only twopence a pair! Who&lsquo;d be without an ornament to his dwelling?&rsquo;&rdquo; 
<p>There are now about <num value="50">fifty</num> persons engaged in this sale on a Saturday night, of whom the majority are the artists or preparers of the pictures. On a Monday evening there are about <num value="20">twenty</num> sellers; and not half that number on other evenings&mdash;but some &ldquo;take a round in the suburbs.&rdquo; 
<p>If these people take <num value="10">10</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> weekly for framepictures the year through, <num value="1040">1,040</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> is yearly expended in this way. I estimate the average number at <num value="20">twenty</num> daily. Their profits are about cent. per cent.; boys and working people buy the most. The trade is often promoted by a raffle at a public-house. Many mechanics, I was told, now frame their own pictures. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.219"><head>Of the Street-Sellers of Manuscript and Other Music.</head>

<p>THIS trade used to be more extensively carried on in the streets than it is at present. The 
<milestone unit=col>
reasons I heard assigned for the decadence were the greater cheapness of musical productions generally, and the present fondness for lithographic embellishments to every polka, waltz, quadrille, ballad, &amp;c., &amp;c. &ldquo;People now hates, I do believe, a <hi rend=italics>bare</hi> music-sheet,&rdquo; <num value="1">one</num> streetseller remarked. 
<p>The street manuscript-music trade was, certainly, and principally, piratical. An air became popular perhaps on a sudden, as it was pointed out to me, in the case, of &ldquo;Jump, Jim Crow.&rdquo; At a musical publisher&lsquo;s, such an affair in the <num value="1">first</num> bloom of its popularity, would have been charged from <num value="2">2</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> to <num value="3">3</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> <num value="6">6</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi>, twentyfive years ago, and the street-seller at that time, often also a book-stall keeper, would employ, or buy of those who offered them for sale, and who copied them for the purpose, a manuscript of the demanded music, which he could sell cheap in comparison. 
<p>A man who, until the charges of which I have before spoken, kept a <num value="2">second</num>-hand bookstall, in a sort of arched passage in the New Cut, Lambeth, sold manuscript-music, and was often &ldquo;sadly bothered,&rdquo; he said, at <num value="1">one</num> time by the musical propensities of a man who looked like a journeyman tailor. This man, whenever he had laid out a trifle at the book-stall, looked over the music, and often pulled a small flute from his pocket, and began to play a few bars from <num value="1">one</num> of the manuscripts, and this he continued doing, to the displeasure of the stallkeeper, until a crowd began to assemble, thinking, perhaps, that the flute-player was a streetmusician; he was then obliged to desist. Of the kind of music he sold, or of its mode of production, this street-bookseller knew nothing. He purchased it of a man who carried it to his stall, and as he found it sell tolerably well, he gave himself no further trouble concerning it. The supplier of the manuscript pencilled on each sheet the price it was to be offered at, allowing the stall-keeper from <num value="50">50</num> to <num value="150">150</num> per cent. profit, if the price marked was obtained. &ldquo;I haven&lsquo;t seen anything of him, sir,&rdquo; said the street-bookseller, &ldquo;for a long while. I dare say he was some poor musicianer, or singer, or a reduced gentleman, perhaps, for he always came after dusk, or else on bad dark days.&rdquo; 
<p>Although but partially connected with streetart, I may mention as a sample of the music sometimes offered in street-sale, that a bookstall keeper, <num value="3">three</num> weeks ago showed me a pile of music which he had purchased from a &ldquo;waste collector,&rdquo; about <num value="8">eight</num> months before, at <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num><hi rend=italics>d.</hi> the pound. Among this was some MS. music, which I specify below, and which the book-stall keeper was confident, on very insufficient grounds, I think, had been done for street-sale. 
<p>The music had, as regards <num value="3">three</num>-fourths of it, evidently been bound, and had been torn from the boards of the book, as only the paper portion is purchased for &ldquo;waste.&rdquo; Some, however, were loose sheets, which had evidently never been subjected to the process of stitching. I <pb id="p.306" n="306"> 
<milestone unit=col>
now cite some of the titles of this street-sale: &ldquo;Le Petit Tambour. Sujet d&lsquo;un Grand Rondeau pour le Piano Forte. Compos&eacute; par L. Zerbini,&rdquo; (MS.) &ldquo;Di Tanti Palpiti. The Celebrated Cavatina, by Rossini, &amp;c.&rdquo; &ldquo;<num value="20">Twenty</num> Short Lessons, or Preludes in the most Convenient Keys for the Harp. Composed and Respectfully Dedicated to Lady Ann Collins. By John Baptist Meyer. Price <num value="5">5</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi>&rdquo; &ldquo;An Cota Caol (given in the ancient Irish character.) The Slender Coat,&rdquo; (MS.) &ldquo;Cailin beog chruite na mbo (also in Irish). The Pretty Girl Milking the Cow,&rdquo; (MS.) 
<milestone unit=col>

<p>There are now no persons regularly employed in preparing MS. music for the streets. But occasionally a person skilled in music writing will, when he or she, I was told, had nothing better in hand, do a little for the street sale, disposing of the MSS. to any street-stationer or bookseller. If <num value="4">four</num> persons are this way employed, receiving <num value="4">4</num><hi rend=italics>s.</hi> a week each, the year through&mdash;which I am assured is the extent&mdash; we find upwards of <num value="40">40</num><hi rend=italics>l.</hi> thus earned, and about twice that sum taken by the street retailers. 
<div2 type=section id="c.15.220"><head>Of the Capital and Income of the Street-Sellers of Stationery, Literature, and the Fine Arts.</head>

<milestone unit=col>

<p>I now proceed to give a summary of the capital, and income of the above classes. I will <num value="1">first</num> however, endeavour to give a summary of the number of individuals belonging to the class. 
<p>This appears to be made up (so far as I am able to ascertain) of the following items:&mdash;<num value="120">120</num> sellers of stationery; <num value="20">20</num> sellers of pocket-books and diaries; <num value="50">50</num> sellers of almanacks and memorandum-books; <num value="12">12</num> sellers of account-books; <num value="31">31</num> card-sellers; <num value="6">6</num> secret papers-sellers; <num value="250">250</num> sellers of songs and ballads; <num value="90">90</num> running patterers; <num value="20">20</num> standing patterers; <num value="8">8</num> sellers of &ldquo;cocks&rdquo; (principally elopements); <num value="15">15</num> selling conundrums, &ldquo;comic exhibitions,&rdquo; &amp;c.; <num value="200">200</num> selling play-bills and books for the play; <num value="40">40</num> back-number-sellers; <num value="4">4</num> waste paper-sellers at Billingsgate; <num value="40">40</num> sellers of tracts and pamphlets; <num value="12">12</num> newsvenders, &amp;c., at steam-boat piers; <num value="2">2</num> book auctioneers; <num value="70">70</num> book-stall keepers and book barrow-men; <num value="16">16</num> sellers of guide-books; <num value="30">30</num> sellers of song-books and children&lsquo;s books; <num value="40">40</num> dealers in pictures in frames; <num value="30">30</num> vendors of engravings in umbrellas, and <num value="4">4</num> sellers of manuscript music&mdash;making altogether a total of <num value="1110">1,110</num>. Many of the above street-trades are, however, only temporary. As, for instance, the street-sale of playing-cards, continues only <num value="14">fourteen</num> days in the year; pocketbooks and diaries, <num value="4">four</num> weeks; others, again, are not regularly pursued from day to day, as the sale of prints and engravings in umbrellas, which affords employment for but <num value="12">twelve</num> weeks out of the <num value="52">fifty-two</num>, and conundrums for <num value="2">two</num> months. <num value="1">One</num> trade, however, (namely, that of &ldquo;Comic Exhibition Papers,&rdquo; gelatine and engraved cards of the Exhibition) is entirely now in the streets. In the broad-sheet trade, again, the &ldquo;running patterers&rdquo; work what are called &ldquo;cocks,&rdquo; when there are no incidents happening to incite the public mind. Hence, making due allowances for such variations, we may fairly assume that the street-sellers belonging to this class number at least <num value="1000">1,000</num>. The following statistics will show the whole amount of capital, and the gross income of this branch of street traffic. 
