<p>&ldquo;I have already hinted at the character and description of the persons by whom these forgeries are framed. It would seem, from the example given, that such documents are available in every sea-port or other considerable town; but this is not the case. It is true that certain kinds of documents, especially sham hawkers&rsquo; licenses, may be had in the provinces, at prices suited to the importance of their contents, or to the probable gains of their circulation; but all the &lsquo;regular bang-up fakes&rsquo; are manufactured in the &lsquo;Start&rsquo; (metropolis), and sent into the country to order, carefully packed up, and free from observation. The following note, sent to &lsquo;Carotty Poll, at Mrs. Finder&lsquo;s Login-ouse facin the orse and trumpet bere shop han street Westminster London with spede,&rsquo; may tend to illuminate the uninitiated as to how such &lsquo;fakements&rsquo; are obtained: 
<p>&lsquo;Dere pol&mdash;I ope this will find yu an george in good helth and spirits&mdash;things is very bad ere, yure sister Lizer has been konfined an got a fine strappin boye, they was very bad off wen it happend. they say in mi country it never ranes but it pores and so it was pol, for mi William as got a month along with Cockny Harry for a glim lurk and they kum out nex Mundie and i av porned my new shift and every indivigual thing to get them a brekfust and a drop a rum the mornin they kums out. They wont hav no paper to work, and I dont know what they will do. Tayler Tom lent me a shillin wish I send inklosed and yu must porn sumthing for anuther shilling and get Joe the Loryer to rite a fake for William not a glim&rsquo; (loss by fire) &lsquo;but a brake say as e ad a hors fell downe with the mad staggurs an broke all is plates and dishes an we are starvin you can sa that the children is got the mesuls&mdash;they av ben ill thats <hi rend=italics>no</hi> lie&mdash;an we want to rase a little munney to git anuther hanimul to dror the kart put a fu monekurs&rsquo; (names) &lsquo;tu it and make it durty and date it sum time bak do not neglect and dont fale to pay the post no more at preasant from yure luvin sister Jane N&mdash;&mdash; at Mister John H&mdash;&mdash; the Sweep&mdash; nex dore to the <num value="5">five</num> Bels grinsted Colchester Essex. good by.&rsquo; 
<p>&ldquo;The person from whom the above letter was obtained, was in the lodging-house when it <pb id="p.313" n="313"> 
<milestone unit=col>
arrived, and had it given him to read and retain for reference. Lawyer Joe was soon sent for; and the following is an outline of the scene that occurred, given in my informant&lsquo;s own words: 
<p>I had called at the house whither the above letter had been addressed, to inquire for a man whom I had known in his and my own better days. The kitchen-door, or rather cellar-door, was thrust open, and in came Carrotty Poll herself. 
<p>&lsquo;Well, Poll,&rsquo; asked the deputy, &lsquo;how does the world use you?&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;B&mdash; bad,&rsquo; was the reply, &lsquo;where&lsquo;s Lawyer Joe?&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Oh, he&lsquo;s just gone to Mother Linstead&lsquo;s for some tea and sugar; here he comes.&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Joe, I&lsquo;ve a job for you. How much do you charge for screeving a &ldquo;brake?&rdquo;&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Oh, half a bull (half-a-crown).&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;No, I&lsquo;ll give you a deuce o&rsquo; deeners (<measure value="2s." type=currency><num value="2">two</num> shillings</measure>), co&lsquo;s don&lsquo;t ye see the poor b&mdash; is in &ldquo;stir&rdquo; (prison).&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Well, well, I shan&lsquo;t stand for a tanner. Have you got paper?&rsquo; 
<p>&lsquo;Yes, and a Queen&lsquo;s head, and all.&rsquo; 
<p>The pen and ink were found, a corner of the table cleared, and operations commenced. 
<p>&lsquo;He writes a good hand,&rsquo; exclaimed <num value="1">one</num>, as the screever wrote the petition. 
<p>&lsquo;I wish I could do it,&rsquo; said another. 
<p>&lsquo;If you could, you&lsquo;d soon be transported,&rsquo; said a <num value="3">third</num>; while the whole kitchen in <num value="1">one</num> chorus, immediately on its completion, proclaimed, that it was d&mdash;d well done, adding to that, not <num value="1">one</num> &lsquo;swell&rsquo; in a score would view it in any other light than a &lsquo;ream&rsquo; (genuine) concern. 
<p>Lawyer Joe was up to his trade&mdash;he folded the paper in official style&mdash;creased it as if it was long written and often examined, attached the signatures of the minister and churchwardens, and dipping his fingers under the fireplace, smeared it with ashes, and made the whole the best representation of a true account of &lsquo;a horse in the mad staggers&rsquo; and &lsquo;a child in the measles&rsquo; that could be desired by the oldest and best cadger on the monkry. 
<p>These professional writers are in possession of many autographs of charitable persons, and as they keep a dozen or more bottles of different shades of ink, and seldom write <num value="2">two</num> documents on exactly the same sort of paper, it is difficult to detect the imposition. A famous lurker who has been previously alluded to in this work, was once taken before a magistrate at York whose <hi rend=italics>own</hi> signature was attached to his fakement. The imitation was excellent, and the &lsquo;lurker&rsquo; swore hard and fast to the worthy justice that he (the justice) <hi rend=italics>did</hi> write it in his own saddle-room, as he was preparing to ride, and gave him <measure value="5s." type=currency><num value="5">five</num> shillings</measure>, too. The effrontery and firmness of the prisoner&lsquo;s statement gained him his discharge! 
<p>It is not uncommon in extensive districts&mdash; say, for instance, a section of a county taking 
<milestone unit=col>
in <num value="10">ten</num> or a dozen townships&mdash;for a school of lurkers to keep a secretary and remit his work and his pay at the same time. In London this functionary is generally paid by commission, and sometimes nartly in food, beer, and tobacco. The following is a fair estimate of the scale of charges: 
